. I don't know the number. But {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Charlotte Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Canning Town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you tell me how long you lived there in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - not long, about five years I suppose. Five or six years, I wouldn't say for sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And then where did you move to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 To 14 New Road, Old Canning Town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Still quite close was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, very close, yes. 14, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Old Canning Town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How long would you be in that house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh I was in that house - I got married in that house, I was there 'til 1937.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, quite a - a good number of years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you know why your parents moved when they moved? Why did they move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - my family was increasing, one after the other, one after the other, and mother - lost her - dad, he died in 1930, April - November the fifth, fireworks night he died, 1930, an
d he - after he was buried mother got - a bit worried about the children you know, running all over the place so she - got a little flat to herself - further up the street. Number - eighteen New Road.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But going back to the time you moved in 1905 when
 you were only five, you don't know why they moved then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. No, I can't remember that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You don't remember anything about that first house where you were born?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No I don't, no. I don't know much about the - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Charlotte Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But - I know quite a lot about 14 New Road though 'cos I was - growing up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You say your father died in 1930, do you know how old he was when he died?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Fifty. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What was his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Pipe fitter, in Broml}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 y Gas Works. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was he ever out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, not - until he become very ill with his chest, bronchitis. He used to - say for instance about November, he'd get attack of bronchitis and asthma and all that and he'd cough, cough, cough and - and it - prevented him from going t
o work for quite a long while. Right up 'til perhaps the following spring before he went back to work, and - he - couldn't stand it no longer, he died in - what - fourteen New Road where we lived, in - in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When he got ill I think you said he became a sort of gatekeeper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes, yes. He - he was so ill after he went back again to work that - the manager, or the managers of the - Bromley Gas Works - they said, well we'll find you a better job lighter one, his job - used to be cleaning - bi
g - pipes led out in the open and - they come from the retort house, where all the thick yellow smoke come from the coal - purifying the coal into coke and gas you see, go through little holes you know, and - fill the gas holders up with gas, and his job 
w
as to keep them pipes clean, with a great big long rod with a broom or a shovel or something on the end of it, and - as he cleaned them so the - more smoke used to come out of them and used to get in his chest, oh and make him cough terrible. Well I could
n't stick it and I was only - a young fellow. I worked there myself. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How long did he keep on at that pipe cleaning job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh he was there quite a number of years on that, I don't know exactly how long. But - I didn't know exactly wha
t he done for a living - until I worked there myself and see him clean these pipes. I said, good Lord dad, church that job up. I said, you can't live like - well that'll kill you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was when you were about twenty or so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, I was twenty-two then. Yes, when I was - worked for Bromley Gas works.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
So it was only just later on that he got this job in the telephone, that gate-keeper's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, he got the gatekeepers job after he'd been so ill so long - in - on and off you know with 
his chest that the - authorities thought they'd better give him a cleaner healthier job. So they made him the gatekeeper. He - his job was to collect the notes as the - lorries come out loaded with coke, and other material, like -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767  t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ar stuff what they used 
to get out the coal - for road mending, lorries of it used to come out of the gas works, and he - collected the notes, at the same time used to sell coke. He had a shed, and a lorry used to come down perhaps once every morning and stack his shed up with c
oke, only in the wintertime of course, and - dad used to sell it. Sixpence a bag. Fourteen pound of coke for sixpence a bag, and he - managed that job all right, until we got the flood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did he give up that job after the flood then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well he - he w
as so ill, that he couldn't stand the - even that job, he hadn't got the strength to lift the sacks of coke up for the people that come for it, so I used to go there - help dad out with sell the coke, and I used to stand in the shed and wait 'til people c
ome to buy the coke and I used to give 'em a bag and - and - take their mon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 y and pop it into dad's box, used to make a note of it like, how many bags he sold during the day, and - he also had the telephone in the box so if - anything went wrong he could te
lephone up to the foreman and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was the last job he had then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was his last job, yes, he never had no other job after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you know what he did before he went to the gas works?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. He was a publican. Not officially a pub
lican, an - a manager of a pub you know. I think it was called the - it was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bidder Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. Oh I can't think of the name of that pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He did that job for quite a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, he had that - well, while he wa
s a young man, until - what happened you see - the mistress - she was - clearing her place up, and they found bugs in the furniture. So she said, oh I don't want this, I'm going to chuck you all out. So she said to my dad, would you like it Robert? They c
a
lled him Robert in the pub, Bob his name was. So - he said, yes, I wouldn't mind it. So it was agreed that dad'd order a pantechnicon van or something to - take the furniture away. Unbeknown to her husband - he also is giving the furniture away, to - unbe
k
nown to his wife I mean - the husband, the publican, he - promised his - brother-in-law I think it was, the same furniture. So - when dad brought his van up to take the furniture away it had already gone. Of course he got - oh, he was quite wild about it,
 
he said, the missus promised me that furniture and the guv'nor said, I didn't know, he said, I give it to - me brother-in-law. So dad says, oh - I'm not standing for that. So he give his notice in. And - there was - they had to accept it I suppose, they c
ouldn't do nothing about that, so from there he went in Bromley Gas Works as a pipe fitter. Yes. That's the only job I can remember him ever having. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That job wasn't a sort of job you needed to be apprenticed for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 To be apprenticed? Oh no, n
o. It was just a labourer's job I think. He wasn't a - a - a chap that fitted pipes together, welded them up and things like that, he was a pipe fitter cleaning pipes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you know where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 My father? He was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
So he must have had some other jobs before he took on the pub presumably, but you don't know what they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh I - I couldn't tell you that, no. I have no memory of that at all. All I know right from a boy - as far back as I can remember, he was working in this - public house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You remember him working in the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Only just slightly. I used to go up and see him. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That would be when you were about five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh, before then, four. Four or five, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 By the time you were ten would you say he had gone into the gas works?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, he went in the gas works long before that. Long before that. Round about 19 - 05 or six, 1905 or six that he come out the pub, and went in Bromley Gas Works. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 About the time you moved house in fact?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I - I haven't got a lot of memory of dad working in a pub. But I do know he - he was - he was a co-partner in the - public house, yes. He had - had so many shares.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In the gas works?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In the gas works, ye
s. Mother drew - when he died mother drew the money out, see I said - I begged her, I said, leave the money in mum, I said, it'll do you a good turn one of these days. No, she said, I want it. So she took it all out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Jus
t a minute, I'll get the book out. Wellington Place - Old Canning Town. That's me father, yes. Me mother was born - you want the year? 1878 dad was born. And mother was born - 1876 in Camberwell, London. Got that? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you know whether she ever had a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Mother? Yes, she used to be a ship's scrubber. Scrubbing the - the - ship's cabins, and the corridors and things like that, and the lounge in - all - all over the ship where they wanted cleaning up she used to go and scrub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was after she'd got the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh before she had her family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, she used to go before she was married, but - she done quite a lot more of it when - after she married. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Any other jobs she had you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Not as I know of. No. It was the only job I knew mother to carry on with, was the ship's scrubber. I think she got sixpence an hour. For scrubbing. They used to pay her every night in case she couldn't come back the next morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She wouldn't do washing for people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes, she's a great - woman for that, she used to - wash and iron and clean up for any lady what - wanted it done, and - I used to turn the wringer for her. Wring - old - old fashioned big roller wringer, you know, and 
she - done the ironing of course for 'em. Then she'd go - baby minding, baby sitting. Then she - she was a - a - assistant to a midwife, she'd go and - bring the baby into the world, yes, if the - if the midwife wasn't there mother used to do it. Yes, she
 was a good woman at that sort of work. Mm. That's the - in her young days of course. As years grew on she had to give it up 'cos she -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your father do any odd jobs like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Pardon? Oh dad never, no, he never had the strength to do any odd 
jobs. No. He was always bad with his chest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How many of you were there altogether in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Eight. Mum and dad was ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you know roughly speaking when they were born, your brothers and sisters?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. I've a record of - in the b
ook. You've got mother's date of birth haven't you? Dad's? The first ones born was - my brother Bob. 17th of May - 1898. Got that? Next was Edie. 5th of September, 19 - 99. 1899. Then me, born in 1900, 23rd of July. There was Louis. 21st of April - 19 - I
 
haven't got that birth date down. 21st of April, 190 - 2. 1902. Then there was Jessie. My sister Jess. 17th of June, 1906. Then there was Rosie. Oh she come before Jessie. Rosie, she was born in - 3rd of March, 19 - she's 65 now, when would that be? Yes. 
S
ixty-five. Sixty-six. 1906. She would be - she was - born - 3rd of March, 1906, yes. Right that's - Rose and Jess - the - then I - had a young brother born - mother had a young - son I mean - Leslie, his birthday is 18th of June, 1912 I believe. Then Geor
ge - brother George, he was born 28th September - 1926. After that comes - what's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's one of your brother's is it, 1926?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Much later than all the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, there was a long time in between George and Rose. George and - J
essie. Jessie was - 17th of June - 1926. '25 or '24 or something, I forget now, and - I thought I had it marked down here but I haven't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's all of them is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Leslie was - Leslie - the youngest. And - Les - 18th of June he was born, yes. See if I can find any more of the birthdays in here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Haven't we got them all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Makes eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Leslie's the last one, he's 1927 you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
George was born in 1926. Leslie was born in 1928. Yes. I know there's a big gap in between - Jess and George, my sister Jessie. Right. That makes eight altogether does it? That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When your mother went out to work who looked after the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh well I used to be head cook and bottle washer. Yes, I used to do a lot of cleaning up and cooki
ng and all that for the children. The other few children there was then, wasn't many. That's how - if - I wasn't available I - I used to go round the City of London quite a lot you know, see what I could find. Pick up different things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were small would somebody look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 My sister Edie. She's the eldest - daughter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You never had one of the neighbours come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. Always look after ourselves. Yes. Yes, my sister Edie was - willing enough, I'd say all right luv, I'm going for a walk. And I'd go up the City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} and see what I could find. Used to pick up all sorts of things up the City of London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you like to tell me one of these stories then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I picked up half a sovereign. In the first place - I could
 - impersonate a taxi call, like a - a commissioner out - outside an hotel, he - he'd blow a whistle. He'd go - know what I mean. And if - I - if I - while I'm walking around the City of London, if I noticed that commissionaire wasn't on the door, and I c
o
uld see somebody waiting for a taxi, who couldn't whistle and who couldn't call out or anything, I used to say taxi sir, or taxi madam? Yes please on. Right. And - bring the taxi over. I used to get a couple of bob, a shilling or whatever it may be. Yes. 
A
nd then - I was doing that one day outside the - hotel, a lady - pulled up in the taxi, so I - rushed and opened the door for her and - oh she said, very nice - for you sonny, she said, very kind of you. Here you are, take this. And she give me a shilling
.
 At the same time she pulled the shilling out, she dropped - a half a sovereign on the ground. Well I - I didn't know what it was dropped - might have been anything, but - when she went in the - hotel - I looked on the ground, Holy Smoke, cor - I picked i
t up, whipped it in me pocket quick, and run. That lady must have a lot of money carrying sovereigns - half - sovereigns about with her. I thought of me mother. That'll do my mother a wonderful good turn that will.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was she pleased then when you got back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was in the Strand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you got home though was she pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh she kissed me all over. Oh a wonderful son. Yes, I give it to her. Yes, she's wonderful. She soon went and spent most of it anyway, food for the children and meself and - dad. Another time I - I'd been touring round the City of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I - getting fed up of walking about so I - see a lorry going my way home, so I jumped on it. It had a tailboard down, you know what I mean, the tailboard? Two chains holding it up. So I 
jumped on the - back of this lorry, and - came very slow. When we got to the Mansion House - policeman put his hand up, there was no traffic lights I don't think them days. And - no there wasn't. The policeman put his hand up to stop the traffic, so he st
o
pped this lorry and - I'm waiting for him to start, I'm looking on the ground, I see sixpence. Cor - off - off I jump quick, picked the sixpence up, by that time the policeman lowered his hand, the lorry started to move. So I run after the lorry as quick 
as I could and - jumped on the back again. And - when we got to Whitechapel, near Aldgate, he went straight on towards {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stratford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Well I had to go down the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - meself, to get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, so I jumped off the lorry, across the road and - st
arted to - run. I - I wouldn't ride. No, I never rode when I found the half sovereign. I run all the way home. That was a distance of about six and a half mile, seven mile. And - when I found the sixpence - from Aldgate to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was five and a half 
mile. I wouldn't ride, I wouldn't spend the money. I just kept running. Then when I got home mother said, cor, bless your heart and soul, she said. Just what I want. So she went out and bought dad a couple of big bloaters. Mm, I think it was bloaters. Yes
 I'm sure it was. He had a - nice feed. She used to buy - she - she used to buy sixpennyworth of pieces. Yes. Meat. Pieces of meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How often would you have meat then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - crikey. Very scarce meat was them days. Once in a blue moon. Unless - I had a bit of luck or - mum had a bit of luck or dad was working -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You wouldn't have some on Sundays usually then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, we'd have a bit of meat on Sundays, that's the only day I think we did have meat, on Sundays. And - mother always made a - a
 lovely big cake - she'd sacrifice other things to buy - to - especially to make this big cake in a big tin - currant cake. Proper old mother's way of making one you know, I used to love that, I used to cut a big slice off. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you tell me about 
the sort of food you had on an ordinary day, what would you have for breakfast, would you have any breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Very seldom I had breakfast. Unless I - found the bread to toast or something like that. Then ten to one there wouldn't be no butter to 
put on it. But - if I had a penny in me pocket - I used to go down to a shop called - Pea soup - pea soup shop, called - Caldori's, Mr Caldori was the - owner of it and he used to - make this pea soup specially for the kids. For the little boys and girls.
 
I'd go down there, I'd get a big basin, half as big as that thing - he had the basins, stacks of them. He used to say, what do you want son? Penn'orth of pea soup Mr Caldori please. Right. A big ladle. Fill the saucepan up - fill the bowl up I mean, and h
e'd say - want any bread with it son? I'd say, yes please. Give me a big slice of bread, thick. Yes, and I used to enjoy that. Then I'd come home - or I might go straight to school or might come home and say I've had me dinner mum. If she was in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What did you say you paid him for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A penny. Mm. Penny - penny a bowl of pea soup.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you wouldn't get a cooked dinner at home ever then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your father stay at work for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh, if dad was working, yes, we 
could - manage to have a - a dinner at home. There was - there was no free dinners at school them days like there is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If your dad was working would you then have a dinner at home usually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, we'd have a - snack of some sort then. Probably 
be a bit of corned beef. And a - or spam. Or cheese and onions. It wouldn't be a - very lavish meal you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Tea? Well we had bread and jam. Yes. Bit of cake. Bit of cake.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your mum's cake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you ever have any fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Prunes. Prunes. Bananas. Yes, we used to have a - a banana each - some nights, spread on our bread - to - make a sandwich of it. Yes. Well sometimes mum was lucky enough to get us bananas out the docks. Yes. And when the banana}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767  ships used to come in - they f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
row all the nice ripe ones in a barge, and all the green ones is - deliver. But - mum used to go along the barge and - drop a few bananas in her bag and - good, nice to eat. Good bananas, only just that a bit over ripe you know
. Not always, occasionally she used to do it. I learned that trick meself, when I worked in the docks. Yes, I worked quite a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 long while}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  in the dock. I used to find a banana barge and - stuff me pockets up with 'em. Fetch 'em home. Of course if I had a nice
 big bag on the back of me bike I'd fill the bag up. I - although I - it wasn't allowed - to take 'em - police never used to say nothing. He was a copper - copper on the gate, as you went to go out he'd say, what have you got in your bag son? That's the o
ld torch guv'mpor and a couple of bananas. All right, away you go.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Could you get anything else like that from the docks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - yes, I suppose you could if you was a thief. You had to be a good thief though because of the police. They - very cleve
r them policemen. They seemed to know - just look at you they know you've got something. Yes. Yes, very clever them policemen. Though I - always kept me fingers clean. Bar the bananas, well I was allowed to have them really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They used to allow people 
- the coopers used to give people a drink didn't they? Perhaps that wasn't your part of the docks, I've been told about that, having a tap from a cask. Do you know about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Oh - oh I've got you. I've got you, yes. Yes. Oh one day, the - the sh
ip come in, and it - the - the top hold, there used to be three holds - dockies started work on her - they - uncovered the hatch and I noticed there was - great big barrels of wine. Some sort of wine, don't know what it was - I found out afterwards what i
t
 was. And - of course the first thing they do the dockies, they have a drink. They got their hooks, what they - pull the cargo about with, and they - give it a - tap with the - bung, where the bung is, and out flows the wine. Well I - I was a crane driver
 
at the time, working for Harland and Wolfe ship repair workers, and - I'm looking down the hold and - one of the dockies hollers up to me - they used to call me Darkie - Darkie, get us a bottle of water or a bucketful if you can. If you can find a bucket.
 
All right. So I used to go down the - galley, say to the - cook, I knew 'em all well. Have you got a bucket I can get some clean water in, lend me, I'll fetch it back. Yes. That's quite all right. If you aint got a bucket a big - bowl will do or a big sau
c
epan. Have a bucket. All right, I'll have a bucket. So I says - go to the water - clean water tap, fresh water tap - fill the - bucket up, get a bit of string, and lower it down the hole for the docky. All right chum? Yes. Yes. Thanks. See you later. Righ
t
-o. Well of course - I hadn't a clue what was in the - barrels. So - I had to go up in the crane - to do my work after the docky had finished his - job - from twelve to one, see, dinner hour. And then I used to go up the crane again after the docky finish
e
d in the evening, six 'til - nine o'clock at night, do my working. Well - I went back down the hole in - during the afternoon. I didn't go down the hold, I just went to have a look see how they were getting on. So - this same docky I spoke to first he sai
d
 - got any bottles Darkie? I said, bottles, no, I'm afraid I aint got no bottles. He said, you'll find some on the quay. On the quay they used to stack all the empties up. So I said, right-o. So - I went on the quay and I got a couple of bottles, put 'em 
i
n me pocket. Empty ones. Poured a little drop of water in and give 'em a shake, washed them bottles out, and - he filled one of these bottles up with this wine, and he caught it up with a bit of wood and - catch. Right. He threw it up to me. Of course it 
- it - it's leaked a bit and splashed down me shirt. Cor }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 strew}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
, I said, it's rough. Oh. So I done more, I knew I'd get - oh - well court }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 martial led}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  if the policeman - smelt run on me. So I nipped down the engine room with it quick and I give it to the char
gehand fitter. He said, what have you got there? I said, well I don't know what it is I said, it smells like rum. I said, you can have it if you want it. Where did you get it? I said, dockey just give it to me out the hold. I said, he wanted a bucket of w
a
ter and so he give me a - drop of rum in the place, kindness like. Blimey. Anyway he said - did the dockey say what - what country it come from? I said, no. Aint got a clue. He said well - if you get a chance you ask the dockey what country it come from a
n
d - what proof - it has. I said, what proof? I said I don't follow you. He said - percentage of it you know. I said, oh I know - all right, I said, I'll ask him. So on the quiet I see this dockey, I said - I had to give that bottle away I said. I couldn't
 drink that. So he said, oh, who did you give it to? I said, chargehand fitter. Ah, that's all right, he said. He'll know what to do with it. Well, apparently the chargehand fitter - \{BLANK\}
 So of course the old chargehand fitter, he had what they call some
 distilled water in a big glass container, for a special reason, down the engine room and - he mixed some of that with this rum, so he - when he see me again he said - want a drop of your drink Jim? I said, I don't mind. So he give me a cup - half a cupfu
l
. Cor - what is it? He says, it's your drink what you brought me down. Oh, I said, a lot too strong. I said, I see the dockey and he said it's seventy five per cent over proof. Did he? Had a drop more water in it then. You see it come from - Buma - Bumada
 - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bermuda{\*\xmlclose}, somewhere like that. What would you like me to talk about?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you tell me what the house was like, the one you were in a long time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}14 New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes. It - actually it was a shop. Although we never sold anything in it. And it - I
 don't believe the person who lived in it before us ever sold anything in it, but - it was all boarded up, the windows, had small windows like - half as big as that, see the shop windows, so - and there was all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ongued and grooved boards - where the big wi
ndow would be to see the display of what the shop was selling, but - it was always boarded up. I'm sure that the shop never sold anything. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How many rooms did you have there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 One, two, three, four, five. Five rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How many of those were bedrooms? Three bedrooms was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Two bedrooms. Scullery. Two box rooms. Two boxrooms. Well, storage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't sleep in the boxrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I did. Yes. Yes. I used to sleep - when I was single. When I got married I used the other - big room, store room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were children, how did you sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
In - in the - well, matter of fact we all slept together - more or less. Me and me sisters and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In one great big bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. We had a whopping great big bed, we sleep to
p and bottom. Yes. I'd be at the bottom, me sister'd be at the top, and me brothers. Only one brother then Bob. Yes. But - of course 'til we got older and then mother - managed to supply us with other beds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 During the day the room you used was the scullery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Cooking in the scullery, gas stove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And you'd eat in there and sit in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, we had a kitchen. We had a sitting room like, yes, we had a kitchen - to have our meals in. Had a big - range - old fashioned range - fire, called a ra
nger. Had plates on top, used to sweep the plates off and put the saucepan on. 'Cos mother always - when she bought her sixpenn'orth of pieces, washed 'em, cleaned 'em up, and the pot herbs - I used to get from under the stalls, well that's another story.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 From the market you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. She'd make a - a nice big stew. With pot herbs. Potatoes, greens onions - all sorts of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you tell me the story about picking them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, I will, yes. And of course she made a big stew an
d we used to - enjoy it, lovely, sixpenn'orth of pieces, it was surprising the amount of meat there was - sixpenn'orth of pieces. All sorts of meat. But - of course it's really stealing, but - the shopkeeper or the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 stall minder}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , he never used to take no no
tice of me - or any other boy come to that. When I used to go - I'd take me bag with me and I used to go down the Marsh - sometimes used to go with me dad. He had a dog named Tiger. A wonderful dog. Dad'd go up to a - stall with the meat on and all that a
nd - them days it used to be all open, you could pick up - a lump of meat and put it down again and nobody'd say anything. It's different today, you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 daren\rquote 
t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  look at it. Anyway you touch that meat and - pick it up and look at it and say I don't want it. I'll
 try somewhere else. He'd say to the dog, go and get it. And the dog used to go and wipe the meat up, what he touched. He said, don't follow me, go home with it. And the dog would run all the way home. Marvellous dog. At the same time - the - greengrocery
 
man - was selling potatoes and greens and - brussel sprouts, onions and things like that - lettuces and what have you, he'd get his scales, shovel and screw up see a - perhaps dad'd go there and say, two pounds of potatoes please, or - I don't say me fath
e
r would, he would never have that much money but - any customer come up, two pounds of potatoes please, I'd be bobbing at the back of his stall, used to have a canvas - back you know so you could - keep it - so the wind wouldn't blow - disturb them. So as
 
he shovelled the potatoes up used to knock a few off on the ground. Well then they'd roll under the - stall, down the kerb and roll more or less to the back of the stall. And when I see that happen I used to get under there and - come here, drop it in me 
b
ag. And I used to pick up quite a few. All sorts of things, onions, carrots, parsnips, and - get a good stock in. When I thought I'd got enough, not only the one stall, I'd go to all of - 'cos used to be quite a lot of stalls selling all the same sort - s
ort of things. It was a place called the Marsh, in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}East India Dock Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. No, - it was called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Victoria Dock Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Victoria Dock Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 it was called. It followed the railway from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to Woolwich, and - oh it was quite a long way, about a mile of sta
lls, used to sell all sorts of things, and shops see. But of course when I thought I'd got enough vegetables to last mum for two or three days, take 'em home. And nobody say anything to me, I never got stopped or anything like that, and - oh I done that q
uite a long while. Until times got better of course. But I was doing it out - up to 1914/18 when the war broke out. Still finding - enough food to feed the family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't have a garden to grow any vegetables in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well dad had allotment. But h
e never had strength to dig it up, he was so ill with his chest, see. Sometimes I'd go over there and help him to dig it up, and grow a few things. But of course - when dad died in 1930 - I took the ground over, being as I worked for the Bromley Gas Works
 
previous to that, and I asked the manager if I could take over dad's garden, he said, yes, certainly, look after it. I said, I'll look after it, said, I'll keep it clean and that. And I did. And I used to grow quite a lot of stuff on the - ten rod of grou
nd it was. And I become - I had a - certificate like that, certificate - certificate of - merit - for the best - garden - on the - on the gas works.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But as a boy you didn't do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No. No. Very seldom, I never had time, I was always up at t
he City, or - down the Marsh, scooping up - yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No fruit trees?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No, nothing like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you keep any hens or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. I did in me married life, I - I kept a couple or rabbits and - two or three - hens and a cock - chicken and all that, used to keep 'em specially to kill for Christmas. Have a good feed Christmas time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 As a boy there was nothing like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. No. Never - never had anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was there a yard at the back of the house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Very short yard, very small. Well say about fourteen - say eighteen foot long the most. Very small garden. A little shed up in the corner of the - where we used to keep a couple of chickens, two hens and a cock, something like that. And rabbits
 hutches to put the rabbits in and keep the rabbits going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Downstairs in this house there was a scullery and a kitchen, was there another room that you used downstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 To get into the house you had to go through the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was all boarded up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was all boarded up, that was a big room, very big room, big as this.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you couldn't use it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh you use it as a sitting room or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But it was dark wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, it wasn't very bright, we used to
 have the lamp - candle - gas lamp burning Half as big as them the windows at the top of the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you use that room much at all then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, unless we had a - jollification, party or some sort. Perhaps a christening or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You had the best furniture in there then did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, more or less, we kept our best furniture in - in the shop. Then half the shop used to go into the kitchen, where the dining room, sitting room, whatever you call it, used to have our food. We had 
a big range fire there. And then you go from there - down a couple of steps, into the scullery. Where you do the cooking, most of the cooking. The toilet was outside, had to go out the - back, out the garden to get to the toilet. Upstairs there was - fron
t
 room was mum - mum and dad's room. You come down them steps and go up another lot of steps, on the side of that, used to go up - round - to another little room, what they call a boxroom - come down from there - go into the - scullery as I call it, there'
s
 another lot of steps - stairs, go up them stairs, that's where I used to sleep - more or less. When I got married I lived up in that room. Made that me permanent headquarters. And that was the - big storeroom I suppose that was for the stores, 'cos - the
 stairs was so narrow - the - your shoulders used to touch the sides you know. And - had no banisters to help you up the stair, so I fixed up a - a long - lump of rope, to pull myself up. That's all there was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was the house rented then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Used to be fourteen shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you remember the landlord at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well we had so many different landlords you see. Yes. Yes. Used to sell it. Sell the property. Everytime they sold it it'd go up a shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But would they look after the roof if it was leaking, would they mend it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, they'd do - and - and do any - serious repairs like - the roof leaking or anything like that or - windows get smashed through }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 hooligans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  or - used to come and put a new window in but - more o
r less you had to do it yourself. Do everything yourself. I used to, I used to - paper and hang - a Mr Pembow, he was a - a Jewish looking fellow. But not a bad chap though, he - he used to leave the rent if we hadn't got it and he'd say, all right, don't
 
forget to pay next week, but - wouldn't - wouldn't let you run too long. You had to pay it. He was very strict on his rent though really, but - wasn't a bad old fellow. Of course then as - as - time went on so he'd sell it to somebody else, somebody else'
d buy it, up'd go the rent again. Another shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you ever have any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 lodgers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  or other relations living in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well, years ago when I was a boy mother had a - her sister's husband in as a lodger, he used to sleep in the boxroom.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But not her sister you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 My mother's sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She was there too, the sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. She died. Yes. And - and mother took her husband in as a lodger. He used to work in the docks. Yes. He was - not for the - Dock Corporation, he was a - a -
 chargehand over the - every gang what done all the heavy machinery on board the ships engine room. Down the engine room he used to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would he eat with you then as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Well of a night time, he had his dinner - out, too far for him to 
walk to our place - for dinner. Same as meself, I never used to come home much to dinner unless I had something quick - like a - good old pushbike or - motorbike or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When she did take him in then, how old would you be then do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I should say I was about - thirteen, fourteen years of age, when mother took Uncle Dick in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 About the time the war broke out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That must have made you all a bit better off then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well it made mother a little b
it better off - getting his - I don't know what he used to give her, I never asked. It made her - a little more comfortable, and - I also had a - a lodger - I brought in myself. 'Cos used to do a lot of hop picking them days, me and mother, yes, go hop pi
cking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Always hop - hop picking right from birth, more or less and - one year we goes down - I was married then, living in 14 New road and I went to - Goudhurst to pick hops with mother, and my wife, she come with me and
 I palled up with a fellow what worked there. He was a - rather educated sort of chappie, spoke - quite - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 educational}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  - educat - lingo you know, wasn't like me. His name was Jack Fraser, Mr Frazer. Jack Cameron Frazer his proper name. So he was telling me 
one night, sitting round the - faggot fire - burnt wood up, called 'em faggots, he said - you know I'd like to come to London Jim. I said, you would, I said, well - I said, nothing stopping you. I said, I'll see me mother. And mother used to hire the lorr
y
 to bring us and take us home again, with our boxes and bags and things. So - I spoke to mother about it. She said, well where's he going to live? I said, I don't know, I thought perhaps - put him up in - Uncle Dick's place. My Uncle Dick had left, he'd g
o
ne - he'd got married again. My mother's - sister's husband. So - it was agreed that Jack, Mr Frazer, Jack - would come with - home with me, and I fixed him up in my boxroom. At that time I was out of work. That was around about 1923 or - 1923. And I was 
o
ut of work, and - I'd been working on Bromley Gas Works for - a little while, and they stood me off redundant, so I had to find another job, so in between that I went hop picking, and when I come back with Jack Frazer I said to him - any good at timber? S
o
 he said, what sort of timber? I said, all sorts of timber. Big timber, little timber, logs. Well, he said, I've knocked about a bit, he said, I - think I could handle that. I said, right, well let's go up and see - one of the Howard's managers - Howards 
Timber Yards, right on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 corner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 of Canning Town Station, Howards Timber Yard. And - I spoke to the manager, and I said, my friend - like to have a job here if possible. And he looked old Jack up, he was big - great big hefty fellow he was, very powerful. 
He said - yes, he said, I'll find him - find him a - job. So, of course he - Jack, he said, what about him? He said, oh he aint man enough - he don't look man enough, too small. He says, he's strong as me. So the manager said, oh - he don't look it. He sa
id, well he is. Equally as strong as me. Well, he said, I'll take you both on. So we both got a job there. And by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 gawk}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  I knew it and all, I had to carry - cut logs on me back. I had a big lump on me back as - like a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767 
\endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  egg}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid409903\charrsid9644767  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 cup. Cor. Anyway, Jack was more har
d, he - he got over it quite quickly. But I didn't, took me a long while. Well I got on so well with that department of Howards Timber Yard they sent me over - - that was called the hardwood department - they sent me over the side of Canning Town Bridge -
 
one side's Canning Town, the other side's Poplar - to work in the softwood department. So of course I was - getting a couple of bob more - in me wages and I was - a lot better off, didn't have to work so hard, carrying cut logs. Getting soft timber is - a
 
lot lighter. So they sort of made me - chargehand. I was in charge of a alley. In Howards, Poplar, there's number one, two, three, four, five and six alleys where all the timber was piled. You walked down the alley to - select what timber you wanted. And 
- or the buyers did, not me. And they made me in charge of number three, so I used to - get the barges unloaded, make sure they was - unloaded in time to save }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 
demurrage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , and - get the - pile up, make a nice neat pile of all the timber. And my job was to go 
down in the barge, fling the sets what the boys in the barge was making up, and I'd sling the sets and - come up the ladder onto the quay, walk down number three alleyway with a pitcher in my hand, long pole like they - shift barges with, pitch her, and g
u
ide this set to the chap what was piling the timber away, see. And I used to do that all day long. Except for times when - a lorry would - want - loading up for - somebody had bought of - some of the - standard of timber out of my - alley, number three al
l
ey, and it was - I had to stop unloading the barge and load this lorry up. That of course caused a bit of a scream that did. You see. When are you bloody well coming down to unload us? Take our sets out of the barge? See. So, plenty of time, don't worry. 
A
s long as you get that barge done by tomorrow night that's all I'm concerned about. Yes. So of course - I - I lasted there 'til 1937. I was there about 1922, '23, something like that. 1924 I went over to soft - softwoods department from the hardwoods to s
o
ftwoods. Used to have visits from the boss, Mr Howard and his son. Two sons he had. David and - James. And the old man himself, oh oh - very strict old boy he was. They used to come down my alley and say - you know, I like the way your timber's stacked. O
h
 thank you sir, thank you very much indeed. Oh, very neat indeed. Huh, never give us any extra. Well from 1937 - I was out of work again. And - my sister Jessie's husband - Jimmy Glenny his name is - he was a - steel erector, and he said to me one day he 
s
aid, can you climb? Can I - climb a tree. Of course I can. He said, well the long and short he said I can take you - get you a job with me. He said, you know what you've got to do don't you? I said, no, what have I got to do? He said, climb up them staunc
h
eons, he said, and - hands and knee he said, and walk along the - four inch piece of steel girder. Well, I says, bit of cake. All right. As long as you're sure about it. I said, yes, I'm sure. Well I goes - works with him. I was like a fly. I'm jumping al
l
 over the place. He said, you'll fall and break your neck. I said, ah, don't worry I won't fall. Anyway - that lasted - oh, quite a long while. Then the - 1939 the war broke out. And - previous to that I joined the ARP. I was living at Rainham then. I mov
ed from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}14 New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, went to live at Rainham, be in the fresh air. And when I got to Rainham I joined the ARP. Go in gas chambers and smelt different gasses and - things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you did that steel thing then you went into the Army did you after that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I went in the Army in 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But in the second world war did you go in the Army again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, I worked all through the war. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What other jobs have you had since the steel erecting one then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - when the steel - I was going to tell you, when - when I finished up steel fighting - steel erecting - I - it was - oh fierce winter we had that year, 1938, just before the war broke out. And - we had a bogey burning with all b
its of wood in it and I was standing round this bogey warming me hands 'cos they was frozen, I couldn't hold a spanner. Couldn't hold me spanner to tighten the nuts up with, and the foreman come along. Walking foreman, used to go around to all the differe
n
t sites and see how the men were getting on. He said to me, what are you doing standing there? So I said, I'm just warming me hands, I said, I can't hold me spanner it's so cold. Get up there, he said, and fix that girder. I said, you be me, you try it. I
 
said, not only sit down, I said, I can't stand up. I had to sit down to bolt the nuts up there. He said, don't you talk to me like that. I said, look guv'nor. I said - you can't bully me, I said, I - I'm a bit too tough for that. I said, if you want that 
-
 beam fixed, I said, you bloody well go up and fix it yourself. How dare you. I said, I dare you anything, I said, you're nothing but a blooming bully, that's all you are. So with that he said, go to the office. I said, right I'll go to the office, I got 
t
he sack. He give me a letter to take to - the - Head office of the - Redpath and Brown, that was the name of the firm I worked for, Redpath and Brown and I took the letter to them and they said, oh, here's your money, here's your cards. Didn't ask me why 
I
 got the sack, they just paid me out. Well then I was out of work again - 'til - the beginning of - just after war broke out in 1939 and a neighbour on the opposite side of the road to me, he was a chargehand working for what do they call it - hm - ship r
e
pair workers, Harland and Wolfe, see. And - he said, would I like to go and work with him, I said, yes, I'd work anywhere, as long as the money's good. So he says, all right. Come with me tomorrow morning he said and I'll get you fixed up. So I had to go 
a
nd see the - foreman and he - he asked me various questions, could I climb? I said, yes, climb, yes, just finished a job iron fighting. Just the boy we want. Iron fighter. Climb anywhere. So then I got the job. And I was with them right 'til - 1943, when 
-
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What exactly did you do for them, were you a crane driver there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, not then I was a fitter's mate. Yes, fitter's mate, and - also working with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 my pal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  who got me the job, down the engine room, what they call the heavy gang. Heavy gang. Pullin
g the engine away. Pulling parts of the engine away and - getting them up on the deck. There was another chap up in the crane then. Well this fellow what was doing our job - doing our work, up in the crane - he wanted to go in the docks as a dock crane dr
i
ver. So he picked on me, would I like to take his job over. I said, yes. Oh yes, I don't mind that. See? So I - he took me up in the crane occasionally and learnt me how to drive. And I picked it up very quick, and - I went and see the foreman, I said - J
i
mmy Wilman, our crane driver, I said, is leaving us. He's going into the docks. He says, so I've heard. I said, can I have his job? Yes, if you can drive a crane. I said, I can. Have you passed your test? I said, no, not yet. So he just wrote me out a let
t
er, go to the PLA and the PLA authorities put me onto a - a tester and he took me up in the crane and said - see that drum there? Yes. Pick it up. I can't pick it up meself. Make out you're going to pick it up. All right. So of course I - moved me crane a
nd - got over the top of the drum and - roughed it up. He said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 swing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  it round, so I swung it round. Where shall I drop it? Down - down there. So I dropped it down there and everything was perfect see. Oh you'll do, he said, you'll pass. Yes. So I passed ou
t as a - crane driver. And I was the only one - for the engineers department, there was another crane driver for boilermakers and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 ship rights}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , and a - I had plenty of, work to do I tell you up in that - them cranes, looking after the - not only one ship, I
 had to pop off to another ship and drive for them and so on. Well - that job lasted me right 'til 19 - 54k 64, sorry '64. That job lasted me right twenty-four years I had driving cranes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Then you retired did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Pardon? Yes, I had to retire. 
You see, what happened, I wouldn't have retired so quick but - not at sixty-four, but - I was coming home after doing a - very tricky job with derricks, you know, the ships derricks, masts - I had to take a very big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 derrick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  down, it weighed about - four to
n, with a three ton crane. Crane only picked up three ton. Stretch it a little bit it might pick up three ten but - I - I managed to get this - great long jumbo }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 
derrick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  - off the ship and lay it on the quay - ready for the lorry to take it away next mornin
g. Well I finished me job, everybody was happy and pleased. I'm going home on me pushbike. When I gets as far as - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}East India Dock Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I had to - before I reached {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I had to turn left. By the way, I'm living in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Custom{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}House{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - Wes
t Ham at this time this happened. I've moved from Rainham I'm living at West Ham. So I could be nearer to me docks, lot nearer. Well I'm turning to me right and there's - to get into Hooker Road, the name of the turning I lived in, when a car - coming fro
m
 a - like the other direction and was turning where I had to turn into, he come straight onto me. Know what I mean? And knocked me from here to - oh - about - ten yards, up against the iron railings. It - it was a recreation ground for the kids. And it sh
o
ved me right through these railings. It cut all me head open - hurt me ribs, hurt me legs, two legs. They had to put me in hospital, the ambulance. I woke just as the doctor was stitching me head up. He said, go to sleep again, and I did. He give me a dos
e
 of smelling salts. Anyway - that put me out of action for - several weeks, and - I had to go on the sick list then, get money. Sign on the Labour Exchange, and - I never got no better. I had to go and see various doctors in the hospital, out patient, and
 
he said - where are you working? I said, I aint working nowhere, I said. I said, to tell you the truth doctor, I said, I'm scared stiff to get a job. Scared, what about? I said, I don't know, I said, I just don't feel like I can - tackle any job now. I sa
i
d, as regards to me own work, I said, I - I don't think I could go in a crane. He said, I know you can't. He said, you be advised by me you won't try it neither. He said, don't you dare try and climb that crane. I said, no sir, I won't. So he wrote me out
 
a letter to take to my firm. What was in the letter I aint got a clue, but they said - right - here's your cards. They give me me insurance cards. So I says, what's this mean, I'm sacked? He said, yes. Can't - they said we - we want a - a fit man, not a h
alf dead man. Oh I said, you've got a cheek. Anyway - yes, that was the last job I had, I haven't done a - days work since. No. I - I can't. I've got no wind. Knocked the wind out of me, that car accident. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Going back to when you were a boy, your m
other didn't ever pay anyone to help her in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. That was - oh that was out of the question. No. If - what I couldn't do or me sister couldn't do - or mother couldn't do herself, well it just had to be left and so we - one of us always - got cracking and - cleaned the house up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did you have sort of fixed jobs, you and your sister in the house? Did you say, I'll do the cleaning and she'll do the cooking or did you just do ..\'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh just mucked in together you know, if - she - she m
ight say to me - clean up the scullery or clean up the kitchen Jim, I - I'm going to pop out and get something for dinner, or something like that you know, and I'd say, all right luv, and - I'd get on with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you do some cooking if you had to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, I'd do the cooking. That's another story, I was a cook in the Army. Mm. They made me a cook. Yes. Yes - when I got - I served in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 for three years you see.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9644767  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Oh yes, she - she used to - help me quite a lot, well I used to help her real
ly 'cos she was older than me. She's two years older than me, my sister. That's her up there. Right across there, look, see her? I'm dancing with her at - Walton on the Naze - holiday camp. Yes. That's my wife in the centre. And up top is me mother. And t
hat young lady there is my daughter. She's my oldest daughter, Nellie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your father do anything to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Poor old chap, no, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 raid not. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He wouldn't ever clean up or help clean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Cook or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He - h
e used to try and mend the boots. Yes. 'Cos them days you couldn't afford to send them - to the snobs. Boot repairs, shoes and that. He used to try and mend them himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were you barefooted quite a lot of the time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, I - I was - I we
nt to school - no boots on. And - oh it was second nature to me to go to school with no boots on, I didn't take no notice of stones in the road or anything like that, just tread on them and never hurt me. Until one day this schoolmaster called us out in t
he big hall, school hall, and he said - when we go home ask our mothers and fathers - mother or father what size boots we take, or shoes' if preferable - as there was going issues - all those boys with no boots and shoes were going to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 issued}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  with boots a
nd shoes from the Raggedy School Union. It was some big society what looked after the welfare of the kids you know, they called it Raggedy School Union. So I got home and asked me mother what size I take, she said, fives I think. I said, all right. So - I
 
went back to school and told the teacher and a few days later I got me pair of boots. Well the first pair of boots I remember - mother was very poor, she hadn't go nothing at all so I said - where's them boots mum? And she got the boots out. They looked n
ew, I give 'em a polish up and made 'em look a bit better, and inside the tag here there used to be WHB, West Ham - WHC, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 West}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  Ham Corporation. So I got a - bit of - drop of petrol I think it was I got - something - kept rubbing and rubbing and rubbing 'til 
you couldn't see that WHC, see. Said what are you doing that - for? I said, you take 'em up the pawn shop mum. So mum took 'em up the pawnshop.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you used to use the pawnshop then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh quite a lot, yes. Yes. Oh if we had anything - like bedclo
thes for instance in the summertime, not in the winter so much, but in the summertime - mum used to give 'em a good washing and ironing and - pawn pem up the pawnshop for a few bob. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would she take some of the clothes up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Parcel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would s
he take some clothes up, some families I think used to keep their clothes, they'd have their best clothes in the pawnshop and take them out on Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, just for a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would they do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your mother did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Y
es. Yes. Oh she'd get 'em out again, she'd get the clothes again. The same as - if dad was lucky enough to have a nice suit - he'd - let mum pawn that. If it - might be a secondhand suit, but she'd posh it up a bit and make it - worth a few bob. I got a w
a
tch - somewhere - belonged to my father. That watch has been out - in and out of pawnshops - wonder where I've done with that, might be in that drawer there, it's been out of pawnshops time after time. It was in the pawnshop when I thought of it one day a
n
d I said to my old - I was working - beginning of last war - 1940 - I said to my mother, what did you do with dad's watch mum? She said - oh she said - I think it's in the pawnshop. Right. I said, can I get it out? If I get it out can I have it? She said,
 yes, certainly you can son, you can have it. And I got it out and I've still got that watch. It's - I think it's in that drawer. A - double backed watch. I'll look for it in a minute.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of clothes did you have as a boy, did you have new cloth
es or second hand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh any old thing we could buy, jumble sales chiefly, used to go to jumble sales and buy up any old clothes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would your mother mend those then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Pardon? Yes, she'd patch 'em up - if they wanted patching and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But she didn't make clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Even - even - she'd cut a man's suit up - to fit me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So she made clothes for you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - cut them down to size you know. Cut them down to size you know. I never forget when I was a boy - we used to 
go to Sunday school regular every Sunday. And we used to go there for one purpose only, that was to get sweets off the parson. And - I used to go there - also to pray, because I - I was serious, very serious when I prayed. And - previous to going to churc
h
 on the Sunday morning I'd been playing out in the street with the other boys and some of 'em got a bit rough and - pushed me over. And as I fell with me legs sprawled out like that I ripped me trousers right up, little knickers you know. Oh crikey. That 
-
 mum hadn't had time - hadn't got time to stitch 'em up she said. I'll put this on. So she put me - a frock and a pinafore. She said don't miss your Sunday school whatever you do. I said, all right mum. So away I go to Sunday school in - dressed like a gi
r
l. 'Course - as we come out of Sunday school, I got me sweets all right in - little packet, screwed up bag, and some of the boys recognized, said, ah there's Jimmy - dressed like a girl. Of course I was a daredevil bugger, I could fight 'em. They took the
 
mickey out of me to - I wouldn't take - well - one - one word and a blow with me in them days. And - they ripped the clothes of me. Yes, I only had a pair of - short - white - knickers on. I run all the way home. There was too many - too many, I couldn't 
f
ight the lot of them. Too many boys all laughing their heads off. And as I got home and I said to mum, oh the boys has - pulled the clothes off me mum. What boys? I said, oh I don't know who they were, I wouldn't give 'em away of course. And - anyway she 
- by that time she had me trousers mended and I - put them on again. Never no more would I go to school - to church dressed like a girl. Yes. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So your father would help by mending the boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about making fires, would he ever do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh he'd light a fire. Yes, he'd light the fire, yes. He'd find the wood and coke, light a fire. As a matter of fact he used to bring wood home from the gas works. Yes. Some - somebody would give it to dad and he'd fetch it home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about doing a bit of painting, painting the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
The what? Ah no, I'm afraid he couldn't do that. Painting was against - oh, get on his nest. Yes. He couldn't do no painting. Poor old chap couldn't do a lot at all for the home. He was always to
o ill, he was always laying in bed with asthma and bronchitis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If your mother was out would he ever look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I looked after him. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did he tell you stories ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of stories would he tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well he'd tell me when he was a young man he used to box. Yes. Bare fisted. Bare fist fighting. On the Mem - Memorial Grounds at West Ham. I don't know if you know - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}East
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Cemetery{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Do you? Going towards West Ham - underground railway station 
- I think it's all built on now, but there used to be a - oh about ten acres of ground, and they - used to play football, West Ham - football - players used to play on there, before they come - a top - a first division - before they become - anywhere in t
h
e divisions, first, second or third or fourth, anyway - I used to go over there and watch 'em play football, West Ham, on the Memorial Grounds. Well - looking - looking back over the grounds - on the pathway that led from the - side of the road, there use
d
 to be a little path, there used to be all sorts of - men get there, gamblers. They used to have - umbrella, find the lady. Know what I mean? And three card trick they call it, Find the Lady. They used to have a penny or ha'penny go and like that. Never f
o
und the lady. Then there'd be - dice. Then there'd be - all sorts of games, I can't think of them now. Anyway there was all gambling, while the footballers were playing football. And West Ham - they they got quite good and they - joined up with the league
 then, that was round about 19 - 08, nine, ten, something like that. And - of course I used to follow West Ham, I used to go where - always go West Ham watching football if I - could afford the entrance fee. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So your father told you the stories about the boxing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, he used to be a - well, as I was going to say, this ten rod of ground - ten acre of ground, they used to - put a stone here, a stone there, a stone there a stone there and make a ring, or fold coats up, take their coats off an
d fold them, that was a square ring - round ring. And - he'd - have - fifteen rounds, twenty rounds, as much as twenty-five rounds, bare fish fighting. With somebody, I don't know who he was. He used to tell me these stories, 'cos - I used to say meself, 
I
 bell he's pulling a fast one here. Yes, saying did you really dad? Yes he'd say - I said, did you ever win? He said, oh I used to win, yes. Oh yes. I said, how much did you get for wining? He said, mm - might get a dollar. Five bob. I said, cor - get kno
c
ked all about all over the place for five shillings? Yes. Yes. So they used to tell me all the stories. He never - remember - Queen Victoria when she come down Canning Town have a look round. And - I - I remember meself, Prince - Edward, Prince - the Duke
 of - of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 Winds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 or, the Du}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 e of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 Winds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
or? Yes, he come down Canning Town when I was a boy - young fellow. - Have a look round. His equerries, the chaps who guide him round, wanted him to go in a special house. This special house happened to be a - a council wo
rker's house. Had nice clean windows, curtains up and all that. Well - most of the people had old sacks and bits of paper - especially if they broke a window, they couldn't afford to buy - glass so they stick bits of paper up. And - the Prince of Wales sa
i
d - no, I don't think I'll go in that house, he said, let's have a look further down the street. So he walked down Bidder Street a little way and he come to a - another little house, sacks up the window. So he said, I'll have a look in here. He goes in. T
h
e man who owned it - man who lived in it I mean, he let him in. When he said who he was he very night dropped dead. Anyway, the Prince o Wales come - and of course I'm only going what I was told, I - I didn't actually hear him say this, but he said, disgr
a
ceful. Disgraceful. Oh how people can live in such filth I don't know, disgraceful. So he got in his car and drove a little way up, bit further, and we had a - a woman's mission - mission hall they called it - in Bidder Street, not far away - from where h
e
 went in this house, and there used to be a - a lady looked after it, she used to guide the old people about and that - look after the kids and - Mrs Bloomfield I think her name was, Bloomer - Bloomer. Mrs. Bloomer, and - she had a - His Majesty was - roa
m
ing around the town, village, so she stood outside this - hall, waiting for him to pass. And when he did pass she got right in front of his car. Stop your Majesty, stop. Now I see this. So he said, oh - he knew her - oh Mrs Bloomer, how do you do? She sai
d
, would you like to come in and see how we're looking after the old people? She had a - few old ladies in there, having a meeting. And - he said, yes, I don't mind. So he went in. All his gang what was with him followed him in, and - she told him then, sh
e
 said - really, she said, I - could do with some help. She said, in any way possible she said to help these poor people? He said, Mrs Bloomer, I've just witnessed - what - how poor people live, he said. And they wanted to take him in a council - blokes ho
u
se you know and - oh lovely furniture in it, and - but, no, he wanted to go in the poorest house, he come to this house with sacks up at the window, he said, that's it, I'll go in there. Well he was just telling Mrs Bloomer what he'd just witnessed. So sh
e
 said, anything you can do for these people, clothing, boots or shoes, money? She says, more money of course the better, she says. And - he - he promised to help her. Well eventually he did. He did do to carry on. He - he sent - sacks and sacks and sacks 
-
 well parcels - bundles of clothing - to the - mission hall, and - she shared them out to all people what was in need of 'em, Mrs Bloomer. Oh I thought, wonderful. Marvellous. Good old King. Well he wasn't King then, he was only the Prince of Wales. Yes, 
I
 can - I was interested in his - when he - well - when he fell in love with Mrs what was her name - now me, my name's Bushnell. I've just witnessed that the Prince of Wales is touring old Canning Town. I said, would you like to send somebody down and take
 
a report about it? We already know it. Well, I said, I haven't seen anybody come and take notes of it. He said, but they're there. Whoever was speaking on the phone I don't know but - I said, oh waste of money. Because it use - the reward would be five sh
i
llings. You got five shillings if you - if it was - what - no - hadn't already been notified see. I was looking forward to five bob. Letting them know the Prince of Wales was in Canning Town. But I never got it. They already knew they said. But I - I - I 
thought to myself, nobody's here taking notes and - can't - they don't know, so I phoned them up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your father ever take you out by himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, used to take me for - when he was capable of course, he'd take me for walks. Chiefly over Woo
lwich. Plumstead Common. See the soldiers on the church parade. Things like that. Now I never forget when he come home from - when I come home from India - 1922 - or '23, something like that, he said to me - come for a walk today son? I said, yes dad, I'm
 ready. Righ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 t s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
o. So - I was nicely dressed, I had a suit - what I had out the Army give me, a civvy suit - and he takes me over Woolwich. Gets to Plumstead Common, see the soldiers on parade. I thought to myself, well I never. I've just come out the Army m
eself done all the Army parades, church parades and everything else - been a cook for eighteen months, nearly two years. I said, and he's brought me over here to see the soldiers. I said, I - I - I thought you was going to show me something else dad. He s
aid, what would you like to see? Well I said, some museum or - place where there's interest, I said, I - I don't want to see that. Done it - soldiers on parade, church parade.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you remember when you were young if you had to go to bed at a certain t
ime every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. No. Not me. Me brothers and sisters had to. But I never. I was always alive, you know, ready to do anything. And - say to my mother, don't want to go to bed yet mum, I'll go for a walk, see. So all right, she knew I'd go for a w
alk for her, see what I could find, or see what I could pick up. Never used to pinch anything. All on the level.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And you put yourself to bed when you came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I put myself to bed when I came in. We had a bit of string on the door, and - ont
o the lock, through a little tiny hole in the street door - put the string through so when you wanted to get in just pull the string used to pull the lock back and - go in. 'Cos - if I was the last one in I'd put the bolt on. But - anybody could walk in m
y house. Pull the string, let yourself in. That was on old trick years ago for - them days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your mother have a kind of weekly wash, how did you manage about that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh, we had our own bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You had a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. We had a big galvanised - tin bath, you know, long thing. Get two in it. My size. Them days. We used to bath in that quite a lot, until - I started work, then I - getting a bit too old to bath in front of me sister, and I used to go to 
the public bath, West Ham. Abbey Arms, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Beckton Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Browning Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} I mean, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Browning Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} there's a bath there, public bath. Went there and bathed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
As she was going out to work how did your mother with manage washing the clothes and all that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Who, mother? Oh, she used to cope with it lovely. She'd - Sunday mornings - she didn't go to work much of a Sunday, she'd have a big - enamel - tin bath, and a scrubbing board, and - she'd buy a couple pound of soda, there was no posh powders them day
s, just used common soda and a lump of Lifebuoy soap. And - rub the old clothes up against the - rubbing board and get 'em nice and white. Then she'd hang 'em on the line. But more or less - the line was hopeless, 'cos where we lived in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}14 New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, right 
the back of my garden - there was the - electric power station. Electricity station, power station - factory. And when they charged up the - furnaces, send out all - sorts of muck, like - soot and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 little}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  pieces of coal, charcoal and all that used to come
 out the chimneys and - and - if the wind was in our direction it fell all over mum's white - nice white clothes. And take 'em in like they got the measles. Yes. And - she had to dip 'em all in water again to get all these little black specks off. Oh, I s
a
id to her, let me know mum when - when you're going to hang clothes up again, I said, and I'll - take 'em out the front, or hang them up in the shop. I said, I'll fix up a couple of lines in the shop and - we called it the shop although we never sold noth
ing. I said, put the clothes up there. Mm -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In that front room really, the front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, it was the parlour more or less you know. But - I fixed up a couple of line from wall to wall and all that and hung the clothes over there, just so that 
mum wouldn't have to - wash 'em all over again. And - after they finished trimming their fires up in the electric light works - apart from that there used to be a Telfer - grab cane thing used to run right round the factory, with - coal. It grabbed the co
a
l out of barges and - run right round the factory to whatever department it's got to be shotted in - shot in, the coal. The dust - thick black dust used to come up - it'd all settle in my garden, being it was from here to here, and - I had to go out there
 and shovel it up. Used to use it myself, put on me fire. Yes. And - I'd get a big shovel full, of this coal dust. Oh it used to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 awful}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 It sounds as if it was quite a struggle to keep clean in that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, it was. It was all - only outside,
 never used to get much inside. Unless we left the door open or the windows open, but - couldn't do that, never know when this stuff was coming down. Although I knew within a little when it was time to furnace the fires up, I said, shut the doors. Cokes a
nd - coal dust coming in. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you'd have a weekly change of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Clothing. Oh yes, yes. Oh mum used to keep us clean. Oh she was always washing. Well, I say always, she used to wash every week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there some families round about then where they didn't keep very clean?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Plenty. Proper old tramps. Yes. Some of the boys didn't know what a bath was. See in - in their places. Yes - yes - oh I - I got a right if I wanted to but - I sit - I sit down to write something I've got to
 keep getting out the back. I heard a lot about Dick Turpin's cave. Teacher used to talk about Dick Turpin's cave. So I thought to myself, one of these days I'll go and see Dick Turpin's cave, in - Plumstead, you know, Bostall Woods - Bostall Woods I thin
k
 it was called. Yes. I'm sure it is. Anyway. I found me way to Bostall Woods one day, I went to - Backwall tunnel, to Poplar, through Blackwall Tunnel, straight the way through Greenwich 'til I come to this place where Dick Turpin's supposed to have live 
a
nd escaped - escaped from the police and all that. So I had a tour round the cliffs where he used to hide hisself. I see a massive great hole - right by the corner of - well - dugout sort of thing, and - there's a pole, straight up - in front of this hole
,
 so I climbed up the pole, and - got me head in the big hole and had a good look round, but I couldn't see nothing, it was too dark. I thought to myself, I wonder if I was to crawl through that hole I'd come out somewhere. Oh I'd better not chance it, mig
ht lose myself. So I wouldn't chance it, so I come down from there, had a good look round the woods, Bostall Woods, and - I was getting tired, thirsty, I thought I'd better go home. So I started to walk home, I got right back as far as - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - Gas Works. And it's just outside - of - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} end of - Blackwall Tunnel. And I sat down. Rest me legs. I hadn't been sitting there long when - across the road there was some bungalows, a lady come out the door and looked across to me and - walked over She sai
d, are you all right son? I said, yes ma'am, I'm all right. She said, are you hurt anywhere? I said, no ma'am. She said, don't sit on the cold ground. I said, I'm all right. I said, I'm hungry. She said, are you really? I said, yes. I said, I've been out 
a
ll day. Had nothing to eat. So she said all right, stop where you are, I'll go and get you - something to eat. So she come back with a parcel. Little parcel. Bread and jam. Oh, I said, what a bit of luck. Thank you luv, I said, God bless you. She said - e
a
t that, she said, and you'll be - refreshed and you'll get along a bit better. So I said, thank you luv. So I ate me bread and jam. And just as I was going to get up I looked in the bag and there was a threepenny bit in it. Silver threepenny piece. Holy s
m
oke, I thought to myself. Gawd strewth, what a bit of luck, what a lovely lady. Oh - so, away I shot through Blackwall Tunnel, walked it, it's a mile and a quarter long, Blackwall Tunnel. And - got to Poplar, I thought to myself, shall I have a penny ride
 
on the trams? Trams were running, them days, no buses or anything. There was buses but very few apart. No - I'll walk it. So I walked home. I gets home, said to my mother - oh she said, where have you been all day? I said - for a walk mum. Whereabouts? I 
s
aid, over Bostall Woods. Over Bostall Woods, what did you go all that way for? I said, see Dick Turpin's cave. Yes, Dick Turpin's cave. He's been dead donkey's years. I said, I know he has mum, I wanted to see what he left behind him. See if he might have
 left some money or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 jewellery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 or something, stowed away in his cave. That was what was in me mind. Find something what he'd pinched. Dick Turpin had pinched and left it up in his cave. Anyway I didn't chance going that cave, it was too dark. So - I said I'v
e got this for you luv. Oh. She said, what? I said, threepenny bit. Oh - you've saved the bacon again son, she said, oh bless you, give it to me. I give her the threepenny bit. Away she went to the fish shop. She bought dad two big fat bloaters. And fried
 'em. Bit of flour on 'em, I remember seeing her shake the flour on them, turn 'em over, put more flour on, put 'em in the pan, frying pan. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She fried on this gas cooker you said?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, all gas. No electric. Gas light, gas cooking. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Which meals did your dad have with you was he out for breakfast or was he there when you had your breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When dad used to go to work of a morning, did he have any breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did he have it with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh he used to go out - too early. Y
es, he'd to be out at six. Well, he had to be at work by six. Six in the morning, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you wouldn't really see him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, I wouldn't see whether he had any breakfast or not, but I expect he did have something. Mother wouldn't let him go without -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did he have a separate dinner when he came in, did he have his tea or dinner by himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, he shared it with - with - yes, we'd all sit round the table and have what we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But he'd have more food than the rest of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, he c
ould eat more than I could. Well not always, sometimes he wasn't fit enough to eat a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 ny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 thing. But when he was alright he used to eat well. Oh yes, especially with the stew mum used to cook with sixpenn'orth of pieces and - oh he loved - loved that. So did I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did you ever see your mother having less so that the rest of you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well sometimes you'd say, can I have a drop more luv? She'd say, yes, certainly, she's give him -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you see your mother having less so the rest of you could have more?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh, I see what you mean, yes, mother used to have a little bit but she didn't have as much as us. I mean she used to make sure we was well fed. Yes. As long as we had - as long as we had enough, mother have what was left. But there was 
always plenty of - stew. We had a - or mother had a - a - a - egg shaped saucepan, with a handle each end of it, and - she'd put all her - meat pieces and - potatoes and greens and what have you in this saucepan and - boil it all up, pearl barley - and al
l
 the little knick-knacks she'd put in the stew, tomatoes if we could get tomatoes and all and put them in. And she'd make a - a whopping great stew. Enough - well, to feed twelve people. And that used to be on the stove - until the next time she wanted to
 
cook some more. It might be two or three days - on that kitchener, that range what used to be there, and - she - put the lid on so it didn't get too hot, the range - cover, and - it'd be nice and warm. Now any time I was out - looking for anything I could
 pick up, I'd come home - lift the lid up, ah, lovely, get a big bowl.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did she bake any bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Bake any bread? No. Never cooked bread, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about making jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, she'd make jam, yes. I used to go blackberry picking. And the ch
ief dish she used to make that when we went hop picking. We couldn't get blackberries unless I went right out in the country. As far as Rainham were I lived afterwards - picking blackberries. But - more or less mum used to make jam down the hop country, '
cos there were plenty of blackberries growing down there. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would she make -pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pardon? Yes. Yes. If dad - could manage to grow some shallots - she'd skin the shallots and make -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your mother make any wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No wine. She u
sed to make jam out of blackberries and apples and - plums and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did she bottle any vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She did what? No. No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 af}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 raid not. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
You said you had tinned beef, corned beef, did you ever have any tinned or dried vegetables before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. No, I don't think you used to get it in tins. Noth - nothing in tins then. Used to be - open on the - on the shop front - or the stall and you'd go and - tell the bloke what you wanted and he'd shovel it
 up for you. Yes. Oh there might have been a tin of corned beef. But - or a tin of spam or something like that. Tin of sardines. But - nothing in the way of - what you buy today. Cut slices of - fruit you know, what do they call it - pineapple, yes, yes. 
Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I don't suppose around {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you could get rabbits from poaching could you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You had to get right in the country to do a thing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But there were people coming round selling rabbits round the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, yes, qu
ite a few, yes. We had one old chap used to come round - selling rabbits. If we was rich enough we used to buy - one off him, perhaps he'd cut it in half and give us half of it, and - what half you fancied, the - head half or the tail half. And - you coul
d
 - buy it with the skin on, or you could buy it - he - he'd take the skin off for you. Hook it on his barrow and - pull the skin off and - put the skin - away - for end of his barrow, and - but if he sold you - one with the skin on he'd charge you for the
 
skin. If - if you wanted to sell it back to him you could. Yes. After you've had a - had the rabbit up. And you keep the skin in a preserved place - any old tin box or something like that out in the garden, and - when he come again say, I've got - rabbit 
skin. All right. Threepence, tuppence or threepence for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But there were other people coming round selling food from door to door?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well, we used to get the baker and the milkman but - I can't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 Ice cream}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I can't think of - no, I ca
n't remember anybody - selling food at the door. Except milk and baker. The butcher used to come round if you wanted a - yes, there used to be a butcher used to push his stuff round on a barrow and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There were no other people pushin
g their barrows round the streets selling things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, there used to be - a hot potato man. Selling hot potatoes. Hot chestnuts. Cooking them on the - coke fire he had on his barrow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you used to buy those as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well, I used to b
uy 'em if I had the money but - if I - it's very seldom I had the money to buy 'em with. And - there used to be another lady come round with a jellied eel stall. Push that round the streets. Jellied eels. Yes. I knew that lady quite well. I think her name
 was Sweetman. She used to sell jellied eels and - things like that. Fish, mackerel. She'd have mackerel on her - barrow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you buy any of those though or was it just the bloaters you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Bloaters more or less.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't buy eels and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Although I loved eels, I used to like 'em - if I could afford to buy 'em, but I never had enough money to buy eels. They was too dear, they was very dear in them days. Threepence a little - bowl - of jellied eels. A lot of money
. But - of course - years - has gone and on and on - I - I can't pass a jellied eels stall now, if I've got - two or three bob in me pocket I must have a basin of jellied eels. And half a crown you get six little pieces now for half a crown. Well that's -
 fifteen pence isn't it, half a crown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Can you tell me about when you were eating the meals, did you all sit round the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you each have your own place or did you sit anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, we all had our own chairs. My sisters
 and brother. We all had our own chairs and we used to sit, 'cos only - had a small family then when I - I was a boy, there - Bob me eldest brother and - for quite a long while he wasn't with us, he went to live with my Uncle Jack - in - saltash, Portsmou
th way, and he helped him out in his farm. I think I wrote that story in there didn't I?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's when you went down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I walked there. I walked to - yes - yes, that - that - me sister Edie, Bob, sister Edie and meself and Jess. Louis, Lou
is, she's the next oldest - then there was Jess. Jessie. Well as far back as I can remember - we all had our own little - seats sometime they got a chair you see you sit on a stool, see, round the table and we all had our respective places. I couldn't go 
and sit in Bob's chair, he'd want to know what I was doing there if he - he'd say, here get out of it, hop it, it's my chair. Being the oldest one of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you serve up in the scullery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, in the kitchen. What we called the kitchen. This dining room, you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you put it on the table there and help yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, yes. Yes. Oh no, we didn't help ourself to it unless - mother give us permission which she used to - she had a - soup bowls, used to put the - whatever it wa
s in the bowl. Well the - them days you couldn't very well ask for more 'cos there was no more to ask for. We'd eat up all what there was to eat. See
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What happened if you didn't like something and you left it on your plate?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well I'm afraid - I 
never used to - I used to eat anything she give me. My brother Bob was a bit finicky that way, he - he - sometimes he'd say, oh I don't like that. And I'd say, oh well, if you don't want it, what would you like? And - I'll have a bit of bread and butter. 
All right. Bit of bread and butter. But - none of - my sisters were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 finicky}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . They ate all what mum could give 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
If you were hungry between meals would she let you have a bit of bread and butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were all sitting there did she let you talk during a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, not very - no it - now and again we used to talk if mother wasn't listening, but - dad used to be the one for that, he'd say you can't eat with your mouth full. You can't talk I mean with your mouth full. Ea
t your food first and then talk afterwards. He used to be like that me father but - I don't think me mother was - strict as dad was. No. Still we used to talk, yes. Occasionally. Didn't make a - show of it, you know, just a whisper to one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Wha
t about how you held your knife and fork or how you sat, were they strict about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - that come natural to you. You - if you didn't want }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 to you\rquote re}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  your knife and fork you just use a spoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They didn't mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, they didn't mind, no.
 They didn't mind how we used the knife and fork. No. There's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 only one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , that's my sister Louis I think, she's left handed. She has her knife in her left hand, the fork in her right hand, and I used to say to her, change your knife and fork round, you're }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 cockeyed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
. She'd say, no I'm not. I'd say, you are, you're eating it - the wrong way round. She said, no I'm not, she'd say, I - I like holding me knife in that hand, in the left hand. I couldn't cut with - nothing with me left hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They wouldn't tell you to sit up straight and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. No. No. Used to say at the end of the meal - had we all had enough. Dad might say, have they all had enough? If you want any more say so now. Don't let your mother - clear up and then say, oh I want 
this and I want that. I'd say, well - no dad, I've had enough. And my brother and sisters say - no, we've had enough dad. Oh, good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If you finished before the rest could you go off?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Go out? Oh yes, yes, go where we liked. Nobody -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They didn't make you sit and wait until everybody had finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, no. No. No, it's - used to ask though. I used to ask. May I get down please dad? Yes, where do you want to go? Oh - in the back. Oh all right, go on. Or I might say, I - I - I've got a ma
te to meet and - all right, away you go. But - we had to ask. Couldn't get down just - push your chair away and walk out - had to ask mum and dad - permission first. Say, yes, all right, go on, away you go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was your father rather stricter than your mother then do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
In a little sense he was stricter than mum. 'Cos mum really was a - very hard working woman, she - she had - a lot of worries on her - plate, you know what I mean, apart from us children worrying her she had - dad to worry abo
ut and - she wasn't quite so strict as dad but - dad was a lovely gentleman, he - kind hearted man, he'd do anything - do his utmost for us children. For me he would anyway. Think the world of me. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How would he show it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well, for an example
 - when I was in - when I joined the Army in 1918 - he said to me, while I've got the health and strength son, he said, to work, he said, I'll put a shilling a week away in a tin box for you. I said, you will dad? Oh lovely. There's be something for you t
o come home to. All right dad. I said to him, I said, don't worry about giving me a shilling a week dad, I said, give it to the wife, 'cos I was married then, before I went in the - to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}
, I got married before I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I heard I was going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 so I said to my - girl, I said, let's get married. You'll have something to live on, I said, you'll have my allowance, or half of me allowance. So she said, all right luve. So we got married. The beginning of 1919. But - dad used to say, I'll put that sh
illing a week away for you son all the time you're away. I said, all right dad. And he did. I had about - three pound something - with the interest on it, from the Post Office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were a little boy would he show affection to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, h
e did, yes. Very affectionate to me he was. I - couldn't go wrong with me father. Yes, he was a wonderful old boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your mother was the same really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, loving. Very loving. Thought the world of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If you were worried about something would
 you come and talk to them or would you keep it to yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well, more or less I used to keep it to meself if I had any worries on me mind. I wouldn't worry me father and mother about it. No. Except like when I used to go to school and I'd get the 
stick for doing something I shouldn't do, like roller skating - putting a ball on me boot to roller skate and all that - take him to school on me foot. Teacher give me - three }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 hinders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  - I come home crying to me mother. She said, I'll kill that bleeder, I'll kill him. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did she go up there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, she did go once to see the headmaster when - he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 calmed her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 down, he said, look mother, he said - he was a danger to himself and to the public. He rolled down that hill - from top of the hill to the
 school, it was all downhill like - and he - couldn't - control himself, he said, I seen him, he said - dodging in and out, he said and people walking up the road, he said, up the hill, people coming down the hill. He said, he's a real danger. So mother s
aid, oh - all right. He said, I had to cane him otherwise he wouldn't understand. He'd do it again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But if you wanted to talk to them it was easy to talk to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Quite easy. Yes. Oh they never got offended or anything I used to say. No. As 
long as it was the truth. If I was telling a fibber - then they'd say, I don't believe you. You're telling me a lot of lies. I'd say, no I aint mum, or I aint dad, I'm telling you the truth. I - I believe you. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How would you say that they expected you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well I - I just - carried on me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 usual}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 way, just love 'em - and - work for 'em and - do me utmost to - look after 'em, feed 'em, do me - whatever I possibly could to help 'em. Same as when I used to go up - City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} looking for anything I could pick up - I always give it to me mother. See? That half a sovereign I found - I run all the way from the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Strand{\*\xmlclose}
. I don't know if you know the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Strand{\*\xmlclose} or not. Yes. What was the name of that - the Hotel Pimlico, no, no, oh I can't think of the name of the hotel, but it's in this {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}Strand{\*\xmlclose}, there's another big hotel on the opposite side where the very rich people usually - The Dolphin - Hotel. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Savoy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. That's it, yes. I should have remember that because - used to get Savoy Orpheans Two L
.O. on the - wire - wireless set. They were crystal set - them days, when - when sets first came out they had a little crystal. You had to find it with a - hair - hair pin. See, the sound. And I used to lay in bed and go to sleep with it - earphones on yo
u
r ears. Yes. This is the - - Savoy Orpheons Two L.O. music. Yes. When me father was ill - of a wintertime, couldn't go to work because of his chest - I used to fix up this little set, fix it on me ears, fiddle about with it until I got a nice sound, say h
ere you are dad, listen to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Oh I was a young man then, I was round about what - eighteen, seventeen or eighteen, something like that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 As far as the way you were with your brothers and sisters, wou
ld your parents tell you how to behave to them or would they just leave you to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, they never told me to - I never got up to any mischief to upset 'em. It was always them what upset me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they say if another child hit you you should hit back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, dad used to say - don't let anybody take advantage of you son. If - if you're in the clear, if you - if you've done nothing wrong, he'd say, you know you're right - let 'em have one. He said, take your own part, he said. Don't come
 crying to me or your mother. Take your own part. I said, well - I - I'll remember that dad. And same as he told me once - when I first - the first motor bike I ever bought - or was it a pushbike, I think it was a push bike. He said, remember son, anybody
 can go fast - but it takes a blooming good man to stop. Yes. He said, when you're riding that bike, take it easy, don't go mad. Right dad. Always think of that. Anybody can go fast but it takes a good man to stop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Looking back on it what kind of peopl
e do you think they hoped their children would grow up to be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 Millionaires}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  I think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They thought that not being poor was the most important thing in life then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 It was with me. I - well I - I - I - knelt down the side of my bed an
d I prayed. Lots of times. Hoping one day I should be rich enough - to send my father to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Spain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - where the sun is always shining or - anywhere where he could get his health back. And me mother. As I said I used to - I was the breadwinner. I used to do ev
erything possible I could to help 'em. Fetch in a few bob for 'em. And then when the flood come - I carried me father from - Canning Town gate when he was gatekeeper there - I carried him on me back, went through all the - timber floating about - and - I 
got dad home and took him upstairs to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 mum\rquote s bed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 and - he was really pleased to think I done it but at the same time he wasn't, he said, you shouldn't have done it son, he kept saying to me, you shouldn't have done it. I said, look dad, I said, you might have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 drowned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 yourself, if you had fell off that high stool you were sitting on, I said, you wouldn't have had strength to get - the cold water would have got in your - I said, I don't know much about - pains and aches, I said, but I said I know - it wouldn't 
have done you no good. Well anyway he - he went back next morning when the flood went down. Terrible flood it was. About 1925 or six I think that was. The logs come down the street from Howards Timber Yard, and they floated down - down the street, and - l
eft - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bidder Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - where I lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} - it was a blocked turning, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and the water kept coming up and up and up, see. Couldn't get out no further. And bloody great tree logs was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 bumping}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  up against the street door. I went - I got up to see -
 I thought somebody was - banging at me door to come in or something. So I got up, I got down the stairs, halfway down the stairs, I put me foot in water. Well it come up to me knee. Good three foot nearly. So - well I thought - I went up to mother's, she
 
said, who's that banging down there Jimmy? She shouted out first, who's that down there? I said, only me mum. She said, who - who's that banging I said, I don't know, I'll go and have a look. I said, the house is flooded. Flooded? I said, yes, don't come 
d
own luv whatever you do. Yes. And the street after that water subsides, well my goodness, slosh, mud - stunk, oh tell you. So all - all the women soon got their brooms and shovels and - swept it all up and - most of it anyway. Firemen come out with their 
hoses and - washed and scoured down. That's from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 station where Howards timber yard is, it's all downhill. Go right down the hill 'til you get to - a railway crossing called Peggy Leggy Steps, that's another story, Peggy Leggy Steps, and then - 
it goes uphill. And then when it gets to the top of - the - hill, there's another bridge - a traffic bridge, not a - footbridge like Peggy Leggy Steps - traffic runs over this bridge, then goes downhill, right to West Ham station. Underground railway stat
ion. Well, all the water - coming from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, the River Lee overflowed, it run down the - hill, and - down my turning, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and there it settled. It couldn't go no further. Logs, timber - all from the Howards timber yard. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Going back ag
ain can you remember what would happen if you did do something which your mum and dad disapproved of, what would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - actually I can't remember - ever doing anything like that, but I suppose I must have done in me time, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You can't remember them ever punishing you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, they never used to hit me. No, not - none of the children used to get a whacking for anything they done. Not as I can remember. Very good to us, mum and dad were. Yes. I can't remember ever getting a whacking. 
Me father, I - he never used to - hit me at all, he used to give me a good talking to mind you, but - never whacked me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Would say that you got your ideas about how to behave from both of them or from one rather than the other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well more from me
 father. He used to tell me - secrets of life and all that sort of thing. But me mother was the kindest - she was kind hearted me mother. All the things I used to do - was more for me mother than it was me father. Know what I mean? I knew dad'd get better
 
some day and he'd be able to go back to work and - carry on - smoking his old - clay pipe. Yes. I used to go to a pub and get him a clay pipe occasionally. I'd get him a pint of - pint of ale, old and mild he used to drink, beer called old and mild, and -
 a clay pipe please. Who wants the pipe? Dad. Oh all right. You don't want it for blowing bubbles do you son? No, no, no, no, dad wants a clay - clay pipe. Right. If you was going to blow bubbles with a pipe you wouldn't get one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He always had his beer at home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
He used to go in a pub occasionally. But he - he liked to have a drink indoors, he - he didn't like going out too much, the old wind and the - smoke and the fumes from the gas works and the glass blowers - the glass blowers was further
 up the road, the - electric light factory where all the cinders and ash used to come - he didn't like none of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would your mum ever go out to the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, mum - mum - no, she never used to go in a pub, I used to go and get her beer. A ping of porter. I don't know if you know what porter is, it's like Guinness. Yes, stout, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was that because it wasn't the thing for women to go into a pub at that time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well not - women used to go in pubs - or some women used to go in pubs, but - 'cos them days they never had a ladies toilet. See? Had a gentleman's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 toilet}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , but noth - nothing for the ladies. No, you couldn't stay long, they had to nip off somewhere on the quick, in some neighbours house or - get behind a cart.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would your mother ever go out just to enjoy herself anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. Occasions she used to go out and enjoy herself. Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What would she do then when she went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well she'd - comb her hair, put on her best - things, what she could afford - and - more or less used to go out with my sister Edie, that one up there, and take her with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where would they go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Might go to pictures. Threepence up the cinema. See Charlie Chaplin. Mm. Or they might go to a meeting. Because they used to have - 
be several meetings about, Lees Hall - Barking Road, and - the Mission Hall down Bidder Street, the one I told you about with the Prince of Wales.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
These were all religious halls you mean, when you say a meeting you mean a kind of religious meeting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh it wasn't all - no, wasn't very religious, they'd talk about - how to make things meet at home - how to cook things - mothers meeting, yes. How to sew. Lot of sewing. As a matter of fact they had their own sewing classes, used to go there to learn 
- to do embroidery or something. There wasn't many sewing machines, people wasn't wealthy enough to buy a sewing machine, they had to do it by hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would your father go out to meetings at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I'm afraid dad never - wasn't - he - he - he wa
s coughing all the time you know, he was upset everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He didn't belong to a working mens club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. No. Afraid not. Although when I become of age, I used to - take him - to a working man's club. I joined a working mans club because I was 
an artiste. I was a talented artiste. Yes. I could whistle - sing, not a good singer, poor singer, but I could sing - all the old fashioned songs like - there swing down our alley comes a toff, my old woman goes and knocks his bloody topper off - all song
s
 like that you know. And - I could whistle, - I could whistle better than I could sing. I could even impersonate any bird you like to mention. Mm. Barring a cuckoo, I could never do - imitate a cuckoo. But - skylark, canary, thrust - blackbird, starlings,
 any - any sort of bird, I - I could impersonate 'em. Just whistle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When did you start that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When I was about - yes, when I was about - eighteen. In the Army I picked it up. 'Cos they - they wanted volunteers to come and make a concert party up i
n the Army, you know, as volunteers. They said, what are you going to do? I said. Whistle. All right. Have a rehearsal - and I whistled. I whistled - when the sands of the - desert go cold. When the sands of the desert grow cold, that was it. And - I lear
n
t that - one of the chaps played the piano so many times I learnt it from him. And I whistled that number, and they thought a lot of it. Said, well - jolly good that, do you know anything else? Said, yes, plenty. Can you sing? I said, yes. Well in a way, 
I said, I - a few old songs. Just the boy we want. You're signed on. Yes. Yes, I used to enjoy it too. Well when I come home from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}, I had a pal out in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} with me named Charlie Dive, he was a Cornishmen. We used to do Cornish wrestling, me and him. H
e'd get me by the coat and try and get me down you know like, and - when we - got home to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cornwall{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 he had a brainwave, he said, I'll go and see Jimmy, called me Jimmy. He might be able to - fix me up as his manager. I'd be - he'd be my manager, and - anywa
y he come to see me and he said, how would I like to come up the City and see an agent and all that, get in touch with the fellow and - get some bookings. So I went to see one agent, and he said, oh - you know I had to do a show for him, he played the pia
n
o and - I do a show for him to prove I could do it, and he said, yes, all right. He sent him - he sent me - to Kensington - music hall. Kennington - Kensington, I think that's the name of it. And - when me and Charlie got there - he told the - the manager
,
 a lady manager it was then, they said I was - a - chap served with the Army and all that sort of thing and - all right, see what you can do. So I done me show. And I dressed meself up as a rookie, soldier, a rookie, I had me putties done up anyhow and - 
c
ollar all undone and me hat cockeyed and all that sort of thing, I was proper rookie. And I whistled - 'Til the sands of the Desert grow cold and also - I pass by your window. I pass by your window. Then I said, now ladies and gentlemen I'll give you - al
l
 any impersonations of various well known birds which you all know so well and we love so dearly. So of course I do all the impersonations. And they - I got a wonderful clap. First house it was, first house. So - the - the man - lady manager said - can yo
u
 be here for the second house? I said, yes, of course luv, yes, lovely. Good. So of course I expected - some money for me shows but - when I asked her I said, any payment for me luv? She said, payment? Oh no, she said. You're here to be discovered. Oh. Oh
 
am I. Well, I said, what about return booking then for some money? So she said, well, she said, we have - we can't pay you for anything you do now, she said, but - if you like I'll book you all over London, all over provincial towns as well, she said - ho
w
 good you - how clever you are at whistling, she said, and you'll bound to be picked up, bus, she said, no money. So I said to Charlie I said, my friend, I said, did you hear what she said? He said, yes. He said, come on. No good stopping here. Won't get 
nothing here. I said, well - what about giving it a try then, let me - he said, who's going to pay your fares? \{BLANK\} Yes. I used to hold it well away from me 'cos my whistling was so loud it used to deafen everybody.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were saying that Charlotte S
treet was about a mile away from where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 New Road, where I used to live, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Of Hermit Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Off Hermit Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Was that where your father kept that pub, would that have been near Charlotte St?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, that was in Bidder St
reet. Yes. I still can't think of the name of the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
You were saying that New Road was just really a terrace of cottages, a sort of cul-de-sac?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 With a pub at the corner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And then the entrance to the gas works?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Tapper Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Next to New Road. Going back towards {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} that would be. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Could you tell me the story about Peggy Leg Steps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well it's - all I know is - what it - Peggy Dooley used to get up to, the steps itself didn't mean a thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well about Peggy Dooley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Peggy Dooley, yes. Well, often when I went over the steps - to go to a relation or - perhaps go to the pictures or something like that, I used to see Peggy Dooley sitting on the steps. Well more or less
 he was drunk, he used to drink a hell of a lot of beer, where he got his money from gawd above knows. But - I think - a lot of people used to take sympathy on him. So this particular - time I went across the steps he's sitting on the step, singing to him
s
elf, and - a young lady walked across the - steps - I thought to myself then, this is it, he - he'll get up to his tricks again. So he just said to the girl, don't be afraid of me luv, I won't hurt you. So - she said, well I hope you don't. Then of course
 
- I suppose the young lady got scared, told the first policeman she - see. Well he come after Peggy Dooley on the steps, still sitting there. And soon as see the policeman coming along so he unscrewed his wooden leg. And started - waving it about. Of cour
s
e the policeman didn't want to get a cosh on the - head with - it was a big heavy thing, that wooden leg of his. And - had a big stump to it, big base you know, a couple of - iron - things to hold it - strap round his leg sort of affair you know. So - I -
 
watching from a distance you know. Anyway - how the policeman got in touch with his - mates I don't know, but suddenly there was another couple of policeman turned up, they grabbed hold of Peggy Dooley and - that one policeman brought the wheelbarrow alon
g
, the ambulance thing, and - he got Peggy Dooley strapped to it, it was - had - belts you know, round his chest and round his legs and round his arms. They used to well strap him down, he couldn't move a muscle. So - away he went to the police station. Bu
t he was back there again in a few days after that, I see him again. Waving his wooden leg around.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was the railway crossing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, it was a railway crossing, it run from Woolwich - to - Fenchurch Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And he used to sit there and frighten the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well, I - I don't know what his - really intentions were but he never interfered with the girls. Used to frighten them you know, frighten the daylights out of 'em. Especially if he took his wooden leg off. Peggy Dooley, yes. O
h he was a well known character in Canning Town. 'Cos - he used to come along the street - after he's had a fair drink, and be singing all the old songs you know. And - people say to him, why don't you hold your bloody row, I'm trying to get my baby to sl
e
ep. All right, missus. Quite calm you know, all right missus. Away he'd trot on, get a little way down the road further, singing away again. And so the people used to get fed up with it - fed up with him, making such a lot of noise. That's how they got to
 
know him so well. Mm. He was a wonderful character though. I only wish I knew more about him. I remember once seeing him outside the - public house - what was that public house called now - it was the first pub after you leave Canning Station, it - they -
 
right in the centre of Stevenson Street and Bidder Street. I can't think of the name of it. Anyway he was standing outside there hanging onto - hanging onto a - a - a post, and singing a top note and all - up come the police. Come on Peggy. Home. Leave me
 
alone. I'll do you with this. And he unscrewed his wooden leg. And he - wave his - wooden leg about the policeman's head. Well what he got that I don't know, he must have got heavy fine or - he might have done the time, 'cos he certainly hit that policema
n very hard with his truncheon - with his wooden leg. No, he - he didn't like policemen. Oh no, policeman - only had to speak to him - he'd - wooden leg off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you see much of the police around at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 We had a policeman there - no, not a
 lot, but we had one particular policeman - he was called Blue Muzzle. He had a big black beard. And - he used to be more after the hooligans, the kids, you know, smashing windows and things like that. Come along with a few bricks in their pocket and thro
w
 them at your window and then run. He used to have - this policeman used to have - ball bearings in the tips of his gloves, or little bits of lead, but more or less they was ball bearings and had - had them in his belt, hanging loose in his belt. So if he
 come up to a few - boys, you know, a bit naughty, he'd say, go on home, go on. And they give him any old cheek he'd hit 'em round the ear with the - these gloves. And them ball bearings didn't half sting. Cor. You used to get - hear bells in your ears.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He hit you then sometimes did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no, I never got in his way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You mean you used to run when you saw him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - well, more or less on me own, I - I didn't mix up with a crowd of boys like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where did the crowd of boys come from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well they might have come from the new estate, that's what they called - Canning Town, New Canning Town, or they might have come from - Victoria Dock Road way, the Custom House, Tidal Basin, or something like that. They wasn't our own lads - 
that lived in Canning Town, old Canning Town, it wasn't them, it was all strange boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Wouldn't your own lads try and get rid of them if they were breaking the windows?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pardon? Well I never see any - street fighting - amongst the two gangs. No, 
very seldom I see anything like that. Except once. The new estate boys wanted to have a go at the Old Canning Town boys - 'cos them days they wasn't so rough and - they never used - knives and things like that the same as they do today. They used to - fol
d
 their cap up with a lump of string, swing it round, give you a tap on the head with it. And - some of them dare - daring enough to put a brick in their - in their cap, or a couple of stones you know, make it a bit weighty, so they could swing it round a 
b
it. And - I remember I was in that lot. I couldn't help meself. I was forced to, to safe - safeguard meself I had to join in with - the Old Canning Town boys, 'cos they knew me. The - these chaps from the new estate, they knew who I was. 'Cos I was - I us
e
d to go along the street whistling you see, impersonating birds. Everybody got to know me. So - of course we won at the finish. We won - the fight, well it wasn't really a fight, it was just a bit of skylarking about. But - they packed up before we did, t
h
e new estate boys. That's the only time I can remember any - what they call fighting, though it wasn't fighting, it was only playing about really. But - I didn't like the way they were swinging theirs caps about, hitting me on the head. My deaf aid's brok
e.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There wasn't fighting at school like that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no, very seldom I see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Is it not working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, it does, it goes off, if - by turning me head it goes off. It's broken see. It's got a bit of paper sticking it together. No, I - I n
ever used to get involved in any fighting like that. Mind you I could fight. Fight like a demon. If I was put out. Any of the boys really come the old soldier with me I used to - lambaste them hard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But there weren't gangs in the playground at school for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pretty friendly all the - as far as I - go back to in memory, the boys in my school. I went to two schools - no, three schools I went to, I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Old{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school, then I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hilda Road
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school. Then I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Gainsborough Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school, that's where I left school, at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Gainsborough Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school, that's - on the way down towards West Ham Station. And - I - I can't remember seeing any boys in a gang fight - in the playground or anything like that. They was always too jolly, too bu
sy - doing exercises and - footballing, a little - tennis ball, they used to play football with. We had a - lot of - gymnastics - things in the - in the playground like - hand - hand rails for spinning yourself round and round and round. Muscles we used t
o call it. The muscles. You - you - jump up - grab hold of the pole - that run - left to right, and - grip your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 waist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , your trousers like, so that your - pole was running through your arms, and then you'd turn over and over and over. Keep going over and ove
r and over 'til you got giddy. I used to do quite a lot of that. And then there was the chute. You sit - go up the ladder and slide down the chute. Then there was the - horizontal bars. You know. You - swing about on two - bars, run parallel, and - turned
 right over - with them. If you was daring enough. All that sort of thing used to - boys used to play about with. But - as for - as for fighting one another, no, I can't remember anything - like that going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would there be a slightly older group of b
oys at the corner of the street? Standing around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well there used to be a crowd of youngsters - but we got to know 'em so well we used to say - pack it up or otherwise - you're for it. As we got older, see - so we knew more about these boys, and - we
 threatened them if they didn't pack up their - tricks. Like - I'll tell you one thing they used to do - they done it to my door as well as other peoples. They get a - piece of string, and tie it to the door knocker, from one door - the doors was - door t
h
ere and a door - street door, a lady living in that one and a lady living in that one you know, tie the two doors together, then knock. Bomp bomp. Then just - go away and stand back and laugh. As the lady come out to open the door she couldn't, the string
 
was - and the other lady'd be trying to open her door and she couldn't, and the knockers going bonkety bonk, bonkety bonk, bonkety bonk. Of course we only done it for a giggle. It was - be so daft. Then another time we'd - set a trap for any old boy or la
dy what come along bit pushed for cash and all that. Used to get a - swept a bit of horse dung up, and get a Nuthbrown packet, and put the horse dung in the Nut}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 h
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 brown packet and fold it up nice and neat and - tie a bit of thread, black thread on it. And we'
d stand the other side of the road, waiting for some old chap to come along. He'd see that packet laying on the ground, he'd go to pick it up, we'd pull the - and it keep moving. So eventually they give it up, he couldn't pick it up 'cos - }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  he be
nt down to pick it up we pulled the cotton - pulled the thread along. Bundles of wood. Get a - had a ha'penny or penny to spare - buy a couple of bundles of wood, and tie them the same as you would the Nutbrown packet. And a lady'd come along, say, oh the
re's a bit of luck, bundle of wood. Pull the cotton - all things like that we used to - just for a laugh.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You used to play out in the street did you mostly then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes, we used to play - a game called buttons. All sorts of buttons. Brass butt
ons were valuable. Bone buttons were not so valuable. And - soldiers buttons well - oh, they was golden prize they were. Off a tunic. Off a soldiers tunic. We used to bang 'em up against a fence, or a wall, and then - whoever got - near - enough to the ot
h
er - opponent's button, just spin it like that. Nine inches Eighteen inches. Well - the nearest one to that other button what the other fellow banged up against the wall was the winner, so he picked your button up. See? Then you'd get another button out a
n
d bang that up against the wall. But the soldiers buttons used to - oh, almost hit one another - before they'd give way. Same as a brass button. You almost had to touch the other one's button before it'd give in. Then - there was other - lots of other gam
e
s such as - cherry stones. Used to make a - get a bit of cardboard, make little holes in it, and mark it one, two, three, four, five and six. And then - you had to flick the cherry stone - through that little hole. And if you got the whole six right, you 
w
as the winner. If you got the cherry stone in - the six holes, you was the winner. Got nothing of course, it was just for fun. Then there was - kick can copper. You get a milk tin. And stand it in the centre of the road. And the - one boy's got to be the 
c
opper. You come along, see the milk tin standing in the road, give it a belting, kick it. And - we all slip - hiding behind somebody's - railings or brick wall or something and laughing our heads off at this boy 'cos he can't see nobody. He holler out, co
m
e out whoever you are, wherever you are come out. Or I'll put you under arrest. Well the first boy what - showed his face or made a move or anything like that, this - this chap - used to come after him, grab him and say, you're under arrest. Then of cours
e
 he'd have to be the copper then. Take over. Kick can copper we'd call it. That's one little game we used to play. Of course the biggest laugh of all was when we used to tie Nutbrown packets up and the firewood and - empty purse, even empty - padded purse
, handbag or anything like that you know. Tie it on a bit of black thread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't have a bicycle at that time I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I had a bicycle, yes. I used to get about on the bike. But - I used to do a lot of biking for mother, you know, get 
all over the place for mother. Especially - when she was - working, I used to go and meet her on me bike. Help her home with her - bit of shopping. And also once I remember - when one of my children was born, I don't know which one it was now - about 192 
-
 4 or '26, I think it was Peter, my son Peter, he's in the other room, he - she told me to go and get the midwife - nurse from Howards Road nursing home. That's in Plaistow. So - I dashed on me bike - and the nurse wasn't there. But the other nurse said -
 
I'll do me best to come. But if the other nurse - the real nurse whose - duty it was to come there - she said, I'll send her. Said, all right. So I come home on me bike, rode home as fast as I could, said to mum, the nurse won't be long mum. Well while I'
m talking to her the baby was born, and mother brought the baby into the world. She said, run, get that nurse quick as you can I said, all right mum. Well I went again on me bike, back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Howards Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} nursing home. And the nurse had just beat me to it, she'
d just started off as I got there. Yes. And she was on a bike. She was on a pushbike. Anyway, when I got back home the nurse was there. Oh it was my son Peter now I remember I think, 1926.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't go fishing as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. Oh I loved that
. Yes, oh I used to go fishing. I used to go Victoria Park. Do you know Victoria Park? I used to go there fishing. And swimming. I used to swim in Victoria Park, and - used to walk all the way from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} where I lived to Victoria Park. Fair old walk
. And either - take me rod with me, I'd either have a swim first or go fishing first. Wasn't big fish in Victoria Park, tiddlers and things like that. But - I used to enjoy that. And then I used to go to - what's the name of that place now - Wanstead Flat
s
 - and fish at Wanstead Flats. Catch some more fish there. Used to - either walk it or pushbike it. At Wasnstead Flats - just where the lake is, they had - sort of - miniature mountains of sand, we used to - cycle up these little mountains and ride down. 
And up the next one and ride down again. Used to be great fun that did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did you collect anything? Like some boys collect birds eggs, did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well, yes, I - I have done a bit of that, collecting birds eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 As a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I
 used to keep 'em and all, used to pick a - pin - get a pin and - make a little tiny hole in the egg then blow it. Blow the - egg out of the - the - the shell. And I used to save 'em up. I used to also catch birds. Wild birds, when I was a boy, yes. You w
as allowed to catch 'em them days. I had a trap cage made me. Well when I lived at k14 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - there was - piece of waste ground right opposite where I lived and there was also - a fence, big high fence, used to part the Bromley Gas Works - from - our road, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Well we used to hang our trap cages on this fence, 'cos - over the other side of the fence was all Bromley Gas Works, it was all - a couple of hundred of acres of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 wild grassland}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . Plenty of birds there, there was a few allotments there what th
e men - used to use. My father had an allotment over there - as years went on. And - I used to catch green birds. Greenfinches. Beautiful birds they are. Lovely yellow, more yellow than they are green. And I used to sell 'em to any young fellows what want
ed to buy 'em. Threepence a cock, and a penny the hen. Threepence a cock bird and penny a hen. And I used to make a few coppers when you sold them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you keep any pets, did you keep any birds or rabbits or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Never caught no r
abbits. No. Birds, I used to keep 'em. Well then - once I went with a fellow, he had nets, bird nets. You spread 'em out on the ground and you have to have call birds in the cage. Put the call birds round the net, outside the net of course, and - they'd w
h
istle the birds down and they'd - go into the net. As they settled into the net, you wait - for so many minutes until you've got a few more settled in the net, then - you pull the string, that releases the lever, and the nets come over like that, see, tra
p
s all the birds. So - some of the birds he didn't want. He gave me three skylarks one day. Caught three skylarks. He said, would you like them? I said, yes, I'll have 'em. So got 'em home, and I - I had a nice long cage, but it was a - a wire top, so I th
o
ught to myself, oh - skylarks - bob up and down you know, when they're flying they go straight up don't they? I'll put parchment on top of that cage, took the wires and - made a - a cage - a parchment top so the - bird kept bobbing up and down he wouldn't
 hurt his head. Mm. So I had - oh, as much as - twenty birds in the shop. Remember me telling you about the shop I used to live in at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. All round the walls there was birds. Anybody wanted to buy one they'd - come in and have a look at 'em. 'Til one 
day - there was a lady in green - she was - something to do with the - R.S.P.C.A.. Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and birds and things like that, something to do with birds I know. And - she'd been talking to neighbours and they said, yes, he catches 'e
m
, he catches 'em and - another boy catches 'em and - so she knocked at my door, and she said - I hear you've got wild birds, wild birds here. So I said, right. I said yes. She said, can I see 'em? I said, certainly you can. I was quite brave, I didn't kno
w
 what was the - the law was then, they'd just altered it you see. So she said - well you mustn't keep them no longer, she said, you must let 'em - let 'em all go. I said, what for? I caught them. I know you have, she said, but you mustn't keep 'em. Well, 
I
 said, it's no - I'm not doing anything wrong am I, I said, I'm - not cruel to 'em, I feed 'em well. Keep 'em well fed and watered. So she said, I'm sorry, but you'll have to let 'em go. Well, I said, I - I'll keep them, I said, I'll be selling some soon.
 She said, I'm - sorry, you'll have to let 'em go - today. She said, I'll be back again tomorrow morning and if they're not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 one, she said, I'll have to prosecute you. Oh well - I told me mum and dad about it. You'd better let them go then son. See, so I sa
id, all right. Took their advice and I let 'em all go. Then when the lady - in green, she had a green uniform on - I - what her name was I don't know, but - when she come the next morning she said - can I come in? I said, certainly. Mum don't mind. So she
 
looks at all the cages and found out that they was all empty, got anymore elsewhere? No. All the birds I've got are in here look, all empty cages now, I let 'em all go. Knowing I could get some more if I wanted. See? But - of course my brother-in-law, he 
g
ot to hear about it, he stopped - he wasn't me brother-in-law then, he was only a boy with me. Brother-in-law at the finish. And - he said, we'd better not catch no more then Jim, he said, we don't want to go to prison over 'em do we? I said, no. So anywa
y - I never caught no more. I finished catching birds.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was one of your main interests as a boy then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes, catching }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 birds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , and - larking about in the street, you know, playing kick can copper and - all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you play football in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. On this bit of field - what I'm just - trying to explain to you, where - parted the gas works from our houses - there was a fair sized bit of ground. There was one house, all on its own - and the - the back - the back of the house was 
facing the ground. If you know what I mean. Well we used to - we chalked on the wall a goal post. Fair size goal posts they were, and we had a proper - football, and we used to belt it, no boots on. Never wore boots, not even to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 kick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  a ball with, we used t
o belt this ball up against this wall. Well inside the house - just where the - ball used to hit the wall the lady'd have a - cups and saucers hanging up, and they'd all rattle, as the ball hit the wall they'd go ding dong ding dong ding. She used to come
 
after us. If you don't pack up playing football on that wall, she said, I'll tell the policeman on you. Anyway, one day - one Sunday morning we was playing there and out come the old boy, her husband. His name was - Mr Brown. Mr Brown said, now - last war
ning. If you don't pack it up, he said, I'll set about the bloody lot of you. Well, an old docky he was, tough old boy. So we didn't want no tinkering up with him so we - stopped playing football. Well we didn't stop actually, we stopped }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 kicking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  it up again
st the lady's wall, so that it wouldn't rattle her cups and saucers. We used to play football with no boots on. Yes. Yes. And there were stones and bit of glass and gawd knows what on - on the - on that field, but we never bothered about em. Just keep run
ning around.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you play cricket or any other games of that type?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, we played cricket on the same bit of ground, yes. Sometimes the ball would go over the fence, we'd have to - stand on one another's shoulders to get over the fence to pick the ball up again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 This would be all boys you were playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. All boys. Never played much with girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Not your own brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Me brother used to play with us when he was - before he went away to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose} 'soc - he went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to live with me Uncle Jack. He - he was very quick at figures my brother. You - reckon up, you sit there, the same as I have many a time, nine, eight, five, seven, four, two - twenty-nine, thirty-six, and he'd give me the answer, without no - w
riting 'em down. Yes. Very clever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So it was mostly boys of your own age really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, definitely all me own age, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Were there any children that you weren't allowed to play with, were you free to play with anyone that you wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, play with any boy if I - liked him and you know got on all right with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There was nobody that your mum said keep away from him
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. No, unless a - a strange boy come down the street. Some of the boys lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Tucker Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, tha
t was the next turning to ours. Some of them were a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 notorious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
. Daredevils you know. And they used to come down the street only to make mischief. Some of them my mother'd say, here, in, don't play with him. He's too rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I think you said something about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wellington Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} where your father was born, that they were a bit rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Rough there, yes, it was. It was a - the men used to go out and get drunk and set about their wives and children used to get work - whacked and all that sort of thing. But - I don't really know much about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wellington Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 except what I've seen occasionally when I've gone by that way. Seen a man having a fight with another man, and - two women perhaps tearing one another's hairs out their head.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you kept away from there did you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, I never used to - go down there much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't see the boys from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I never used to play with the boys down there. Not 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wellington Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. See they were so poor, they had nothing to play with, there was 
no amusement for the children there, and nothing for the parents. There's - all - well they were such small places, like rabbits hutches I used to call 'em. Very small places they were. The houses they lived in. Wasn't houses, like a bungalow. Rows and ro
ws of 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of jobs would their fathers be doing then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Mostly dockers. Dock workers. Some worked in Bromley - Gas Works where me father worked. Others would be coal - trimmers and coal heavers. Shovelling coal up for the - people to buy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Why do you think they were that worse off than your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well, their conditions of living -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were saying about their conditions being different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Different to - it was like - we lived in a - six roomed house you see, well them 
people only had one bedroom, one little kitchen. Very poorly - situated they were. They had no entertainment or no - nothing to - no wireless, no television or anything them days. And the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But I don't see why your family was better off, if they were 
working in the gas works too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - no, we - financially no, we was none better off than them, but we lived in a better atmosphere, we lived in a better place you know. Had more room to move. See what I mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But how could you afford a more expensive house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
It wasn't expensive, it was only - used to be - six shillings a week them days, then it went up to - eight, then ten then twelve. It was fourteen shillings when I left it - in 1937, fourteen shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you think it was more that they were spending their money on drink then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Definitely, yes. They was always drunk and disorderly. Always drunk and roll in about and interfering with other peoples - wives and things like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your mum and dad looked down on them a bit as being rough did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, not exactly, no, they didn't look down on 'em, they just - sympathized with 'em to think they was living in such poor - circumstances, poor ways of living. The people really were - happy go lucky people 
except perhaps when the -d man come home a bit drunk and then the wife'd set about him. Throw cups and saucers at him or something like that. Hit him with a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 
Brodhead}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there families like that down your road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No, was very friendly peopl
e. All the people where I lived, there was - except one person - she used to - have a row with anybody in the street, over the children. The children got in trouble and she'd stick up for her children naturally. And - whoever's child it was in - in the - 
row - would take it up as well and they used to have a fight, two women. And - one woman, she said - used old - hat pins, when she had that hat on, used to stick it in the other }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 perp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  - person. Keep sticking the hat pin in her. Oh that used to be cruel that 
did. Anyway - she had to - she had to give in at the finish 'cos the police come after for using a hat - pin. A long thing. About four or five inches long, the hat pin. Six inches long. She kept it on this hat to keep the hat on. That was the only two wom
en - well, the only woman I know that used to cause any trouble down the street. Down the road, it was called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But - apart from that most - people were friendly and helpful. When I - when I was out of work, when I was working and out of work - I us
ed to get about - thirty bob, two pound - and a bit from the assistance board - I used to get it on a Thursday, - and the peoples husbands wasn't working as well, apart from me, and those that were working used to knock at my door, wait for me to come alo
n
g. Knock at my door and say, is your wife in Jimmy? Yes. Tell her I want to see her a minute. Could you lend me five shillings Mrs Bushnell 'til my husband brings his wages home? And not only one - quite a bunch of 'em. Regular as clockwork they used to c
o
me - Thursday, directly I drew me Labour Exchange money they'd be at my door borrowing a few bob. Yes. So I said to the wife, there it won't last love, especially if they don't give you it back. So she said, oh they give it to me back. I said, yes, but I 
s
aid, while you're waiting for it you've got to suffer haven't you? I said, you cant get the things you want, not while you lend the money out. So - anyway, I - I made her stop it. I said, don't 'end no more. Tell 'em you can't afford it. And so she done t
hat. Broke her heart really, she didn't like turning 'em down but - same time she thought it best.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
But when you were a boy would you say that there was a big difference between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh definitely, yes. Craftsman was a - collar
 and tie man, but a labourer - rough old choker round his neck.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any craftsmen living in your street then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, several. Several men were craftsmen. Bricklayers. Two or three bricklayers, there was - joiner, carpenter - oh - got some men down the road had - apprenticeship for some sort of trade.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you would play with their boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, I played with their sons, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They weren't superior?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, they wasn't - oh no, never thought that - they were superior to me, not as children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But the father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
He might have done, yes, he was a bit proud of his - hisself but - go over the pub for a pint, play - game of darts. He'd be quite friendly - muck in with us. Although he had more money to spend than - most of the men. Yes, very friendly people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You know you were mentioning about these houses with sacks in the windows?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any in your road like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well there was a few, yes, a couple of - houses that - the hooligans used to come 
down and belt the window with a few bricks, and - they had some - animosity against the - the owner or - or person who lived in that house, for some reason or other. And so - they had to put a sack up or - a lump of cardboard or something like that to kee
p
 the draught out. Yes, several - houses were like that. But most of 'em - the houses with the sacks - was - in Bidder Street. Along Bidder Street, from - New Road where I lived, that's the last turning down Old Canning Town, to - Canning Town Station, Bid
der Street. They had scores and scores of - of - houses there with sacks up the window. When the Prince of Wales went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's where the Prince of Wales went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. He went down there to have a look at - and - they wanted him to - wanted him to go in this special house run by a - a council worker. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You mentioned Mr Caldori?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you go along any time of the day to get this soup?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes, go any time during the day. But most times - I went there - was during me dinner hour - from school. Two hours for dinner you see. I used to go - from - either one of the schools I used to go to in New - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName
}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose} school, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Hilda{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Road{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Gainsborough Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school - I used to run to Caldori's in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Rathbone Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. That is the market place today, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Rathbone Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. It's built up - better than what it used to be when the Marsh - was the - was the market place. But Mr Caldori, he lived in a - he had a shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Rathbone Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} before it really become a market. And we used - I used to 
go there - providing mother was - out working, scrubbing ships or whatever she may be dong. Minding babies or - giving birth to a baby or - I mean - a midwife to a baby. She used to give me a penny, mother did. If she was at home I used to have dinner wit
h
 her but - if she was going to be out she'd give me a penny - to go and get me dinner. I used to get a - a big bowl of soup, green pea soup. With onions - a few onions and carrots - and a slice of bread to go with it, off of Mr Caldori. And it was - quite
 sufficient to keep you going for the rest of the day until night time, you come home from school and - cut yourself a hunk of bread.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Some of the children went late at night did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. They used to go of a night time. Had their tea there. Mo
ther used to send me there - to get - a - a can - a half a gallon can - full of - pea soup. Especially for herself and dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Is that really all he sold?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, that's about all he sold, yes, it was - pea soup. He never sold nothing much else, only 
soup. Oh, cups of tea, yes, he'd sell a cup of tea, and biscuits, if you wanted a few biscuits he - in a tin he used to keep them, the biscuits. They wasn't like they are today, all wrapped up in cellophane paper aren't they. Yes, he had - he had biscuits
 
and cups of tea if you wanted them. People used to come in there just for a cup of tea and a biscuit but - oh that more or less that was his trade, pea soup. And he - he made sure he had - sufficient to last all day - for the children that used to call th
e
re and get their penn'orth of pea soup. And I used to go there quite a lot, get me penn'orth of pea soup for me dinner. And he was a wonderful old boy. As I said to him one day I said, Mr Caldori, I said, if I become rich in my lifetime, I said, I'll buy 
you a big coffee shop. Yes, very kind man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Going back to meals you said you usually ate up everything you had but what would happen if you left some food uneaten on the plate? Would your mum have minded?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - it's awkward question, 'cos I - I d
on't think you - I ever left anything on the plate. There was never enough. See what I mean? Oh if we'd - left any on the plate, she'd say - come on son, eat it up. I said, no mum I've had enough thank you. Whether I liked it or whether I didn't - she'd s
ay, eat it up son.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She wouldn't put it back there the next meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, no. Oh - yes she - yes she would, yes. If it was - say - turnips, parsnips, carrots - in with the dinner what she used to give us, give me - I didn't like turnips, and I ver
y seldom ate carrots - or - anything - in that way, carrots, parsnips - onions, I used to like dip plenty of bread in my soup. She'd - strain them off for me, specially for me 'cos I didn't like - but should she - drop a few out - on the plate, she'd put 
them back in the saucepan. She'd put them back in the saucepan, the turnips, the carrots and the parsnips and all that what she - boiled up. Because I used to get most of the vegetables from under the stall. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were sitting at the table could
 you bring a book or something along if you wanted to, or a toy to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. No. No, you - sat down to dinner, you had to eat that dinner, then you'd get up and do as you like, play, go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did they manage with the little ones that 
had to be fed, when they were babies, did they sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well more or less they had a - big high chair. And they sit in the high chair, and - mum used to feed 'em with a spoon. Or sometimes I did. Feed me brothers and sisters - with a little spoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If grown ups were talking did your mum and dad allow you to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. They said, you've got plenty of time to talk when they're finished. If - if there was anybody indoors that used to be talking while we were eating - we wasn't ri
ght to my father or me mother. They used to say, you can't speak with your mouth full. Eat your dinner and be quiet. Or eat your tea, whatever it may be. Be quiet. All right dad, all right mum. And we didn't have to say nothing. Never said - used to keep 
ourself quiet. If she was talking to any - neighbour or - whoever may pop in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If your father heard you swearing what would he say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh I - I should - get well told off that, he'd say, do you know you're swearing? -Am I dad? Yes you are. Don't let 
me hear you say that again. All right dad. But - if I swore - it wasn't a very bad swear word anyway - I used - always try and cut that out, the swearing. In - in front of me mother and father. Oh yes, I - I didn't like doing it meself I know but sometime
s it'd slip out you 'now, the talking -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Can you tell me about what a birthday was like then, did you do anything special on your birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. I'm afraid not. I'd have a card. Mum and dad used to - find me a card. Happy returns of the day. They might buy me a - penn'orth of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 stickjaw}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . Know what that is, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 stickjaw}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A sort of rock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, you know, very toffee - sort of sweet. When you started to - chew it it'd stick to your - teeth. Stickjaw. Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Could you have some friends in to tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pardon? Oh no, we could never afford anything like that. Oh no. No. Not when - while - while I was a boy. I did as I got older and went to work you know, I used to have - a few friends come in. And if any of me children's birthday I used to ge
t the other little kids come in and see 'em. Yes. On my - children's birthdays. When I was living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, 14 New Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about Christmas when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, we used to have a good Christmas. Well, best we could make it you know. Cl
imb up on a chair and put the - homemade paper - decorations for the ceiling. Mum used to go to Houndsditch, I put that in there, and buy - all sorts of things for Christmas. Paper chains. Some of the papers were just loose, you had to stick 'em yourself.
 
And we had a little pot of glue and - fold the paper round your fingers and then - stick that one and put another one in and stick that one and so you got a long string of em. Then - used to tack 'em all round the ceiling. And she used to buy - happy Chri
s
tmas to - everybody. God Bless our Home. A Merry Christmas to you all, and all sorts of things like - paper - bells. Something like that - that shape, you know, hang it up on; the ceiling. All sorts of things mum used to buy, and I used to stand - up - do
wn the Marsh - selling 'em. She used to go there specially for me to sell it again. She knows the shop - only I can't think of the name of it now. She knows - the - place where she used to get them, down Houndsditch. I think it - somewhere near 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Middlesex Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Houndsditch. Anyway, I - I was talking to her last Sunday when I was with her. I said, do you know - the shop - name of the shop where you used to buy them mottoes for Christmas? Yes. She did say it but now I've forgot it, I - it's gone out me memory.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were selling these just to get a bit of money then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, to make more money from what mother give for 'em. Yes. And - I had a - I made myself a tray, a wooden tray about as big as that table, used to hang on me chest with a bit of string r
ound it, and - I made a - got a hi - a small hinge, and underneath the table I put the hinge with a - broom handle on it so you could hold the tray out. And I used to stand outside a shop - seeing - a tailors shop named Segal, Mr Segal. He was a good old 
b
oy too. And - it - a grating - led from the pavement in front of his shop and it was always warm. And I - I blessed him for that because I used to stand on that and keep my feet warm, in all the heat - it wasn't very hot but just warm enough to keep me - 
from shivering. Yes, very nice. It was in wintertime used to sell 'em of course. Nothing in the summer, but - in the summertime, as the summer - spring come along, mum used to go to - Stratford Market. Old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stratford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you know. And - buy up - lettuce - onions
, beetroot - anything - she could get hold of cheaper, and - I made me barrow out of perambulator wheels. Four perambulator wheels with a long board, made into a box shape - a nice sheet of white paper on it, and used to take 'em up to - Barking Road, on 
the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Star Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Itled onto the Barking Road. And stand outside a grocery shop. Used to sell bird seed and tea, sugar and milk and things like that. That's where I used to get me bird seed from that shop to feed me birds when I used to catch 'em. An
d I used to sell out quite - as soon as sold everything I used to come home. Give mum the money.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's when you were still a schoolboy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, when I was at school, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Going back to Christmas, did you have any kind of games in the ho
me, family games
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes, we had postman's knock. I remember one game - had a sausage in a bowl, they blindfold me - or blind - not me particularly but - blindfold a - another boy or girl, say - you're in the sea, the ship's sinking. Grab - grab 
something you see floating about. You've jumped overboard, you've got to grab something you can see floating - something you can feel floating about. They'd put their hand in the big bowl and they grab this sausage, and scream. Aaah. Yes. And then - we'd 
h
ave a game at climbing under the table. If you could climb - over the table - under the table, and back on top again without touching the ground - without touching the floor, you was the winner. You might get a orange - or - something, you know, just for 
- doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would your mum and dad join in the games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, they used to love it, yes. They used to join in with us. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they play games at other times with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, often dad, when he was fit enough, when he was well enough, he u
sed to come over the - bit of ground where I used to - live and play cricket or - have a - have a game of football with us. But - after Mrs Brown come out and told - or Mr Brown - said he was going to set about the lot of us if we carried on kicking his -
 kicking the ball up against his wall, shaking his cups and saucers off the - shelf, he said, no, better pack that up Jim. He said, we mustn't disturb Mr Brown, he's a - hard working man. He was a dockey. Used to work hard them days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you ever have a sing song together in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. Oh yes, always - having a sing song. All the old songs we could think of. On the corner of my street there was a pub called the Dartmouth Arms, I've mentioned that before haven't I. And - this was when I
 was a man, or a grown up boy. Used to go in there, me and my dad used to go in there and have a - pint of bitter. That one pint of bitter, that'd last me all night. Me father never drunk a lot. He'd have a guiness or a - porter, glass of }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 porter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . But I use
d to play darts, and I was very clever at it too. And I used to give - if I won them, 'cos they days if you won a game of darts they used to buy you a drink. Don't - do it today, they play just for love today but them days - they used to buy you a drink i
f you won. So I used to give most of the beer I won away to the - old age pensioners what used to sit round the table. There used to be a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 long table}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  in front of the dartboard, they used to sit along there and - I said, your turn for the next drink pop. Say,
 all right Jim. See, if I won a game they had to give it to him. And if I won again I'd give it to the next bloke. Five of them there was, always - waited on somebody giving them a drink. All old age pensioners. Yes, we used to do all right at darts. Then
 
- we used to come out of the Dart - Dartmouth Arms, and the rest of the men what was in there, what about a song? Yes, I'm again. We'd stand outside the door, the guv'nor'd bolt the doors up, go in, leave us outside, and - we used to sing. Harmonize. Well
 
- if it was a - say Sunday dinnertime - perhaps the women had kept their babies - trying to get to sleep - that lived opposite the pub - oh, they night be wanting to do something else, and they had to come out, shut your bloody row up, you're keeping us a
l
l awake, keep my baby awake. Say all right missus, sorry. We'll lower our voices down. And we'd - sing a bit quieter. Still it wasn't satisfying - they still come out. You'll get this in a minute if you carry on, and - bottles - water or anything heavy yo
u
 know. Threaten to throw it at us. I said to one lady, don't throw that love whatever you do. If we duck it'll go through the guv'nor's window. Yes. But we used to have a - didn't get interfered with very much, occasionally that's all - when one woman tri
ed to get her baby to sleep and she couldn't because there was - singing going on outside. So - we used to have a good old song. And we used to enjoy it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you sing back at home too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Oh no, once I got home I used to - settle down a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But at Christmas say?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Saturday night you might all have a sing together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. Yes. I write a song meself once. Well just a chorus of a song. It goes, dear old mother, always kind and true, dear old - other I thin
k the world of you. When my friends have left me, when my friends - friends have departed - oh - when my friends have departed, there's only one good friend in the world and that's your dear mother, or something like that you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't have a piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I did in years -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Later on but not when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. No, not when I was a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Any other instrument?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Only a mouthorgan. I used to play a mouthorgan. I've still got one in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did anyone else in the family play anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Not a soul. None of my - brothers and sisters could play - nothing at all, only me. I used to - get on very well with the mouth organ. In there I think. But - we used to go hop picking. Yes. And I used to - life of the party, ho
p picking. Yes. Out come me mouth organ, we used to go round the local pub and - I used to play all Scotch jigs. Irish jigs and things like that and get 'em all chat - dancing away there. Yes. Then after - the pub closed we still carried on outside. Sit -
 I used to sit on the seat outside and - rattle away - a - a good tune, all the old ones and - Knees Up Mother Borwn and all that sort of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they do that back in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Yes. I was the life and soul of a - hop
pers party. Yes, think the world of me. I got to - make 'em dance and keep 'em happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Back at home were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well, we had a few books, yes. Robin Hood, Dick Turpin. That's why I went to see Dick Turpin's cave. I - I think I wrote that. Yes. Read a book about him, I thought I'd go and see it one of these days. Well they had - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 encyclopaedias}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
, all the history of the world and things like that. Oh we had several books. Dad was interested in books. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would he ever read aloud to you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well he has done I suppose but I can't - just can't remember what he was reading about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you remember him reading anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, he used to read to me, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And your mother used to read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Afraid not. She never had time. Always too busy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you have a newspaper as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Used to get the - the Ev - Star. A newspaper called the Star. Yes. Penny newspaper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Any other magazines or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, unless somebody give me some. 
I might call in a shop and - get dad's - tobacco and - shop keeper might say, interested in these son? Say, yes sir, yes, thank you very much. Oh yes, I'll have them. Take a magazine home, used to give me 'em. There used to be - Norton's - Norton's - groc
ery and tobacconist on the corner of New - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Used to give me magazines. Take home to read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Would you be taken out visiting with your mother and father visiting neighbours or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Didn't see much of the - the neighbours but we used t
o go and see our relations. Yes. My Aunt Bella, she lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dowl Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Used to go and see her. See me Uncle Tom, he lived in - in the next turning - what do you call - Flifton - Clifton Road, my Uncle Tom, me mother's brother. And me mother'
s sister. Used to go and see them. And they both died eventually, my Uncle Tom and his wife Aunt Alice, they both died. Left two lovely children. And - it's only just a little while ago I found out that - young Alice, their daughter - she died. Only left 
one now. Tommy. Young Tom. Where he is I haven't got a clue.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any other relations nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Afraid not, no. Just her brother and sister. My father's people all lived at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But mother had a - brother and a sister lived - lived
 in - Canning Town.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 If your mother was ill would one of those come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Well - her sister would come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Not a neighbour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, her sister used to come in and - do the work for her. Bella. Aunt Bella I used to call her. And her husband was a - a dockie. Well he wasn't really a dockie, he worked for Harland and - yes, Harland and Wolfe, he was a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 charge }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
and, down in the engine room, pulling the machinery to pieces - had to be repaired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's how you got one of your jobs later wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, he got me a job with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 The neighbours would help each other though when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh definitely, yes, they was very friendly to one another, neighbours. As I said, if - I come home on Thursday
 with me Labour Exchange money and they'd come in and say, Mrs Bushnell, can you lend me a dollar? Then perhaps - mum'd - my - wife in them days - she'd be the same, she'd go to them and say, I've run out of cash love, can you lend me some?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you remember your mum doing that when you were a boy though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes, mum - used to borrow money. But - not a lot mum, never - never - she could never - afford to pay it back. But tell you what she used to do, she used to wrap up a parcel and take it to t
he pawn shop. And them days there was a - lots of pawn shops. They was - they'd take anything in. Bedclothes or suits. Blankets. Anyway - mum used to wrap up a - do her washing, perhaps my shirt, dad's shirt - and - some of the childrens small things and 
- wrap - up a parcel and take it to the pawnshop and get a few coppers on it, to see her out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you remember bank holidays, going out on outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. I can tell you a story about that. Bank Holidays, mother used to go - for a brake ride, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 They}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 don Bois - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Epping Forest{\*\xmlclose}
 - Loughton, all them little - little country places. I don't know if you know them do you, Loughton. Well - she used to - there used to be a pub - in the same pub I've been telling you about, the Dartmouth ARMS on the corner of 
my turning, they used to organize the outing. And used to have a four horse brake. And - quite a big thing like, like a big bus. And the ladies used to get on it, climb up the step into the bus, into the brake. All sit down, start singing. Somebody with a
 concertina, wasn't any accordions about them days, used to have concertina. They used to play a few songs for 'em. So I used to run behind. I run - follow that - coach up - that brake up I mean, right 'til we got to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4467573\charrsid9644767 T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 heydon Bois or wherever they was going,
 Loughton, Epping Forest, and run all the way back again. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Amazing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, it is isn't it. Never used to get short winded. Keep running. I'd follow mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you ever go down to the seaside for the day then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. We used to 
go to - Southend. More or less it was Southend each time. If - we could afford it that is. If we had the money. I - I used to pushbike to Southend when I was a boy. All the way from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to Southend. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would your dad go too on these outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Poor old dad, no. He stopped at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He didn't come hop picking with you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, he never used to come hop picking with me - with mum. He'd come down for a - a visit, weekend visit. But he - he'd go back to work again when he was fit enough to go to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's the only holiday you had ever away from home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Hop picking was our annual holiday every years. Was mine. I didn't }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9186407\charrsid9644767 like picking hops. No. Used to m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
ake me hands itch. I used to get a rash, came in between me fingers, little white - blisters used to one up in me fingers. And the doctors put it down to the sulphur they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9186407\charrsid9644767 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
quirted on the hops to keep the files and all that off 'em. They used to reckon it was the sulphur in the hops that used to cause me to have - hop - they ca
lled it the hop itch. Hop rash. I remember once - my brother Bob, he was working - or he was living, with my Uncle Jack in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}, Walsash, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and - he come home. Mother was hop picking at the time when he come home. So he - found his way down
 to - Goudhurst - a country place called Goudhurst in Kent, and - on the Sunday - oh dad come with him, my father come with him, taking him back home again, taking Bob back home. Bob was a - a gentleman sort of chap you know, he wasn't a rough - and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3032294\charrsid9644767 tumble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 fellow like meself. Anyway, Bob took me for a walk in the woods, around the hedges, wood }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 netting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , blackberrying things like that. So I said to him - I said, what things are they Bob? He said they're - gipsy - gipsy berries or gipsy something. So I said, c
an you eat them? So he said, yes, of course you can, he said, they}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767  won't hurt you. So I said, well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  you know about them more - more than I do, I said, you living in the country with Uncle Jack. So he said, yes, they wouldn't hurt you if you ate them. So I s
aid, fair enough. So after they'd gone - perhaps Monday or Tuesday I was out - looking for birds, whistling so I could impersonate 'em. I used to sit on the bank you know, sit on the hedge, or hide meself in a wood and listen to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 birds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  so as I could - i
mpersonate 'em. They used to come almost down to me hand. I used to whistle to 'em. So - I see some berries growing on the hedge. And I picked 'em ate 'em. I didn't know what I was eating, I only thought that was something my brother said you could eat. A
ll right. Took a good few of 'em. All of a sudden I come over ill. And - I'd only ate deadly nightshade Poisoned me system. I was ill quite a long while. And - my father - he come back the next weekend, 'cos the doctor said I - I'd have to go home to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to go to hospital. So - dad come down, and - some good lady lent him - her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 perambulator}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
. I couldn't walk. I was too ill to walk. And he put me in the perambulator and wheeled me five mile - five mile, from Goudhurst hop farm, to the railway station. Goudh
urst railway station. And - we boarded the train. When we got in the train - I was definitely white, some lady in this coach - in the carriage, she said - you - is that your son mister? He - he said, yes ma'am. She said ani't he ill? He said, yes, he is, 
very ill. So she took off her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 fur coat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 - and wrapped it round me. And she said - that'll keep him warm 'til we get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} station. So of course I - thanked the lady for it, or - my father did, I was too ill to talk. Well - from there - from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} station he piggybacked me - to - the bus stop. The other side of the - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}London Bridge Road
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Then when we got to canning Town he piggy backed me home to his house. Two years I was layed up. I must have been about seven or eight
 then - years of age, when I was poisoned - when I poisoned meself. And - the doctor used to give me castor oil to drink. I never went in hospital with it, I was at home in bed all the time. But the doctor used to call on me quite a lot and he used to giv
e me castor oil to drink. To work it through me, see. Well down - we lived upstairs - in this particular house, number {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}eighteen New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, before we moved into fourteen. And - the lady downstairs, she used to pop up and see me while mum was out, and dad was 
out working. And she had a lovely daughter. Lovely girl she was. She was about the same age as meself, about - eight, seven or eight, nine, something like that. And she looked after me like a mother, that little girl. She used to sit and read books to me,
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 comics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 and - and - cowboy books and all that sort of thing. But eventually I said to her I said - will you marry me when I get old enough? She said, yes, I'll marry you Jimmy. I said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 good girl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . You'll keep your promise won't you? She said, yes. And I real
ly did love that girl. I did, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 honest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
, I fell in love with her. But most unfortunately - she died. Yes. She had something wrong with her. She died. By that time we'd moved out of - I got better and we moved out of eighteen into fourteen, the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your mother make any medicines, any sort of homemade medicines?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. She used to make up what you call licorice powder. I don't know if you've ever heard of it. That cleared our systems out, every night regular, before we went to bed, mum'd - mix up
 a big spoonful of licorice powder in a drop of hot water, say, here you are, drink that. Whether you liked it or whether you didn't you had to drink it. I used to get on all right with it though. Tastes like - what do you call that stuff now - you could 
b
uy a long stick of it, like a - something like a - a stick off a tree - off a - flower bush, and keep - chewing it, just like rag to chew, this stick, but it had a - a nice twang about it, licorice taste. You buy that. I used to buy it go to school and ch
e
w it. When I used to go to school I used to buy that. Apart from the stickjaw. I've got many a cane off the teacher for eating stickjaw. Not hard, just a tap you know. Took me sweets away from me. Oh, he says - I'd try and chew it up when the teacher wasn
'
t looking but I couldn't chew it, he'd see me chewing it, he'd say, what have you got there chewing, Bushnell? I'd say, stickjaw sir. Oh. Give it to me. Give him me stickjaw, he used to put it in his desk, say, right finish what you're eating and don't pu
t - don't eat no more, don't ever bring no more to school with you. Horrible stuff he said it was, horrible stuff. Couldn't speak with it. You go to speak, you - your mouth wouldn't let you, it'd stick - stick to your teeth. Stickjaw.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you went on this holiday did all the sisters come too then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, all my brothers and sisters, bar Bob, me oldest brother, he didn't. He didn't have to come with us. No. He was always down with Uncle Jack. He was with Uncle Jack until he was - fifteen. Then dad s
aid to mum I think we'll have Bob home, he said - he can go to work and fetch a few shillings in for us. So he did, so Bob come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He went away as early as that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh he was only a boy - about - six or seven or eight years of age. He went 
to school at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, Walsash I think it was. He went to school there. And he also become a - a clerk as years went on for Uncle Jack, reckon up the amount of - money needed and what was spent and all that. Very clever see was my brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was his first job then was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, yes. That was his first job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
So then he came back, what did he do, I thought he was a farm labourer at some point?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Well he - he - he - you could call him a farm labourer for uncle, but he was more or les
s - a - domestic man, he was - indoors all the time reckoning up - books and checking up figures and - then he - then he get a job in Bromley Gas Works, me father got him a job there. Not as he wanted it, my brother said you get me there dad, he said, I a
in't going to work hard, he said, I'm going to be in the office. Yes, so - yes, he got a job in the office. And he got on so well with it - that - they made him a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 laveman. Checking up the cubic feet of gas that come out of one holder - and - reckon up 
the cubic feet of gas that went in another holder, gas holder. They had a - a special little place that they called the valve house, well apart from the factory - in a - in this valve house along the - round the walls of the - little tables with - a sort 
o
f clock attached to it, in a glass - can - container then. Had a red fountain pen. And as the - gas holder - used to - release the gases, either out or in, so it'd register on this - the needle used to point - so many cubic feet, so many - so on. And it w
as my brother's job to reckon all that up. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He stayed at that job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
He stayed at that job, oh, 'til he retired. 1965. Yes, he had a good job. With me - I went in Bromley Gas Works and me father wouldn't - he wouldn't let me go in the Bromley Gas Works but - my brother Bob, he got me in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You just had a very short time there though didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I only had about three years. Two year - two years, two years. Yes. I think it was two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's before you were in the timber yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I left that - left the gas works. When I'm made redundant I went hop picking, picked up this pal name - Jack Fraser, and - Jack Cameron Fraser his full name, and I got - yes. Yes. And - we went to - the hop country, and when I com
e back from the hop country I brought Jack Frazer back with me and we went to Howards timber yard for a job. And we got the job. Jack being a big - hefty fellow - he - he got took on right away but - 'cos he said he was a tree feller, he could fell trees 
s
ee. He done it hopping. And - they took him on but they was very doubtful about me. But Jack said, well, he said, if you want me you take him and all. I was only a little shrimp to Jack. They said, go on, he don't look man enough for that sort of work. He
 said, ain't he? You give him a try, he said, he can do it. So of course they - took me on. Which I did do, I do do it. Yes. And then from there I went - the hardwoods, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} first to Poplar. Got a job there.
