{\*\xmlclose} then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - nothing really, never found much in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Jyde{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But - I used to like going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Hyde Park{\*\xmlclose}
 because it was a nice - river there, used to - stand and see the fish swimming about. Hundreds of 'em. But I - I was always bogging in case somebody dropped something or left something on a seat or something like that you know. But I never found much in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Hyde Park{\*\xmlclose}. I used to like going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Hyde Park{\*\xmlclose}
 because it was very - clean and cheerful and - something interesting about it. Seeing the ladies riding their horses up Rotten Row and things like that. I 
used to get on quite well up the City. Did I tell you when I picked up the half a sovereign? And - also the threepenny bit the lady gave me when I sat outside - Greenwich Gas works? Marvellous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What would you do on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh, what did I do on
 Sunday. Well, go to church. First thing I'd do was go to church as a boy. And I was well in - well in with the Parson, his name was Mr Gardner. He - he had been through the war, 1914/18 war, and he always give us a bag of sweets. As we came out the churc
h he'd give us a few sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 This was before the war you're talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, before the war, yes, 1910, eleven or twelve or something like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was that Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you have to wear different clothes on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well you put your best things on for then, yes. You'd smarten yourself up a bit. Crease your trousers or - put a clean shirt on as - mother - had one washed for you, which more or less she did - clean up for us. Polish your shoes, make sure y
our shoes were clean - if you had shoes to wear. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your mum and dad go to church or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Not - no, very seldom they went to church. No, very seldom. Mum used to go to church - occasionally. Like a christening - weddings, or - you know, peo
ple invite her to - being - could she be good mother to - their mother and all that, they - youngsters get married they say - let's have old Granny Pushman round. She used to be a wonderful midwife to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was there a club or anything attached to the church that you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, there was a - a club there. That's where I learnt to box. Mm hm. And the old parson - he - he had a - a special man used to come in a trainer. He used to train us how to box and - how to jump over the - hurdles and the iron bars and the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 dumbbells}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 and - skipping rope and things like that. And - also talk about the - traveling, gardening - and - oh used to talk - quite a lot about different things that was interesting them days - to us boys. And also - used to train us wel
l in the way of boxing. Yes. And - I used to put the gloves on and - three rounds with - some boy they pick out for me. And - without boasting I was very clever, I got quite clever at boxing. I used to win practically every fight I went in. Then we used t
o
 have a proper showman ship. That would be the hall for the public to come in and see us box. As my father said, be careful what you're doing son, he said. There's always somebody can hit harder than what you can. Yes. I said, I'll remember that dad. Same
 
as he said to me when I - riding me first motor bike - don't forget son, any bloody fool can go fast, but it takes a good man to stop. Yes. Yes, so - we - I used to get on quite well. As - as a boy I - I went to - I used to go to Sunday school regular eve
ry Sunday, and - I'd be playing out in the street before church time used to come and - tore me trousers right up the middle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you went in the girls clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, mum said, well don't - don't - don't cry, she said, I - I'll put a frock - pinafore on you, you can go as a girl. She said, don't \{BLANK\}
 I said, no - all right mum. Well playing about outside after the church service some - some of the boys recognized me, they said, it's old Jim, young Jimmy. Hat pin, go on, knock him out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you belong to the choir?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No, we didn't belong to the choir. I wouldn't go in for that. I didn't have a very good voice. I don't think the parson liked my voice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was there a sort of band of hope or a temperance club of some kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, 
we had a temperance - club or Band of Hope as you call it. We also had the Boy Scouts in the same hall. We used to go away to Epping Forest - or one of the - Loughton - knocking bottles off of trees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You enjoyed that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. I was a Boy Scout for a little while, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You joined the temperance club then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I don't remember much about the temperance club. Temperance society. I might have done, I - I ain't sure about that. But I know I joined the Boy Scouts. I used to be - I used to love climbing up the trees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they teach you to make fires and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, and taught - taught us how to cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's where you learnt to cook was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - helped to. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any other clubs you joined as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Not as I can remember. I was all too busy doing other things. Going up the City looking for things and - when my father had his allotment going I used to go over there and - help him out quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Going back to religion did you say grace at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, dad used to say a few works. Thank the Lord for what we're about to receive. A little bit more and I would be pleased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He actually said that did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. I used to laugh when he'd say that. He'd say to me, don't
 laugh, son, kits true. Thank the Lord for what - what we're about to receive. A little bit more I would be pleased. All right dad, I believe you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
You told me about how you used to pray, was it your mother who taught you to pray then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - she used to pray as well as me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you went to bed you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, she used to say a few prayers for me. And - the parson, he had more to do with it than anybody. He made - made me more religious.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't sit round in the family and say prayers as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. No. Only when we went to bed. Say a few - prayers and - it was chiefly God bless mum, God bless dad - you know - sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 This parson was quite an influence on you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. I used to go round to his
 - cottage, he had a cottage round the back of this church, and he used to - have a cupboard full of boots and shoes. He'd say, now Jimmy here's a job for you. Clean them white shoes and boots up. I used to - get the - blacking, used to go and get the bla
cking or - brown polish or whatever it may be, rub over his shoes. Rub 'em up and - he used to thank me, give me a few sweets. Sometimes he'd give me threepence or sixpence, whatever he could afford. Cleaning all his boots and shoes up for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't do that sort of job for anyone else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, no, no. No, just for him, just for the parson. Helped him do his garden, he had - little garden, very small. Go round and - trim up the - edges and the - he had a couple of gooseberries bushes, I used to -
 trim them up for him, you know, chip 'em down a bit. Yes, we used to get on quite well me and the parson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you remember a funeral in the family when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well the biggest one I remember is me own father when he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I meant when you were younger, when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - no - not - I can't remember going to any funerals, no. Only our Aunt Bella, and me Uncle Tom - Cannon. He's - my mother's name that was before she married dad, Cannon. I - I can't remember. Ever going t
o any funerals or anything like that. Because I was a lot older when they died. Oh yes there is, no, I was too old then. I was going to say - I had a little sister, name of Annie - Emmie. She died. Oh I must have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 about}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  - twenty-one, twenty-two when she died. I was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} anyway. Serving out in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She's one of the eight or was there another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
She was the ninth child, she was the youngest one, she died. She was the ninth child. Emmie her name was. Emma - really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you remember
 your father taking any interest in politics? When you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well yes, occasionally he'd talk to me about - different - politicians and - especially the council. He couldn't get on with anybody in the council he said. Remember him saying, - the
y're a lot of twisters. But what he talked about I don't know because - I wasn't interested in it myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't take an interest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No, I wasn't interested in that at all. Me mind was always on - what I could find - what - earn and what -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Not even by 1918 you weren't interested?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 1918, no, the war was on, and - I was interested in politics then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You don't know which party your father supported?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Labour party. He never - belong - believed in any other party, only the Lab
our party. And millions of fellows - husbands and wives in - West Ham - had been Labour all their -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 It started early there didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They had a Labour MP early there didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You remember him voting do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I used to go with him when he voted. In the school, go in the school to vote. I don't know the peoples names they - used to vote for. It was all Labour members I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would he go to meetings or do any canvassing or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. Never well enough to go. No. When he was well he was working, and when he got - come home from work he was - fagged out you know he was - doing nothing, only sit. Sit and read a book or - read a paper - newspaper. Have his tea and go to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your mother take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Fraid not, no. No. Things like that never worried her. Them days, all mothers. Nor me come to that. It - was not til I got - been in the army, then I began to realize - that politics was - something I should study. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
So when you were a boy quite a lot of London boys at that time used to go along and listen to the outdoor meetings and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You would do that would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. On the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Beckton Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - oppo
site Trinity church - used to be a - Labour party meetings, Communist meetings - and things like that. I used to stand there and listen, but - I - what they was talking about I hadn't got a clue, I - I wasn't interested. No. Dad used to come and all. He u
sed to come and hear 'em talk. Because I used to ask him, what - what's he mean dad, he said this and said that. I don't know, he said, they talk a lot of rubbish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your dad take any interest in football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Interested in football.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You used to go to the matches then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Used to go and see West Ham play. We had - before West Ham become - first - first, second or third, fourth division players, they used to play on the ground called Mem - Memorial - Memorial Grounds - near West Ham stat
ion. Huge lump of ground, big enough for three or four teams to play on. And - dad used to say, come and see West Ham. They - they didn't call themselves West Ham them days, they used to call theirself - Iron - Iron - Iron something - Ironworkers club, ir
onworkers - ship - ship builders they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Boilermakers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Weren't boiler makers. Iron - iron - iron and something, I can't - I - ut'll come to me in a minute.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Iron moulders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Thames Iron Works. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Thames
{\*\xmlclose} Iron Works. That's what they ca
lled theirself. And it was on the River Thames - where the factory was, that - that was in - Tidal Basin. Huge great big building it was, they used to build barges and small ships. They built the Thunderer. Ever heard of a ship called the Thunderer? Big b
attle ship. They built the Thunderer there. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Thames{\*\xmlclose}
 Ironside - workers. Where West Ham was originated from, and the Thurnderer was put to sea - in 19 - 1912, 13, something like that. I know I got a - a medal. What they call a - wasn't really a medal, it was 
a - a - engraved - thing - just telling you when the ship was launched. Can't think of the name of it now, anyway - some years went on when the Thunderer was - was sunk. Sunk by the enemy aircraft, or an enemy craft of some sort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was he interested in
 any other sports apart from football, what about the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 The what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Horse racing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, he was very interested in horse racing, yes. Yes, he - matter of fact I had a jolly good old fight over him. Fighting the - the bookmaker's runner
. Poor old dad he used to - stick his bills up every week, know what I mean, stick 'em up? Owed the money - to the bookmaker. He'd write out - one and six round about or - shilling each way, sixpence each way and - perhaps only threepence each way. The}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9186407\charrsid9644767 se}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  d
ays you used to do a penny bet, there was a threepenny bet, a sixpenny bet, anyway - I said to dad one day I said - coming for a drink dad? He said, got no money son. Oh don't be like that dad, I said, come on, let's go for a drink. He said, I've got no m
o
ney. I said, surely you've got enough for - one drink? He said, I haven't. I said, what have you done with it then? Oh, he said, I give it to old - Dick, the book - maker. So I said, cor, you silly old shap, I said, what did you want to do that for? I sai
d
 - go to work all the week, I said, and you come back with nothing. Come home with nothing, I said, at the end of the week you've got nothing to - enjoy yourself with? Give it all to the bookmaker. Oh, I said, I'll put a stop to that. No, he said, don't y
ou interfere with it son. I said, I'll go and see him. So I went up to this bookmaker - stand - stood on the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I said to him, Jack his name was, Jack. I said, Jack, I said, I've got a bone to pick with you mate. I said, from now on don't t
ake no more stick up bets from my dad. He said, what's that to do with you? I said, being as he's my father, I said, I've got the right to stand up by him ain't I? So he said, yeh. He said, it's nothing to do with you what he does with his money. I said i
t
 has got a lot to do with me. I said, my dad has to work all the work, works blooming hard, I said, and - all the week he's having a stick up bet with you, I said, come the end of the week he's got no money because he's got to give it all to you. Well, he
 
said - sometimes he's lucky and win a few bob. I said, yes, more or less he's unlucky though, don't get nothing back. Anyway I said, pack it up will you? I said, I'll go as far as to say if you don't pack it up I'll pack you up. He said, you will? I said,
 
yes, I certainly will. Hm, he looked me up and down as much as to say, oh he's easy meat. He said, when would you like to start? I said, next bet you take off my father, I said, I'll come and swipe you one right on the jaw. Oh - said, well we'll see about
 
that. So he had the audacity to come up to my door, knock at the door, he said to the old chap, got any bets? Dad said, yes, I'm just writing one out. I went for him. And I hurt him. I come to the door, I said, give that back to my father. Give it back to
 
him. He said, he wants me to put this on for him. I said, did he give you the money for it? He said, no. I said, well hold that one, and I hit him across the jaw. Knocked him right out in the road. I said, come on - I said. I don't take promises and - don
'
t keep 'em. So - had a good old fight. I won. I said if I hear - hear of you taking any more bets, I said, off my father, I said, you'll get a double dose. Yes. So he though he'd best not take them. So every time dad went up to him - to put a bet on the q
u
iet - no I ain't taking it Bob. Wouldn't take no more from me father. 'Course he nagged at me a lot dad did about it so I said, look dad, I said, it's no good beating about the bush mate, I said, if you go to work, I said, you want a few coppers in your p
ocket weekends so you can turn - with your mates and have a drink in a pub and talk about all things, all kinds of - I said, it don't go - I don't agree with that, I said, I - I'm not against you for having a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 gamble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  but only gamble when you've got money to 
spare. Don't gamble all the week and - you've got no money, you stick 'em up like you have been doing. They used to call it stick 'em up, you know, that means - on trust.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did he belong to any kind of savings clubs, sick club or something like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, he belonged to the - Gas Works Sick Club. And used to get a few coppers off of them when he was really ill. He was also }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 co-partner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  for the gas works. He was in partnership, he - he had so many shares, didn't have a lot. He wouldn't touch them sha
res though. When - when he died mother did, mother drew 'em all out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When he was ill and out of work did you get any money from -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You'd get a little from the sick club would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Me father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, when your father was out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's all the money }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 you\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  get or could you get any from charity or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, not very much. We used to get a - I think mother got a little from the - National Assistance Board - when he was very ill.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But that would be after the war wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. He wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He wasn't so ill before, you don't remember him being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. When - when he was - he was getting - he was always - on and off, practically every year - when a - rig
ht from a boy I can remember him - being ill in bed, bronchitis, asthma and that. But as years went on he got worse and worse. I don't know - I - I don't know where mother used to get any - money from other sources.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you ever remember any poor relief things before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, there was a poor relief - done in them days but - whether mother got anything from them I - I don't - I can't recall. I never used to ask her. I know she always found a couple of coppers - give me my penny for me - pea soup.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you have any pocket money actually as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Me? Only what I used to - earn meself. Sell the coke what dad used to sell. Used to bring up to him from the gas works, when I used to sell that. Used to go round the old neighbours and say, 
want any coke today Mrs? Yes son, give me a bag. And the next lady - going to gas works Jim? Yes. Bring me back a bag of coke. Yes ma'am. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your dad was able to have that free was he to sell then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. They used to bring it up to him in a big
 van, all in bags. Used to get fourteen pound of coke for a sixpence. It - it was up to him to sell it. And he sold it. Put the money in a - this little box what he had. And I used to help him. I used to go down help him to sell it. Lift it out for him, p
ut in the prams and boxes with - perambulator wheelbarrows and things like that. Children used to come for it. Just coke, nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were a boy did you go to any sort of theatres, music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, not as a boy I didn't. I used to go to the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Imperial{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Palace{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I think it's still there, it's a picture palace today. No, I used to go there and watch - even Charlie Chaplin, I see him up there once. In the Humming Birds of - little sketch called the Humming Birds, Charlie Chaplin 
was - throwing bananas on the stage and - the other comedian on the stage said, if you don't stop that I'll come up and thump your ear. He said, I'll come down and let you do it, so Charlie left the box where he was sitting in and - went down on the stage
 and slipped over a banana and - all that sort of tricks you know and - got a dump under the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 ear hole}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  and he went back in the box again, threw some more stuff on the stage. He was a comedian. He was just starting up then, Charlie Chaplin was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You went more as you grew a bit older you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh I used to go quite a lot more when I was older, yes. But - wasn't always I had the money to go to - see a - a music hall. Go to music hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you take a girl there then when you were a bit older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, I started counting my wife when I was fourteen. Fourteen years of age. Yes. We got - I got married when I was - eighteen. Just before I joined the - just after I joined the army I got married. I was called up in the army and I - I heard we was 
going to get drafted to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} as -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Ay? No. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. After the war. 1918. Yes. I didn't join the army 'til I was eighteen. I joined up in - October - no - July I was born - I was - eighteen, July 23rd I was eighteen, I joined th
e army - August. August - the eighteenth or something like that, I had to go in the army, I was called up. And - I was stationed at Aldershop, also Deep - Deepcut and Blackdown - training, then - during our training we heard we was trained to go to German
y
 - army of occupation on the mine, but - I said - I said to my wife when I see her, come down one day, I said, what about getting married love? I said, I can leave you half pay, you won't - starve. Because her mother was a - very cruel woman, my wife's mo
t
her. Used to half starve the poor girl. Never give her a decent meal. I said, you'd bet better off married to me love, I said, you'll have something to eat anyway. So - when I come home from - on leave one day, or a week's leave, I said, that's it, let's 
get married. So we got married in the same church I've been telling you about, Mickey Dalton's church, old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}
Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And - went back - went back. And the wife used to come down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aldershot{\*\xmlclose} to see. One day we went to Farnborough to see the first aeropla
ne. First - wasn't the first aeroplane, it was the first - twin }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 engine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  aeroplane. Double engine. And - as - as it took off it come down and crashed. I picked up - I went on the field, on the aerodrome, picked up lots of bits and pieces of that aeroplane, b
rought 'em home, had 'em for years. Gradually lots them. Nuts and bolts and bits of iron and - you know, aluminium. Anyway - me and the wife used to go up in the caves, Farborough had a - huge bank - and - loving couples go and dig - caves out for theirse
lf to squat in. And me and my missus find a cave we'd go and squat there. Yes. Yes. We used to sit there for a couple of hours or more until it was time for her to go back home. And I used to go back to me regiment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did you first meet her then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - we moved out of eighteen - into fourteen - New Road. Her mother moved into eighteen as we moved out. So my mother said to me - I think I've left me towel roller - on the door Jim, she said, will you go and get it? Yes mum. It was a - roller, you k
now, iron - a wooden roller and - two screws on the end to fit in a frame and you - put a towel round and round and round. Know what I mean? Something like a toilet roll. So I went and - knocked at the door and I went in, I said - Death her name was, Mrs 
D
eath. Mrs Death, I said, can I have mum's - towel roller off the door? She said, yes son, come in and get it. So I went in. And - my wife there - only a young girl, she looked up, oh I said, what a beauty. Live at first sight. Then we got chatting you kno
w of course it went - one thing led to another, I used to take her out and take her to the pictures and all that sort of thing. When I was fourteen.
