the wood up for the fire. And somehow or the other - a splinter of wood got in my ring and - showed it off me finger. 'Course it was all very broke, cut off by this - orderly, and it flew - somewhere in amongst the sand and stones. Well I was - hunting fo
r that for weeks and weeks and weeks. And every time - I thought to meself, if I see something sparkly and keep me eyes glued where I see that sparkling it might be my -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 ring}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . So I did for weeks and weeks and weeks I hung around that little spot while the su
n was shining, and looking and looking and - finally I see something glittering. I said, cor, stone the crows, me ring. I said - the first thing I'll do is have that joined. I never did. I don't know why, I - never had it joined. I should have done 'cos I
 
kept thinking to meself - I - I'll wear it - broke like it is I shall lose it again. Or if I go home with it on me finger and my wife sees that she'll say, we've parted we're parting, you've broken your ring. She'd be suspicious. Anyway I never - never ha
d it repaired. And - eventually I lost it. Lost it for good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you remember what you wore for the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Me army uniform. Yes, I was in uniform. I've got a picture of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What did she wear then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 She - she wore a blue - flowery dress. My wife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did she make it herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, she bought it. Yes. A - a friend made it for her. A friend made it for her but she had to pay for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Was it kind of kept a secret from you or did you know what she was going to wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I did
n't know what she was going to wear, and wouldn't care even if she ain't - what she wore. But - my uniform.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did she have any bridesmaids?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, she had two bridesmaids. Yes, she had a - one of my sisters was one, and - I think her sister, her you
ng sister was another one. Two bridesmaids, and - my best man was her - her brother. My wife's brother. He's dead now. Arthur Death his name was. Lived at Tilbury. Anyway - went off all right the wedding.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was all, there weren't sort of flower gi
rls or ushers or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they throw rice at you or things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Confetti. Yes. Not rice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did anyone give her a present as she left the church, sometimes they give people a shoe or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh they tired to tie a couple of old boots on the back of me - on - on me coat. We walked from the church home. And they tried to tie a couple of old boots on the back of me coat. Yes. I was only laughing, I didn't mind. Yes. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was th
ere any other sort of ragging the last day before you were married, in the army, did they play any tricks on you, the other soldiers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - they went upstairs in my bedroom and they - put a lot of - I don't know whether it was tin tacks or what they
 were, something very sharp, press buttons I think, press studs. I know when I got in bed I got oh - mm. I looked under the bed, I've heard of bells ringing under the bed. Never seen none there. But I got these tacks - or press studs, whatever they were i
n me bed. And there was also a - a - imitation of a worm - wiggled about like that you know. I said, soppy lot of devils, frightened the life out of my wife. That was when we went to bed. Yes. That was the first night I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 The last week with your soldier friends you didn't have a kind of stag party?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. Didn't even know - I didn't even know what a stag party meant. Not them days. No, I'm afraid that was out of the question, stag parties. Mm. I had nothing. I had no money to - have a 
- fling before I got married. Just cleaned me shoes and brushed me - army jacket down, put me Glengarry on nice and straight. Away I went to the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Had you been buying things to set up house though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. I had already - I already got me home room - me own room what - in }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, a boxroom, and - double size bed in it, and I made that into our home. That one - one room we used to sleep and eat in. Me and the wife. We had to go up a very short narrow - steps to get in the room. Had no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 banisters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 or anything like that so I fixed a rope up and helped to pull us up. Yes. The wife used to go downstairs and cook - help mum to cook the dinner, Sunday dinner, and - she'd dish it up down - downstairs and bring a plateful up to me. We'd eat it in our 
bedroom.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When you got married, on the day did you see her before the church service at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No, I never seen the wife not 'til after we - I met her in the church. All that day I never went to see her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Why do you think that people don't see each other like that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well just a suspicion I suppose that something fatal might happen. I don't know why. It was just a - a - an old - routine, you know - been ding it for donkey's and donkey's years now. They don't see one another not 'ti
l - they meet in church. I - I don't know why. It - it's really nothing in it to my mind - they could meet and have a good old laugh before they went into church, but - it's just a - a religious habit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you leave before the party had finished, did 
you go off or did you stay there 'til the end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, we stopped right to the end, yes, and went to bed. Yes. Next day we went to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Watford{\*\xmlclose}. To join my aunt, my mother's sister. We spent a week there with her. Had a nice time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 This church where you
 got married, had you carried on yourself going to that church after you'd left school or did you give it up really when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well when I was in the army of course I couldn't go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But before you joined the army I mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well I used to go there before I joined the army, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Even after leaving school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, yes, after I left school I used to pop down and - do my gymnastics and - do a bit of boxing. Yes. Oh yes. I was - well in with the - people that - run the church. But 
- I wasn't a very religious sort of fellow. I wasn't all that mad about it. As long as I was enjoying meself one way or the other I was happy. I don't think you know what I mean but - playing about with the other boys. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you carry on going to the club even when you were courting then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Not quite so much as I did when I - before I met my wife, before I - fourteen years of age. 'Cos I was working as I said and - all me time was wrapped up in - working and looking after the - the girl. I used 
to look after her. Oh yes, well - her poor old mother, she never had nothing to give her and - I used to find some means of feeding ourself. Going to a tea shop and have a cup of tea and a - cheese roll or something like that you know. Another time I'd ge
t
 her fish and chips. Carry 'em all the way home until I got in my house and then I used to sit down and have a bit of bread and butter and fish and chips. Oh well - I had to keep the wife well fed otherwise she'd have faded away. For what her mother could
 give her was - enough to keep a little puppy dog on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was she working at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
My wife? Yes, she had a job. She used to work at - oh I - I'll never forget that - it's - asbestos factory, in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Steveson Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, factory was. It runs - along the railway, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to Stratford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What did she do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
What was her job, I'm trying to think of the name of the factory. She was a - sorting out - sorting out something to do with the asbestos pipes, lagging. You know wh
en they're - covering a pipe over with lagging. They go round and round and round. Well then her job was to - sort out the right length and measurements
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I was interested by you saying how old the house was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 1815, about that time it was - built, yes. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}14 New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Old Canning Town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was it rather }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 decaying}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  then, the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was it what? Oh yes, yes. Mouldy as anything it was. Horrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Then you were saying about the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 elfer that kept you awake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, it was a - Telfer crane, ran ro
und on lines you know, the lines were fixed - sky high above the - building. And used to go round to the barges, were - the very fine coal they used to burn, very small coal, more dust than it was lumpy like, they used to go round and pick a grabful up an
d
 then take it round to the - wherever it had to be dropped. Different - furnaces. And as it went round and round the building so it used to screech and growl - groan, oh terrible noise it used to make, this crane. Or grab like, I called it a grab. Well th
at's what it was really, it was a grab to grab the coal up and - and while it was nicely closed up they used to travel round the building with it, drop it wherever they wanted to. The driver.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They didn't stop at night then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, used to be shift w
ork. Day and night. All day and all night, still keep coming. Yes. 'Course I didn't - being working all - or out of work whichever the case may be, I used to mooch around quite a lot, see what I could find or see what - if I could pick a job up somewhere,
 but - when I was out of work of course I couldn't hear it then, but - when I got home of a evening, sit and have me tea or whatever I could have to eat. This thing used to go round and round. Terrible noise.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you slept all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 We got used
 to it at the finish, yes, used to sleep. When we first - when I first - heard it I couldn't sleep a wink. More I used to sleep out in the open. Over the park. Over - Hermit Road Park, not far from where I lived. And sleep on the bench. And sleep there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 As a boy you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 As a young man. Yes, when I was married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They put it in, it wasn't there when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. No, it wasn't there when I was a boy. It was put in - in later years - oh I must have been about - twenty-two - whe
n they first started - rolling round the - electric light works. Electric light factory. And then they built two Telfer - like chimney pots, like flower pots to look at that - Telfers they call 'em, and - the water runs through them. Or water comes throug
h
 them into a - a kind of a big sieve and then the steam used to come up, from the hot water, what they make electricity with, and the steam - used to blow over to my garden - 'cos I only lived at the back of it like. And if the wind was in that direction 
I'd get steamed up. Damp all the house. House used to get terrible damp with this steam from the - you know, but - 'course as years went on we didn't take no notice of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When you were a boy and sort of playing around I suppose you got pretty mucky sometimes, did your mother mind when you got your clothes all messed up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When I got the what messed up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you got your clothes all dirty from playing as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your mother mind very much or not take much notice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. 
She never worried. Oh no, she never worried. She used to be glad of my help, when I used to go out - looking for different things. See what I could find. Yes. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
She didn't mind if you got all sort of dirty because of going out playing or something like that, she didn't worry about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, she never stopped me from going out playing. Oh no. 'Course Saturdays and Sundays - well, Sundays - I used to play more in the street and - than any other day 'cos I - mean I was at school - when I us
ed to come home from school I used to go - looking for anything I could find, to help me mother out. So - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did your father have any friends, any close friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh now, I can't remember. He had a - one mate used to come round and 
see him. And this mate was a moneylender. I used to go to his house. To borrow a few shillings for dad. Like for mother. What was his name? No, I - I can't remember the old gentleman's name. And he used to come round and - visit dad and have a chat with h
im. Whether it was business or - what it was I don't know but - I was never listening. I was always out somewhere. I used to see him come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He had workmates too he was friendly with did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, he had a couple of work mates, he'd - chat wit
h, especially if he went over the local - and had a chat with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But would they come into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Not a lot, no. Used to do most of his - conversing in the pub. In the Dartmouth Arms opposite where I lived. But - they never used to come in
 - to me house, a lot of them. Not as a boy, I can't - I wouldn't take all that much notice. Anyway I was never in, I was always out somewhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about your mother, did she have friends like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, she had several neighbours used to conve
rse with. Oh yes, she had several neighbours. But most of 'em were on the scrounge. Oh - see what they could borrow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would they borrow }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 food}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Tin of milk. Cupful of sugar. Two or three spoonfuls of tea. All things like that used to come in for. If we had it. But - wasn't always we had it to give 'em. But then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They'd help out if somebody was ill would they, the neighbours?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When I was a young man, when I was a - married like and - living - me mother had moved to eighteen New Road, left
 me with the shop - I used to be out of work, I'd go up to the Labour Exchange and draw me money, or - go to the relieving officer and - get what they call it by the kind - I don't know if you know what I mean, kind, it's - a grocery bill. You don't get t
h
e money, they just give you a grocery bill to go to the grocery shop and get tea, sugar and milk, bread and butter, whatever you want see. And - no sooner I got home with it the neighbours'd know - that - I was - just coming home with a few bob, they'd - 
b
e on me like a shot, well not me particularly, the wife - Mrs Bushnell, could you lend me a dollar, five shillings? Or two shillings or half a crown or anything like that, 'til me husband comes home with his wages? Or 'til me husband gets his RO money. La
bour Exchange money. But - we'd get it all back of course. But it used to leave us very - poor, when we want anything we couldn't get it 'cos we lent the money out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
But if there was somebody ill in the street one of the neighbours would help would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes, they'd be - oh, right there, right on the spot. The same as when me father died - there was a lady up the road - further up the street - her name was Mrs Lee, and - my sister Edie, the eldest one, that one up there, she - I was working
 at the time, I was working at Howard's timber yard, and she come running up the yard and asked the - foreman if I'd - come out and talk to her. Is it important? And she said, oh yes, very important. His dad's just died. So of course the foreman come up t
o
 me and told me what happened so I - got permission to go home. Well we trotted all the way home and - me and my sister and - 1930 that was, and when we got home of course - dad was - dad had died and this Mrs Lee was just - arranging his - features of hi
s
 face, you know, to make it look pleasant. She was a skilled woman in that way. She closed his eyes. Know what I mean? And - he looked - quite - natural when I see him. And I - popped upstairs quick and had a look at him. Of course it broke me heart. I wa
s quite upset about that, losing me dad. He was a good friend to me. Yes, he was. I never }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 forget}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  the time when he saved me a shilling a week. While I was in India.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were going to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. No, no, when I get married - I was m
arried then. I was married then, I got married in 1919 and I served in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 'til 1922. Three years. Well when I - had a letter once from - my wife, she said, dad is - still saving that shilling a week for you. I said, well that's a bit of luck, I'll have 
a - quite a bit to pick up when I get home. Mm. And he did, he saved me a shilling a week regular - well when - when he had the shilling to spare of course - sometimes he'd - miss a couple of weeks but then if - if he had any luck he'd make it up. Put a -
 two or three shillings away for me. Yes. So I - I was - well pleased when I got home from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. He said, here you are, I saved it up for you son. Tinful of money.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Going back to when you were younger, would your mother's friends pop in for a cup of tea? Would she give them a cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. Yes she was - they used to pop in to have a chat with mother and especially if they was in trouble or wanted a - their daughter seen to 'cos she was going to have a baby or anything like that, 'cos moth
er was very - intelligent in that way. Oh she was a skilled midwife I suppose in her time. But they all used to come in - any ladies couldn't afford a - well, couldn't do it theirself used to come in and get me mother. Got and see their daughter on confin
ement case you know. Yes. Quite -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But people would just drop in casually, they wouldn't have to be invited?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh, pull the string. Are you there Edie, they'd shout out. My mother's name was Edie. Edith. They'd pull a string that was attached to the
 door - into the lock - pull the string and then release the lock and - they'd open the door and walk in. Just shout out, are you there Edie? And mum'd say, yes, I'm here Come in. So they'd come in and have a chat. But - 'course I wasn't very interested -
 
in what they used to talk about. I was all on - me mind was all on other things you know. But - I know I've heard mother say - well give me half hour and I'll be round there. So I said - I used to say to her, what's up now mum? Oh Mrs so and so's daughter
's having a baby. Keep your eye on the place. Won't be long. All right luv.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Would there ever be a time in the evening when the group of friends or neighbours in the house and be singing or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Having a party? No. Couldn't afford parties them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Just a sing song though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I'm afraid not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You told me about outside the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh, singing outside a pub, yes. Yes. That - that'd be the end of the singing session. I'd come home and go - climb to bed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your father's friends were different from your mother's friends were they?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well, not a lot in it - just working people like ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I mean they didn't share friends, your mother had these women friends and your father had men friends, work mates?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There weren't any couples for instance that they were very friendly with?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Married couples?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That they used to see together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13920269\charrsid9644767 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 raid not, no. I - not as I can remember. No. Used to be - this moneylender ch
ap used to pop in and - see how dad was getting on, perhaps he wasted a bit off the - arrears or something. Or perhaps he wanted to know if dad wanted to borrow a few more bob. But - wish I could thin of the old chap's name. So many years ago now I forget
 it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Looking back to that time, people usually sort of think of different social classes don't they, when you look back to the time when you were a boy how did you think that the world was divided up like that, what classes did you think there were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Class distinction? Well - in a - in a sense - I kept wishing that - one day I'd be a rich man, to help me mother and father. Either through - work or - finding something, which is - would bring me a big reward. Like perhaps somebody lost their ear ring
s or something like that - or a gold ring or something like that. Well - anything like that what - what'd give me a reward. But - never did happen. And I - I used to say to meself, one day I'll be like him, especially if I was working - you know, walking 
u
p and down the Strand, up the West End of London - looking to see if I could find anything in the road, or whistling a taxi - helping - people with their luggage from Mark Lane station to Fenchurch Street station and the reverse, back from - Fenchurch Str
eet station to Mark Lane station and so on, I used to - say to meself, Gawd luv a duck, if I could only be like that gentleman there - nicely dressed, bowler hat, walking stick, gloves in his hand, cor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you thought there was a chance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did you know anyone ever who became rich who came from a background like your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I'm afraid not. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you thought there was a chance anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I always - looked for that chance myself of becoming - somebody - rich and famous, you know. But it never did happen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
What do you think that the main social classes were at that time? You said you were working people didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What were the other ones, what did you call them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Middle class people. And rich 
class people. See? There was the middle class like shopkeepers and - clerks, bankers and things like that. But - the rich class, you - I didn't see much of them unless I went up to the City of London, you know - whistling a taxi for them as they come out 
that hotel and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But no rich people in Canning Town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. No. The richest people was the shopkeepers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They were the most important people in the district where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Shopkeepers were, yes. Because you had to go shoppin
g and you spent your money in the shop so - once it had gone it had gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they mix with the ordinary working class people, the shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well some did and some didn't, some was too highbrow, some stuck up people you know - that thought the - they was well above our level. But - no, I can't remember now how they used to - treat the working class people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. They were very friendly of course, you know, do their utmost to help you in a sense. The same as for instance, I - I used to go - to the - Relieving Officer and get me - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 voucher}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 for - grocery, what they called kind, and - I'd take it to the shop called Rogesters in Bidder Street, Canning Town, and I could get the things - from there - according to amount the bill was, the kind
, and - he'd say, you sure you've got everything you want? I'd say, well I've go no more money. All right, leave it, I'll trust you. And he used to trust me with a extra pound of sugar or perhaps quarter of cheese or something like that you see, and - I p
a
id it back of course, when I got the next bill I used to - he'd take it off of that one. Yes. That's how we used to go on them days. Trust one another. The shopkeepers were very good in their - way you know, but - they wouldn't let you have too much. Make
 sure you could - pay back what you borrowed. If it went over the limit they'd say - sorry, can't let you have no more, you owe me a - lot now. 'Cos they'd reckon it up you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they make you stick to their own shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no, go anywhere you l
ike. No. And of course some shopkeepers were better than others. As I said, Rogester - Mr Rogester, he was a very - decent chap, he - very kind to us. He'd let us have - whatever extra we wanted - to make ends meet for the end of the week. Sugar, tea, mil
k
, butter, eggs - and - but some of the shopkeepers, they had to know you very very well - to trust you, same as Mr Rogester used to. And I never used to go anywhere else - particularly, only to Mr Rogester's shop because I knew - we got on well together, 
he'd let me have what I wanted and - he'd trust me. See? See what I mean? Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any employers in the district where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Any employers? What do you mean, the - the boss hisself? Yes. No. No, there was nobody like that where I lived. No. There was a couple of chaps, they were foremen - chargehands and things like that but - no - no bosses. Not where I lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did the foremen think themselves rather superior to the rest then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, they used to go out - dressed - a bit smart
er than what - me dad did, or I did come to that. They was quite cheerful chaps though - friendly. And if they knew you wasn't - rich enough to get a drink they'd say, come on, I'll treat you. I used to go and have a drink with 'em. To keep - friendly you
 know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
But do you think within the working class there were some people who thought themselves a bit superior to the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well they was in a sense, but very few. The same as I said - the - the foreman, the chargehand - anybody a little above -
 ourselves, they would be - a bit class distinction - sort of thing you know. But - I never found no fault with 'em. I - I - I always admired 'em for - what they done, what they was doing anyway. We had a chap named Mr Peters - or was it Peterson? No, Mr 
P
eters I think his name was, he was - a friend of dad's, and - he used to pop in and see dad now and again. Well when I was a boy of fourteen - this Mr Peters said, I'll get him a job dad, don't worry, I'll find him a job. He did, he got me a job in Tates'
s
 sugar refinery factory at Silvertown. And - although he was a very nice man he was very strict at work. And my job was to - to put sugar tanks ready to put the slices of sugar - in this tank, a tank about - eighteen inches long by nine inches wide - a bo
x
, won't call it tank, it's a box, and - all them little boxes I used to collect up as the - ladies and - gentleman in the factory used to put 'em in the boxes, count and so on you know, and I had to - put 'em on a barrow and wheel 'em into a great big mas
s
ive steam tank. And when I got all the shelves piled up with these - boxes of sugar, I used to shut the doors, turn the steam on, and - that used to - dry - the sugar more or less you know. 'Cos it was like mucky, wet. And I had to - after a certain time,
 
about a hour say, I used to open the doors again. Get - all the steam in me face, and - then I used to - take the boxes out, put 'em on the barrow and then take 'em back to - another department where they'd - tip 'em out and - go along an elevator where t
h
ey used to crush 'em up into powder like you buy it - in the shop. Well this - chap, Mr Peters - he said - when am I going - one morning he said, when are you going to get the sugar out? I said, I've only just put it in. He said, you're well behind your t
i
me. Anyway, we had a row over it. I said, well I can't do no better than I'm doing guv'nor. I was only a boy of fourteen. So he said, oh, you'll have to do better than that. Well, I said, if I can do any better I will, but - if I can't, well - just too ba
d
. I said, I'll do me best for you. So I couldn't do me best for him. He kept finding fault with me. Well apparently he had an - a relation about my age who wanted a job so he - got rid of me and put his - relation in in me place. That's what happened ther
e.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He was a chargehand was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, he was a chargehand, yes. Yes. He was my foreman really I think.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Were there other people that you worked with there, or were you really working by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, just by meself. I used to go and coll
ect the sugar - the boxes of sugar, slabs of sugar and then - put them on me barrow and take 'em into the steam tank. The steam tank used to dry 'em up into - very dry - and - put 'em back - take the boxes out, put 'em back on the barrow, wheel 'em to ano
ther department, and that - it got - tip 'em out on a elevator and they used to go - and they used to go like into a crusher, a - a machine which crushed the powder up - sugar up into a powder.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of hours did you have to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I think I w
as working from six to six. Six in the morning 'til six in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you get a half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, I don't think we did get any half days. Never worked Sundays. I worked Saturdays. Most Saturdays 'til Four o'clock I think you - you knocked a couple of hours off anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And no holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh dear no, nothing like that them days. No holiday with pay. Well I didn't know what a holiday was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Do you remember what they paid you in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, six shillings an hour. Six shill
ings a day - a week. Six shillings a week. Six shillings an hour, I'd have been a wealthy man wouldn't I.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you feel that was a fair wage at the time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well I was happy with it - really. But - I didn't know know different, whether it was a fair wage or whether it was a bad wage or a good wage or what, I - it - didn't worry me that part, as long as I got something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You gave it to your mum did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, mother always had that. Yes, she had all me wages. Same as when I worked up the City, as a - a - bookbinding place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was that the next job you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Next job I found, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did you get the next one then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh, I mooched around and - see an advertisement, I just went in the shop and asked the gentleman if he w
anted a - a boy. So he said - yes, he said - strong enough to push a barrow round? I said, all depends how big the barrow is. A little box - on two wheels you know, just like a little donkey cart. And it was - certain amount of books in it and I had to de
liver 'em all over the - City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, different offices you know, where they wanted the books. I used to get six shillings a week for doing that. And a penny if I was a good boy and done me work well. Extra penny a week. I used to give mother the six shi
llings and I used to keep the penny. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What hours did you have to work on that one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was from - half past seven in the morning 'til five in the evening.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And weekends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, no weekends. Oh Saturday - no, oh worked Saturday 'til t
welve o'clock. But - no Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What were the people you had to work with like there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - very friendly. I got a - stop there perhaps today I might have been still working there but - it didn't suit me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't like it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well
 it cost me more in boot leather than it - wearing boots out in galore I was walking round pushing this barrow along.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were by yourself most of the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Always by meself, yes, doing this job on the barrow. Taking books all round City of London, all on me own. No help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What was the boss like there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Very nice man, yes. Well - reasonable you know. Never took no liberties or any - never piled }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 too much}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  on me. Just give me a certain amount to do and - what he thought would be a fair day's work, and - I trotted to off to different offices - all over {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. That's how I got to know more about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Yes. I know all the alleys and streets and - avenues.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How long were you on that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 'Til I was fifteen. Yes, I was fifteen. Then 
from there I went to - Pheonix, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 sanitary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 engineers. On the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mark Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. You know where the Mirror - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 D}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
aily Mirror offices is - well - the Daily Mirror, they had a - a printing place underneath, in the basement sort of there and - Tom Pheonix - I thi
nk that was his name, Tom Pheonix, they had rooms up - further upstairs. I was there - working - when - the first zeppelin come over in 1914/18 war. It dropped a bomb on - Holborn Viaduct. And I was on top of the Mirror - Pheonix roof, right on - very top
 
of it, had a flat roof, and I was standing there watching. All of a sudden I see this bomb come down. Yes. I could hear it as well as see it. Bang. Yes. Blew great holes in the - Viaduct. You know Holborn Viaduct? Just there it dropped. Into Farrington - 
Farrington Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 It's not {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mark Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} by the Tower then, you said it was hear {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mark Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 but it's up near Holborn Viaduct?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where the Mirror is now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, what - what's that turning called then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I always think of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mark Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} as near the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Tower{\*\xmlclose} of London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, you're right, yes, that's right, yes. Now what was that turning called then? Oh I used to know it quite well. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You got that job through an advert did you or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, just - well I did see it advertised, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In the window you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
In - in this - in the firm's window, yes, a boy wanted. See? So I went in and made application. And - I remember the - this - \{BLANK\} Yes, he said - any good with a hammer and chisel? I said, yes sir, I can use a h
ammer and chisel. So he said - well I'll tell you what I want you to do. See all that timber stacked up at the side of the wall? I said, yes sir. He said I want you - to make a case - to put a sink - a sink what you use in the - in the - scullery - to was
h
 up in and things like that. So I said yes sir. He said, have you got a rule? I said, no sir. All right he said, want you to measure the sink - north, south, east and west of it, and then - make a case - to put the sink in. You'll find plenty of straw in 
the bin, if you pack it well with straw first and then put the sink in and stuff the straw }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2835894\charrsid9644767 round}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  it, he said, you know what to do don't you? I said, yes sir, I know what to do now you've told me. Well I did. And I made a success of the first - case I made. 
Plenty of nails and - pinchers and hammers. Barbed wire also to put round - not barbed wire - hoop wire you know, what do they call that wire? A falt wire, it goes round the case. Plenty of that, rolls of that there was. And of course I had to strip it of
f the roll and then - punch it with a little punch, make holes in it, and nail it to the case, make sure it didn't fall to bits. So I was there quite a long while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Making cases all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Making cases and putting - any - any sort of - san
itary engine - engineering - things, like - toilet sinks, big sinks they were. You know, what they used in the gentlemen's toilets, on the road. The - the trouble was getting them in the case. I used to lay 'em on the floor and build the case round 'em. A
nd they was very heavy to handle. Them - sinks - the toilet sinks were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were you working with anyone else there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, I had another young fellow with me, used to give me a hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What was he like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh he was a nice boy and - about the sa
me age as meself. But he was not - on the docile side, you know, he wasn't - he wasn't a sort of rough teara - chap like meself. He was more of a - what can I - say - very modest quiet sort of boy you know. He had no - go in him for - making things like I
 used to. Oh he used to give me help but - find what I wanted, get me some timber or - more nails or things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you didn't get really friendly with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, no. Once we knocked off work I never see him no more until the next morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you go out for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes, I used to go out to dinner. Remember going in a teashop and asking for - I only had eightpence - eightpence in me pocket, and I went in a caf\'e9 or teashop as you call it and, I said can I have a sardin
e sandwich please? So, shopkeeper said, certainly. So - I had this sardine sandwich, and when I asked him how much he wanted he said, tenpence. I said, good Lord, I said, I've only got eightpence. So he said, oh you come in here and you ask for this, that
 and the other, he said, and you haven't got no money to pay for it. He said, don't you ever come in here no more. I said, I won't. I said, can you trust me, I'll bring it in tomorrow. Never mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of hours did you have to work there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Eight o'clock - 'til five. In - Pheonix. Sanitary engineers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you have a short day on Saturday again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, twelve o'clock Saturdays. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you see much of the boss there really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh he used to come up - not the boss act
ually, it'd be the foreman. Mr - what's his name. Oh, can't think of his name, but I did mention it just now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Skinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, it wasn't that name. Yes, anyway - he used to come up and see how I was getting on and - give me further orders, what to m
ake and what not to make. Write 'em out on a list. He got - I got so good at it he used to - write out a list of what I had to make. I used to go down to the storeroom and - pick out - a decent size wash basin - if it was a wash basin, and - put a case ro
u
nd that. Or perhaps two or three wash basins going in one case. And I used to get a - a truck, and wheel it down to the - down the lift - go down the lift first to the - like - ground floor, and then - the carters used to come and take it away in their - 
lorry. Or horse cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You never saw the employer himself though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Only the foreman. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of wage was that, six bob still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I think I got eight shillings there. Eight shillings a week there. Yes, I'm sure I did, eight shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you like being indoors though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. I never was a boy for staying indoors. I used to get out as much as possible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you said you preferred the indoor job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes - well - beggars couldn't be choosers in the
m days, you know what I mean. You had to have a - indoor job or else nothing at all, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Less interesting though than walking round the town I should think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh it was, with me barrow of books. Yes, very interesting. I was - well educated in the
 - streets and roads and - the avenues and the alleys in the City of London. I could - can't remember the names of them all now but - o - I used to go to so many I - I just knew me way there and - that's all I worried, as long as I found it all right. Som
etimes I had to climb a lot of steps. Books in me arms. Get up to the office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You'd meet more people too, walking round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you get to know any sort of interesting characters like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well yes, often bumped in
to - somebody - who wanted a - parcel or attache case carried to a - hotel or station, railway station. Used to ask me if I'd put it on the - barrow. Me box - barrow like and - used to follow me along. I used to go out of me way sometimes to - so they'd -
 drop me a - sixpence or whatever they could afford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You'd get a bit extra then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Did I - ever tell you about the job I had at - Waterlow Brothers and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When does that come then? You were packing cases, what did you do next?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I went to Waterlow Brothers and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How old would you be then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Round about fifteen to - fifteen and a half, something like that. The - job I had to do was - go with a - a - pony cart - to take - bundles of pound notes to Somerset House
 - on the Embankment. And - my job was to - sit with the driver - you know, - sit with the driver, make sure - nothing happened - as an eye witness. And - we'd have a detective sitting in the van. First of all - a man }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 would come}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  down from the - printing fl
oor, down the lift, he would come to the - main door to go out to the street, and my driver - he used to back his horse right up against the door, and - the van, and then they - they'd count these bundles as they was thrown to me, I had to throw them to s
omebody else and somebody else - until they got into the van and then packed the - bundles in the van. Hundred and thousands of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 pounds worth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  of pound notes. We take 'em to - oh first of all a detective'd get inside the van, well whether he was a detective o
r not I - I should imagine he was - a security guard you know, and - he'd sit in the van and I'd sit with the driver. Off we'd go to Somerset House. The - the money then was - taken out, passed from one to the other, in bundles of two - two bundles were -
 
counted and checked and all that. As long as it corresponded with the amount what was put in as we took 'em out everything's all right. And they had to go there to be signed by - Bradbury. The gentleman named Bradbury. The old black and white pound notes,
 
remember - you don't suppose you remember them now. Once they were signatured by Mr Bradbury - then the note was value, otherwise it wasn't. We used to do that twice a day. In the meantime we'd - perhaps take - literature to different - offices, from the 
firm - of - of - Waterlow Brothers and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Certain times in the morning and certain times in the afternoon it was our delivery of pound notes to Somerset House. And then they got a - they done away with the van. And they got a - a small lorry - van. And
 this lorry was made by - a firm called Aldays and Onions. I don't suppose you've ever heard of that. Yes, that's - manufacturers of lorries and cars and that. So we - loaded the van up - with pound notes. Took 'em to Somerset House. On the way - first da
y
 - on the way to Somerset House, it starts to rain. Well as the driver went down the Embankment and he got near Somerset House he had to turn off to his right to get into the big gates, and - the thing skidded. We went round and round and round. So I - I'
m
 - I'm hanging on the driver's seat like, wow, what's happening here. Well we got - we got in all right, got rid of our load. Coming back - still raining - the driver put his foot on the brake 'cos a cyclist dodged in front of him, we skidded again. Matte
r
 of fact we hit the cyclist, knocked him over. He was a paper boy, he had a load of papers in the front on a - a tray in front of his bike. So the driver said to me, that won't do will it? I said, no, I said, crikey, I said, you'd kill somebody with that 
thing. So he said - well I'll report it. So when he got back to Waterlow's - office - he reported about the lorry skidding. They said all right, so they sent it back to Aldays and Onions in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Farringdon Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} I think the - the - the - garage was where they got
 the lorry from. And they - they said, all right, we'll - see what the trouble is. Well both tyres at the back - were studded with boot studs. You know the studs you used to put in your boots years ago? Knock 'em in with an - a hammer. Save your sole wear
i
ng out so quick. Well - they took - the - offside wheel, all the studs out of the offside wheel to see if it would improve it at all. Well instead of skidding - to the right, it skidded to the left. See? Wouldn't stop skidding even though there was one - 
w
heel free from studs. The next go, they took both - took the other wheel's studs out. Of course that made it a lot better, it never used to skid then. And - they were solid tyres. Wasn't balloon tyres like - there is today. And - apparently, they had a be
tter idea so - they invented the - balloon tyre, pumped up one. And - of course that was a lot better, wasn't so bumpy going along the road and - everything was merry and bright then. But after that I left.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you remember about the driver and so on, what sort of people they were?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
What the - the lorry driver? Oh yes. He was the same driver what was driving the horse. He learnt to drive. Of course he knew the job you see, so they didn't want to lose him so they learnt him to drive a - the lorry. 
And I was quite friendly with him, nice man. I remember him quite well, he had a - he always rolled his own cigarettes. He had a - Nutbrown - smoked Nutbrown. Oh it used to choke me when I started to ride with him, I didn't smoke meself, not them days. I 
d
id in a - a small way, have a fag now and again but I wasn't keen on it. But - he - he used to sit on his seat there puffing away and - cor. But he was a very friendly man, very - fatherly man, you know. Something like me own father, always - cheerful and
 chatty and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What did he like chatting about then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pardon? Oh - anything he - nothing in particular like, anything - weather or - the job. You know, perhaps he'd talk about his - own children, his sons and daughters and that. But nothing - particular. Nothing I can remember, that was very interesting.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And you said there was a detective or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. He was a - detective or security guard. He - he was - he used to get in - side the van and used to check the bundles as we took 'em out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you didn't get to know him in the same way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, I didn't know much about him. I never spoke to the fellow much. No. I was scared to in case he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any boys of your own age at that place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, only me. We only had th
e one van. Then we only had the one motor, until - perhaps - after I left there. From there I went to Woolwich Arsenal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You never met Mr Waterlow or whoever he was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no, never see none of them. No. No I never see none of them. I didn't know who they were. Waterlow Brothers and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. There were two Waterlow's one's Waterlow and Sons. One's Waterlow Brothers and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But I never see none of them people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you went to the Arsenal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did you get the job at the Arsenal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh, just - made application for it. That was in 19 - 16. I went to - Woolwich Arsenal. And - there - I was - I had a job given me as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 bandolier}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  inspector. Do you remember - in the 1914/18 war they wore bandoliers round their chest. Bullets. Yes. Ye
s. Well - there was thousands - millions of 'em - bandoliers - they was collected up in France by the troops and sent to - sent home - to the Woolwich Arsenal to be examined, and - used to have - hell of a long length of tables all girls and boys examinin
g the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 bandoliers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 - the bad - very bad ones they throw one way and - the good 'uns they'd throw another one - another way and - half bad and half good they'd throw another way and so on. Those what was repairable. And my job there was to collect the bandolie
rs up. Had to - roll 'em up, put about fifteen in a bundle. Fifty bandoliers in a bundle and then tie it with a bit of string, and - I'd come along - I used to have a friend with me, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 his}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  name was - Thomas Horn, we used to call him Blood, 'c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 s his face was 
red, very red. We nicknamed him Blood. He - he was a man what used to catch 'em, and I was the boy that used to throw 'em. Well he was only a boy hisself. I used to throw 'em to him and he used to catch 'em. Save me walking up and down with a armful, I us
ed to throw 'em to him. And - I - I remember having that job - oh, til I was eighteen. And - I joined the army then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What would you earn in the Arsenal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I was earning roughly about - twenty-five shillings a week. Thirty shilling a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was a big amount?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh, was, hell of a lot of money then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you work long hours there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Half past seven 'til - five. I think that was - or half past seven 'til six, I ain't sure which, half past seven 'til five.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Saturdays, yes. And Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A full day on Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, half a day Saturday and full day - on Sunday. Mm. Used to get extra for working Sunday. Mm. Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you give that all still to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Most of i
t I would, yes. Only keep a couple of shillings for meself. 'Cos - you could buy a hell of a lot of things for a couple of shillings them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You must have felt rich then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, oh I was - top of the world when I was working at Woolwich Arsenal
. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There was quite a big group of your own age then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh there was hundreds and thousands of young fellows - all about me own age. It - it was a shop called - the Hundred and One. And E Hundred and Eleven. Two shops. One had more girls than b
oys and the other one had more boys than girls. I remember when the - siren - it was the only siren they had there during the war, 1914/18 war, was in the Woolwich Arsenal. And - when that used to go - sound - used to all dash out and look for a - a place
 
for cover. We had no dugouts or anything like that in them days. And - my brother Bob was courting a young lady. And she worked in there. And - my brother was in the army. He was fighting, he was - four years older than me, so he was at the age - 1914 or 
1
5 to go to the war. So - he said to me one day he said - will you look after my girl for me? I said, sure I will Bob. Don't let no one interfere with her will you? I said, 'course not, no, I said, I'll - smash 'em up, I said, if they - touch her. I used t
o think a lot of this girl, meself, don't know about me brother. Although he never see her for ages - being in the army out in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. He was a - officers batman by the way, he was - well in. Good lad he was. So of course - he - left me to look after her. W
ell when the siren used to blow, me first job was to fly to - E Hundred and One, where the girls were, sort - Cissie, that was her name, Cissie out, come on luv. We used to go over to - Plumstead Common. Sit on the grass. Watching the - zeppelins. Wastchi
ng the guns. Yes. Oh yes, used to have some good fun. And - we'd all come home together in the train from Woolwich to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And going through - Silvertown tunnel, -there's a tunnel you had to go through, at - Silvertown - to get to Woolwich - they n
ever switched the light on in the carriage. And of course there was girls and boys in the carriage and used to - lark and giggle about this - that and the other and - when we got out the tunnel, the daylight come back - they used to laugh. I said, what ar
e
 you laughing at? Ah hah, you wouldn't be funny - wouldn't be so funny if you knew. I said, oh - oh - I used to get home, my mother'd say to me - what the dickens have you been up to? No mum, why. Look at your face. I'd look in the glass, see I'd - red li
pstick - yes. The girls in the dark, going through the tunnel - they'd paint their lips you know with that red lipstick and then give me a - banger. There'd be all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 lipstick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  - kisses on me face.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were quite a favourite were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, oh yes, I
 was a great boy with the girls. Well that particular girl I was but not all the girls. Although she had two mates always goes - always going about with these two young ladies, her mates. They used to be as bad as what Cissie did - give me a - a banger on
 
me cheek. Yes. And - I'd say when I got out the tunnel - I mean - next day I - I'd put 'em about it. Say, here - which one of you - young ladies give me a banger on me cheek? Not me. Oh yes it was, one out of you three. Well I didn't mind, it was only a -
 
joke you know when we went through the tunnel the next night I was going - put me hands up at me face. Then I'd find 'em on me forehead. Yes. Find em again on me forehead. Of course - it wasn't done going to work, it was done - coming home from work. Then
 it wouldn't make much difference, because I went in the - the Woolwich Arsenal with lipstick - kisses all over me face, never hear the last of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about during work, did you have time to talk at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Not with the girls, no. Oh no, never use
d to go in there unless the siren blew. You wasn't allowed to really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about the dinner hour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, if they went to dinner you could meet 'em dinner hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was there a canteen there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. There was a canteen in the - and we used
 to go in the canteen to have our dinner. And used to get chatting to the girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You'd make some new friends among the boys as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes. Yes. I remember saying to my mother one day, mum - would you like to make me a nice big custard to 
take to work? Said I - I - when they go for their afters, theirs sweets as I mean, at the canteen, they always seem to dish up a nice sort of custard. There's not enough of it to - give you a good fill you up. I said, if you make me a nice custard mum, I 
can - buy - the sweet and add a lot more custard to it. I said, and then I'll enjoy it better. She said, all right son. So she made me a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 pudding}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  basin full of custard and I had to take it to work in a cloth, red handkerchief. And - when I used to - c
all for me sweets, used to fetch 'em back and put 'em on the table and add this custard to them, all the boys say, you going to eat that lot Jim? Say yes. Here, don't be greedy, give us a bit. I had to share the - the rest of the custard I didn't want wit
h them. Yes, they enjoyed it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were you allowed to talk during working hours there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes. You could talk and a have a laugh, a chaff, yes. In the Woolwich Arsenal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A bit of a sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, you could sing a son if you wanted to. Yes. No restrictions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there chargehands around there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, they never said nothing to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They were quite friendly with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. The chargehand'd make sure that - the bundles what was - on the - wheelbarrow - to take to the - sorting - factory, that there was - that amount what he expects on - on the barrow. No - dishy-dashing, no - putting half on and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 half}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 off. It had to be the correct number. He'd just run his eye over them and say all right, away you go. That's all he used to do, the foreman, make sure we done our job properly you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Do you think having a full time job changed your relationship with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, not really. No. My sister - Edie, the one up there - I don't know where she worked now. No, I haven't got the faintest idea. She used to work I know, but where, can't remember. I know as she got older she worked - for Dicks's Asbestos. That was in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - I often wonder if that affected my wife, 'cos she worked there as well. Mm. Asbestos - powder. Fumes and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Edie was the one that you were fondest of as a boy was she, were you specially fond of one of your brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9186407\charrsid9644767 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  was my sister Edie. Oh yes. She was - my other mother really, she used to - do most of 
the - when mother wasn't at home, Edie was our mother. She used to look after us. Because she was three years older than me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did it change your attitude to life, being in work, did it make you feel different about life at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In a way, yes, it
 did. Well I used to love 'em. I couldn't do enough for 'em. If I could help 'em - in any way I used to be only too pleased to do that. Oh yes, I always helped me brothers and sisters. Mm. I still do. Excuse me. Well my sister was doing - 'cos I was away 
for three years. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you didn't have an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 apprenticeship}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  for any of the jobs that you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, but I tell you I nearly did fall in for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 apprenticeship}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 , while I was at Waterlow Brothers and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. My Uncle Tom, my mother's - sister's husband, he
 worked there, he was a printer. He was a foreman printer. And he said, I'll - give you a nice job Jim, he said. Be made for life. So I said, all right uncle. So he - put me in the printing shop. Got me into it rather, see the boss and he said, yes, certa
i
nly. Well I had a machine, only a small machine on a concrete base, had a round plate to it. Had a lever. Had a rack where they put all the paper on it. And had a - sort of a - a - a frame that used to pick up one sheet of paper at a time and - plonk onto
 
the round - plate, and I used to - push down the lever with one foot, pull the handle with a - me hand - right hand, and that used to print the bit of paper, and then they'd go - slide onto a - tray, somehow and - I had to do that all day long. Know what 
I
 mean? So I said, oh - I got so fed up with it I couldn't bear it no longer. So I said to my uncle, I said, here, find me another job uncle, I said, that's - too monotonous for me, I said, I can't - stick that. I can't - you know, it wasn't what I was - b
orn to - to do. I wanted to get about. All over the place. I - I was glued to that machine. Couldn't move. I had to do so many reams of - so many sheets of paper a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Looking back on it do you wish you'd done a different kind of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. So my
 uncle said, oh stick it, he said, it's a lovely job, he said, you won't be on it for long, he said, you'll go on a proper - machine, he said, one you don't have to - stamp your foot and pull the lever, he said. That's only a - get you - used to the print
i
ng. He said, you stick it. So I said, no, I'm afraid not uncle, I said, I can't stick that. So I'll have to leave. It was against me grain to stand in one position all day long, doing the same thing - all the time you know. And I said, no, I can't stick t
hat, I - I want to road, I want to get out. So - of course, he see that I couldn't be persuade so he let me go. And I left Waterlow Brothers and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Layton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 after that. I went to Woolwich Arsenal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But looking back on it do you have any regrets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I do, 
I - I very much regret it now. 'Cos - years afterwards, when I used to go my uncle got transferred from - \{BLANK\}
 Yes, my Uncle Tom, my - as I said he was my - mother's sister's husband - he was transferred from - Waterlow Brothers and Layton - from Upper 
Thames Street, to Watford. He was also given a place to live there, being a foreman printer. See? They built another big printing firm at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Watford{\*\xmlclose}. And - he was transferred to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Watford{\*\xmlclose}. And of course I never see much more of him oh for ages. Now and again I used to have a cycle ride from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Watford{\*\xmlclose}
 - specially to see him, and he used to say to me, yes, he said, how are you getting on? I said, all right, not bad uncle. You working? Yes, I'm working. Don't you wish you'd have still been in the prin
ting trade, he said, you'd have been - a wealthy man now, he said, look at the money I'm getting? I said, oh you were different to me, I said - he said, well I only started the same way as you, you would have started. He said, I had to do the same things 
a
s what you was doing. He said, and I built meself up, he said, which you could have done. So I said, yes, but, I said, I'm not born to be that way uncle, I can't be shut in, I don't like to be shut in no where, I like to be free, open, get out the place a
nd wander round and - see?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you belong to any trade union at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, not them days. No. There was no such thing as a - trade union. All that come about in about 192 -7, 28, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Not even in the Arsenal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, never belonged to a union, no, there was no union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
At that time did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests or that there was a difference of interest between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Never used to think of anything like that. Never worried 
me at all. I was getting me wages and that's all I was hoping - worried about. As long as I had enough money to - look after me poor old mum and - give me dad a few bob, and - have a couple of shillings for meself. No, I'd never think of union - or - anyt
hing in that way. I was always happy to get around and - long as I was working somewhere. But - I never belonged to a union, not 'til I - what years would that be, about - no, can't remember. 1930. Something like that. Yes. About 1930.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Going back to th
e time in the Arsenal, you said you were quite a favourite with the girls, can you remember any other girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, just them three - just them - three particular girls. My brother's young lady, and her two friends.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You didn't tell me about her friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well they was the girls who used to kiss me in the train. Yes, yes, they used to come home all together, three of 'em. They lived in Canning Town somewhere. Oh - Cissie, my brother's young lady, she only lived about five minutes walk from wher
e I lived. But I never used to see no more of her once she got home. I'd escort her - nearly up to her door, goodnight luv. Say, goodnight Jimmy. And - that was - the end of it see 'til - until the next morning. Used to meet one another again on the - Can
ning Town railway station go to Woolwich.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You never took girls out at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. There was no love - no - nothing like that. No. I - I never - well - never dawned on me to make love to any one of 'em, just fun, we used to have a laugh and
 a chaff, you know. Any love or sex or anything like that, I never give it a thought. No, nothing like that at all. It was just - laugh and joke and have fun with one another you know. And when we was over Plumstead Common when there was air raid on, the 
siren used to blow all clear we'd go back. See? And - used to go over Plumstead Common and sit on the grass, yes, just laugh and joke about you know. Tell funny stories or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You sound as if you really enjoyed that time in the Arsenal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes, it was great time in the Arsenal, yes. Yes, I was sorry to leave it. Yes, well of course I had to - join the army then, I was eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Going back to the different sort of social groups, were you brought up by your parents to treat the superior groups in different ways from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Superior groups? What kind of groups are they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Like the middle classes or the chargehands or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh - oh, I see what you mean. No, I'm afraid not, no. They - well as my d
ad used to say to me - if you work for a man work for him, don't play about. 'Cos this fellow - Pearce his name was, I've got his name now, Pearce, he was a foreman - at Tate and Lyles's who got me to do the steam boxes. Pearce. And I told my dad about hi
m
 once when I got home, he said, look son, he said, he's your foreman. Whatever he says you do. He said, and - don't say you can't do it because he knows you can. See? I said, it isn't the way he said it, dad, it's what he done, what he wanted me to do. I 
s
aid, I couldn't do the impossible. And it was impossible for me to do the things he asked me to do. See? Well he said, you keep trying, he said, and - be friendly with him. I said, I will dad. But - I couldn't stick it, I had to leave it. He wanted - he w
anted me to do - more than it was capable of me of doing. Know what I mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you were brought up to call some people sire and others not weren't you

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would you call a working class man sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Of course if I didn't k
now him. Yes, I'd call him sir. But if I knew him - say a - an ordinary workman or - chargehand or foreman - I'd just call him by his - Christian name, Dick, Tom, Harray or - Peter, whatever his name may be. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were you taught to raise your cap to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Where ladies were concerned. I used to follow what dad used to do. If dad met a lady coming down the street or anything, raise his hat, good morning or good afternoon or whatever it may be, I - I copied it from him. Yes, I kept
 that up oh for years. I still do. If I met any - if I meet some of these ladies, they are real - ladies that live around this district I always raise me hat to 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When you say a real lady, looking back to that time can you think of anybody you thought of as a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There was nobody you thought of as a real gentleman then either?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I never see many. The real gentlemen - the - the boss hisself or any of the - of his class, no, I'm afraid I didn't see much of 'em at all, not when I was a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would other boys call your dad sir for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. They call him Mr Bushnell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Even if they didn't know him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - if they knew me they'd know me dad. We was always together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You said you went to the Church of En
gland and I suppose some of the people were to the chapels in your part didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Did you notice any difference between the sort of people that would go to the church and the sort that would go to the chapels?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No. to me they w
as all Christian. They all believed in the one man - God. You could be - a Catholic, you could be a Protestant, you could be a Church of England or ever - whatever religion you belonged to - believed in. But you - there was only one God. He's God over eve
rybody. Don't mater what religion you belong to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There were Catholics in that part too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, there was - Catholics there, yes. There was a Catholic church in Canning Town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You don't remember any kind of dislike of Catholics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, not th
em days. Was all brotherly, sisterly, all friendly. No, we never had no bother at all. There was no - animosity with any of us. Where - whatever religion we thought - or what we believed in. Matter of fact I don't know as I believed in - well I didn't kno
w the real meaning of - of Christianity. Such as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 Catholics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 and protestants, Church of England people. We were all one, we - we never - we never used to argue over religion. Oh no, we - nothing like that ever happened when I was a boy. Quite friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 I
f there was somebody in the district that people disapproved of for some reason was there any way that they used to show it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What would they have been displeased about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Supposing there was a woman who was thought to be a bit sort of immoral or s
omething like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. Yes. No. You mean a prostitute? No, I'm afraid not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You don't remember ever seeing rough music used? Do you know what I mean?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 People with tin - pots and cans banging them outside a house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Christmas time. Christmas time used to - yes. Get a dustbin lid, or two dustbin lids and bang 'em together and make a lot of noise. Christmas time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was just for fun?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, that was just for fun, yes, nothing ever - nothing ever - a
s I know was - detrimental to what religion you belonged to or anything. No, I'm afraid not. I always enjoyed my life and - I never - used to ask people what religion they - belonged to or - if they was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 Catholics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  or protestants, it never dawned on me to ask them that effect, never worried me.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
There sometimes might be somebody in a street that people thought were not behaving as they should and they'd get angry about it. You don't remember anything like that happening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, not there. I only had o
ne person in mind, that's my - aunt - my mother's brother's wife. Aunt - what was her name - been dead years now. She used to be very hot headed - you - hardly say a word to her, if it was offensive, she'd stick a hat pin in you. If she had a hat on, and 
a
 long - hat - pin needle, she'd take it out of her hat - stick it in you. Oh she was wicked woman that way. And what - what the arguments and rows were all about I don't know, sometimes she'd attack my mother - over children I suppose. But - I couldn't sa
y why they used to row and fight one another like that. But I know - she was a very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 vigorous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  woman, she was very - spiteful, very - oh, I don't know how to describe her. The least little thing said she'd want to have a fight with you. And she'd get a woman 
by the hair and tug away at it. Not only my mother she used to attack, a lot of other women down the street. If her children were - you know, in squabbles. Rowing with one another. Well - I can't remember her name now. Dolly. Dolly. Her name was Dolly Can
n
on. My - mother's brothers name, Cannon. A very spiteful woman she was. But it was nothing - what you just asked me. Religion. Nothing like that. She never used to go to church. Dolly, she never went to church. More or less it was over children squabbling
 with one another, you know, perhaps her - her little boy Tommy would come in with a black ye and she'd want to know who done that and oh - get her hat pin out and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When we were talking about the most important people, would you say that the parson was one of the most important people in the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh definitely he was, yes. He was a - a real gentleman. Most - parsons were. Oh yes, he's wonderful old gentleman. Well as a matter of fact I like all parsons. I - I believe in that sort of thing. M
r Gardner, he was the parson at - when I was a boy, in Canning Town, used to call it - Mickey Dalton's, the church itself, used to call it Mickey Dalton's 'cos - years before I was born - a gentleman named - parson named Mickey Dalton was - in charge of i
t like. But of course he died or transferred some - to another church, I ain't sure which, but - then on come Mr Gardner. He - he was an officer in the army during the 1914/18 war. Preaching for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ar - the troops like you know, and I first met him, when 
I was a boy - I used to clean his boots and shoes for him. Yes. Oh I was - game enough to do - anything like that for the parson. Yes, very fine gentleman I thought he was. And he was a very tall man, six foot four, something like that. He used to like to
 do a bit of boxing and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's how you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. They had a - a mission hall, you know, the other side of the church. And a - big room, go in there and do gymnastics and - skipping, jumping, down the chute, down the - vault - over the
 horse, if you know what I mean, over the horse, and - all sorts of - athletic games we used to play. Then put the gloves on and have a box, several boys and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were there any schoolteachers living in the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. Not in my district. Oh, low
ered their dignity to live where I was living. Yes. No, they all lived at Leytonstone or - Leyton, or Stratford or somewhere over there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Before you went to school had you already learnt anything like counting or the alphabet your parents had taught you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I'm afraid not. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were they very interested in what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, yes. My - my best - what I can remember now is - sketching, painting. Drawing things. I was very clever at that at school, I used to get more mark
s for that than I did anything else. As regards to spelling well that - I lost all me education when I was poisoned eating - berries. But - I was very interested in sketching and painting. You put an article in front of me and said now I want you to paint
 that, see I'd - paint it so you could see what it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were taught that at school were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, taught that at school and I used to get on very well with that at school. And when I used to come home - I used to say to mum, oh I got a lot of
 marks today mum for painting. Say, oh well, paint that then. Put say that - thing there in front of me, say, here you are, move yourself and paint that. So I used to get me paints out, in the tin. I used to love painting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's what you really liked about school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you like school as a whole?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh well I used to love school meself. Yes. Yes. And I was very - oh I was quite a - intelligent boy, at school - in a way, you know, I wasn't - all that educated but - I - I 
used to - get on very well with the teachers. Yes. Very well indeed. Yes. I used to go out with 'em a lot. My teacher, his name was Mr Barton - when I was at Gainsborough Road school - he - used to take the best boys in his class to - Theydon Bois, Epping
 Forest - and places like that for a day's outing, and - he'd stand bottles up on - on a tree trunk, knock 'em down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You were married at St Gabriel's church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 St Gabriel's church, that's the one I've been telling you about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 April 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. It was called Mickey Dalton's in the first place. But then they altered it to - St Gabriel's 'course when {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Gardner{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 took over, that's his name up there isn't it, Mr Gardner? Or would it be that other - parson. Sweetning - Sweetning. He was another parson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your wife's father was a labourer then it says?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pardon? Yes, yes. Dock labourer he was. He's intelligent, trustworthy - do his utmost to please him - his employer. That's what it says.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was a certificate written by the headmaster?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Headmaster, yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You must be pleased with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. But where it is now I ain't got a clue.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That would be when you were fourteen you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When I left school at fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How old were you when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Wh
en I started school? Oh I must have gone to school when I was five. Five years of age. I remained at school for quite a number of years until I - poisoned meself, eating blackber - deadly nightshade. And - had three years away from school then. Three year
s
 away from school. And - I - I left in standard - left in standard four I think it was, and - I went back to school again, I remember going up to the headmaster - and he said - how do you spell cat? I said K_A_T. Well I never. Not there. Aye? Hope so. And
 - he would do his utmost to please his employer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They were all board schools you went to, not church schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Elementary schools, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And they were all mixed, boys and girls were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. Boys were in one department, girls in an
other. Yes. Oh no, not them days. Boys were boys and girls were girls and - the girls had a different school altogether to us. At the same school but I mean different departments you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Talking about the teachers, what sort of things do you think t
hey thought were most important in life, what did they emphasise in ways of behaving not just lessons? Do you know what I mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well you'd have lectures, used to have - the teacher would give you a - some definition of how to - greet people, to - say yes sir where it was necessary - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 
madam}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
, if it was a lady. Oh we used to have several - good - talks - the teachers give us - some idea of how to - go about life - in a respectable way you know. That's all, I - I can't remember much about it. Not now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did they emphasise being punctual?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, had to be punctual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Tidy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No fighting. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What about ways of talking, did they try and correct the way you talked?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No. No. Oh occasionally he might say - say - as a boy I might sa
y, you fink I'm mad? He'd say, no Bushnell, you've got it wrong there, you don't fink, you think. The. Poke your tongue out and say it. I can remember him saying that to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 They were all boys very much like yourself, same kind of background?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Ve
ry - all the same, yes. All lived in the same class. All lived in the same way of - none - none of us was rich boys, none of us was - mothers and father were well to do or anything like that, there was - oh better off than meself, they - we were all about
 the same. You know, got nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 There weren't any very neglected children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. If there was a child neglected of course the authorities'd clamp down on the parents then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you don't remember children who were very poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Or came to school in rags or something like that, there weren't children who were left out of things, rather different than the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, I see what you mean. Well - there was one or two now and again used to come with their - backside hanging ou
t - the shirt hanging out their backside and all that. But the teacher used to say to 'em now look son, you go home and get your mum to sew that up for you. And he'd talk - to 'em in a kindly way that - the boy would come back the next day with his - trou
s
ers sewn up. Yes. But - some of the boys were - very rough. They used to - get tron up for no reason at all, you know what I mean. Same as they did when I was a boy going to church that time. They ripped me up. See? Very rough lot of boys some of 'em were
. But - I was as tough as them if I wanted to be, but - I always seemed to draw a line and say, oh well, they don't know what - they're doing of, they're - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did the teachers behave differently to those rather rough children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, he woul
d. He'd - be more firm, more strict with them than he would - say - a fellow like meself. He knew he could trust me, if he couldn't trust them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You said there was one time when the teacher bought you a shirt wasn't there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Collar. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Can you tell me what happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. I used to go to school with a muffler. A - a scarf round me neck you know. Only in the cold weather. In the warm weather like we're having now used to have no collar at all, just - loose neck. And - we'd already be
en given boots by the - Raggedy school union - shoes or boots, whatever you wanted. And - I come to school one day and the - teacher said to me - you don't look smart at all his morning Bushnell, haven't you got a tie you can put on? I said, tie sir, no I
'
m afraid I haven't. I said, I ain't got a collar neither. So he said, well - I'll give you sixpence, he said, you go to Lewis drapery shop, buy yourself a collar, he said, and - find yourself a tie, ask your dad if he'll let you have one - one of his old 
'
uns. Said, yes. And he said, and come to school with a nice clean collar on and a tie. Very good sir. I gets home and tells me mother. Gives her the sixpence. God bless you, she said. Wonderful thing. She said, I know what we'll do. On the corner of where
 
I lived at New Road, Canning Town, there was a shop called Nortons, grocery shop, they sold all sorts of knickknacks like that - collars and things but - they never had a rubber collar, what the teacher wanted me to buy. A rubber collar. You could wash it
.
 So mother give me a penny, she said, go to Nortons shop and get yourself a paper collar. I said, very good mum. I went to Norton's shop, I said, can I have a paper collar Mr Norton? He said, yes son. So he give me a penny paper collar. There, nice and cl
ean and neat. So - dad hadn't got a tie, so mum got an old blue skirt and - cut a bit with the scissors, and - fitted it so it looked like a tie. See? Anyway - I go to school }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 next morning}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . Ah, said Mr Barton - you look smashing - this morning Bushness, he s
aid, you look quite a gentleman. Thank you sir. Now you keep like that. I said, very - very good sir, I will. Well as the days went on I used to muck about a bit you know, got me collar all dirty and - I say I had a bit of rubber, used to rub the dirty ma
r
ks out with a rubber, well doing that so many times - I rubbed holes in the collar and it - got creased up all over the place. So teacher said to me, he said, your collar's in a filthy state Bushnell, he said. I said - yes sir. He said - let me have a loo
k
 at that collar? And when he looked at it he said, it's made of paper. Yes sir. He said, why didn't you buy yourself a sixpenny rubber collar as I told you to? Well - I said, I'm sorry sir but me mum wanted a few coppers so I let her have it. Oh. Well he 
s
aid, you come back tomorrow morning with another nice neat collar on or - otherwise, he said, I'll give you the stick. He said, you deserve caning. So I said, very good sir. So I gets home, tells me mum. got another penny mum? And of course I got another 
paper collar. And that lasted me for two or three weeks. As long as I keep it clean. And the same tie made out of a bit of a skirt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would he have done that for other boys do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, he would have done it to other boys if they - you know, 
worthy of it. I - I don't know whether I was worthy of it or not, I used to take a chance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You never went to evening classes after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No I'm afraid not. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you have a chance to go on? You couldn't have stayed on if you'd 
wanted to after fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No, I'm afraid that - no, that was well out of the question 'cos I was a ro
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
mer. I liked to get out and about, see what I could find to help me mum and dad, that's all my ambition was, and - evening classes, no, I - I - I ne
ver had time for that, the minute I found me first job, you see, I used to come home of a night time, have me tea then go out in the street and played. You want to hear the story from beginning to end?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How you sent to Porstmouth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Beginning to e
nd. Take about hour. All right. Well year 1924. I hadn't been out the army long, 1922. Well at the end of 1922, nearly 1923. When - I'd been out all morning - I was up very early and looking for work, couldn't find nothing. So on me way back, I used to go
 to Silvertown and Woolwich - in amongst the docks, to see if I could pick up a job. On me way back I - I never found no work but anyhow - there was a lorry going by. Well he happened to be going slow so I jumped on the back of it. And - he went - up to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 station and over Poplar bridge, the iron bridge they used to call it. And he - went on to Aldgate, I'm still sitting on the back. I hadn't a clue where he was going. I thought to meself, well - I might as well have a - day out - somewhere. So I s
at on the back of the lorry. And - had me eyes glued to the ground in case I see any money laying on - on the floor you know, on the ground, like sometimes I used to get in the City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So this lorry took me right to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Kingston{\*\xmlclose}, no - not {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Kingston{\*\xmlclose} - oh - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Guildford{\*\xmlclose}. Was it {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}? No it wasn't, I - I was right in the first place. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Kingston{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Yes. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}'s further on. We pause in a - yard there and the lorry driver did and I jumped off. Waved to him, thank you. Where I was I hadn't got a clue, I'd nev
er been there before in me life see. So on the corner of the big wide road at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Kingston{\*\xmlclose} there was a - board marked - on the wall - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} road. To {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}, arrow pointing towards {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I thought to meself, cor strewth. If I could only get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Well in the meantime my brother Bob - is working for my uncle Jack. He's a farmer, my Uncle Jack. He grows strawberries, blackcurrants, redcurrants and whatever. So I thought to myself, if I can only get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} my Uncle Jack might fix me up like he had me brother Bob. Right. I carry on. So I - started to walk. I almost got - halfway between {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Kingston
{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose} when I see a chap messing about with a car. So - it was a Rover, a red car. So I said to him - I see he was in a bit of a bother,
 kept scratching his head and that - you know, wondering what to do next so I says, excuse me sir, can I help you? He said, know anything about motors son? So I said, well not a lot, I said, but I could hold a spanner for you or anything like that if you 
wanted to use two spanners and only got one hand. So he said - well, yes, stand me, he said, I might need some help. So I did, I helped him, and he got it going, the motor. He said, where are you bound for? So I said, oh I want to get to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Oh, he said, a long way away. I said, yes sir. He said, well I'm going as far as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford
{\*\xmlclose}. He said, if you'd like to - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 jump}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 in, he said, I'll take you to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}. I said, thank you. I gets to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}, left the gentleman, and - I was feeling hungry, thirsty, 
been out all day and nothing to eat. So - I walked up to a pub. Round about six or seven in the evening then it was. And - I thought I'll take a chance. Well being a - a good whistler, impersonating birds and things like that, I could whistle - oh what - 
a
nything, do all sorts of lovely birds what we see around about here, blackbird, chaffinch, canary, not - canaries in particular but - skylarks, that was my speciality. I - put me foot in the door, in the pub, and looked in, just put me - opened the door a
 
little way with me foot and started to whistle. Can't do it now, got no teeth. So - after I finished doing me show I went in the pub. No one in there, not a soul. The guv'nor was leaning up against the counter. I take him to be the guv'nor. He said, you -
 
you done all right there son he said. What were you whistling for? I said, a few coppers. Oh. He said, no one in here. I said, I know. He said, what do you use for doing that whistling with? I said, nothing sir, it's a - natural gift. Oh, he said. And whe
re are you going. So I said I want to get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Oh. Right. He said, would you like a drink? I said, oh yes please. Would you like a bit of bread and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 cheese}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ? I said, yes please. So he fixed me up with a lump of cheese and - bread and butter and a - 
pint of bitter. No it wasn't, it was ordinary ale. So - oh I thanked it for it very much, I said, I can't pay you for it sir, I haven't got no money and - as you know. That's all right, son, he said. You come back another time, he said, when there's some 
p
eople in the bar, he said, they'll be quite pleased to hear that. Said, well, wish I could. Anyway, I'll do me best. He said, I'll tell you what, you want to get to Portsmouth, he said, there's a - a lorry - leaves Guildford - leaves - what's the name of 
t
he place - Knightsbridge or some place like that he said, the lorry comes here every - Tuesday I think the day was, a Monday, it was on a Monday, the lorry comes - calls here every Monday, he said Fills his - radiator - radiator up - with water, he said, 
and - he's loaded with biscuit tins. He said, you can't mistake him, you'll hear him coming miles away, he says, tins are rattling. So I said, very good sir. He said, you ask him if he'll give you a lift to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He don't go in to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he said,
 he goes to Cosham. I said, very good sir. He said, you wait outside, you'll hear him coming along. Well the pub closed, it was gone ten o'clock. So I waited and waited and anyway eventually I could hear a rumbling noise coming from the distance and this 
l
orry drove up. He pulls in the pub, takes his - petrol can and fills it up with water, puts it in his radiator. While he's doing that, I'm thinking to myself, if I ask him for a lift and he refuses me - what have I got to do then. I shall be stranded and 
c
old night and I said there'll be nowhere to sleep. I'd better not ask him. I'll jump on the back. So while he was away getting his water - I - shifted the cans about bit. Tin cans you know, tin - boxes like I've got in there, and - made meself comfortable
.
 So - he started off. Well going along some country lane, I don't know what lane it was - and all of a sudden, wallop, he goes in the ditch. And he tips the - van over. And - shoots me out onto the grass - in the grass ditch, dry ditch thank the Lord, and
 
it was a - all these tin cans, tin boxes come - dashing after me and buried me almost in - the sudden jerking you know shot the tins out the back. All he had was a tarpaulin sheet - at the back, he didn't have no folding doors or anything like that, just 
a
