\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. That's the cause of it, being out of work so long, going out each morning looking for work, couldn't find any. Thought, I've got to do something. I've got to go somewhere and find a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Mrs Hill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You tell me when you were born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh. 8th of October, 1876. Had when I was five. And I've been at West Ham ever since. Now I'm ninety-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What was your father, was he a West Ham man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. He was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Suffolk
{\*\xmlclose}, no, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Norfolk{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And my mother was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Suffolk{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And - he got a job - doing houses up, house decorator and - I don't know when they moved to Cambell - Camberwell but anyway - I was born at Camberwell, but whereabouts - I don't know. May have been under the arches somewhere for all I
 know, and - and I come to West Ham - when I was five. And my father got a job house decorating for a gentleman at Buckfast Hill. And he had so many houses to look after, and - we moved from Camberwell to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Tidal{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Basin{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and that's where we lived for two years. And then they come to Custom House. Then we come to Old Canning Town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So he was a painter was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Used to do houses up. House decorator.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Has it changed a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. Oh a lot, it has.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In what sort of ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Well - 
in one way - there was more work then than there is now. 'Course the wages wasn't so high. But - still it was a living I expect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A lot more poor people around at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. I used to go to St Lukes school - Tidal Basin. Used to pay three
pence a week there - to go to school. Well then - then we moved to 40, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Acre Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. That's where I lost my mother. I was sixteen and a half. Well I would have been seventeen in the October as she died the 17th of July before, she died with con - died in a co
nfinement. She left seven of us. Of course I - I was mother. Unfortunately me father went anywhere he liked, stop out - all the week and leave us all. Yes. I wouldn't like them times over again. No, I wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where was he going your father, you mean out to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, going out on the spree. What he had - had he used to keep to spend. Never used to come home here. I went to work for a woman in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Barley Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. She used to take seafaring men lodgers. And she had a big house and I used to go there and 
work, and when - when they'd finished their meals I used to put all what was left, what they left and what was in the dishes and that, put 'em into a big pan and bring them home and feed me sisters and brothers. I used to get three shillings a week.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were you helping to clean there or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Cook - help - help - like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 cooked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  the dinners and - helped and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 In the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 It was quite a big place was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. And all the food what was over I used to have for the children. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 It must have been very difficult to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh it was. It was. There was no money coming in. And then - 'course there was no rent - rent paid and we had to get out. That was Adam - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Adamson Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, Custom House. We had to get out of - no, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hooker Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. We had to get out of there, 'cos we couldn't pay the rent. Then the children, they all went into the workhouse. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your brothers and sisters you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. They all went in the workhouse. Leytonstone. And - I got
 a - a - I got a job - in - Old Canning Town, in Bidder Street, used to get two shillings a week there. And - like a servant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of a family were you working for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh they was - only a man and wife, but they were very good. And they -
 they used to let - let me come away Sundays, and I used to go - used to go and see father then. Well - I never used to go every Sunday. I'd go and see father one Sunday and go and see the children next Sunday, take 'em some bits and pieces. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What was the man's job in that house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well it was in - it was in - own job, he - used to mix up paints and all that and sell 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 A sort of shop, oil man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, no it was a - house but there was a great big yard at the side of it. And he had about six men working for him. Name of Old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You lived in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes. Lived there. Used to get two shillings a week there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
You lived there later didn't you, when you were married was it there that you had the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh my husband 
did. He - he was working in a pub. Working in a pub called the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wellington{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, down - Old Canning - Town. And he used to get - eighteen shillings a week then, the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 postman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  and barman. Well - father - I got my father a - a - couple of rooms in Bidder - Street,
 well then - he was all right a little while. I was single then, and - but the - kids weren't. And then - he come home and - the children and that, but - he - he wouldn't let me go out - anywhere, my - my young man what was at the - used to work at the We
l
lington - he come for - used to come for me, but I couldn't go out, if I did I'd get a good whacking. And - well then father was bad. And they took him into - well what was no - Whipps Cross then, took him into the infirmary, at Leytonstone. And the four 
c
hildren I had - I - I was married then and I was expecting my - eldest boy, which is seventy-four now, and - when - father was bad, they took him away, and I had to have the four children. They could either have gone back into the New Inn, which was the w
o
rkhouse, but I said no. I'll manage with 'em, I'll go to the assistance. But the assistance them days - we used to get a grocery ticket, and two big black - black loaves. Well - I - I had the four children. And I only had the one front room - about half a
s big as this, and I used to put the pal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
ses what was then, no overlays, on the floor, and the four children used to lay there of a night and me and my husband, we was in our bed. That - that was how I looked after them. And I used to pay half a crown a 
week - out of my - eighteen shillings a week - what my husband used to earn, I used to pay half a crown a week - towards the rent, for the two rooms, up in the baker's shop.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was your husband still a barman then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Then he was, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did he manage the pub at one time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No. Oh no, no. Well he used to do - used to do the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 cellar work}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 . What they called potman barman, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did you find the people at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Union{\*\xmlclose}, what were the officials like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh they were very nice. Oh yes.
 Yes. Oh yes, and the children liked it very well. 'Course they was only young. And - when I lost my mother be - of course the baby, and the next one - my - she was two and a half and Tom, he was four. And - and that - and then - Tom was four, Louis was s
even. Alf - he was nine. And Louis - no, Louis was seven. There was - Emmy tow and a half. Tom four. Em - Louis, seven. Alf nine. Bella, she was eleven. But of course the baby, we had the baby, that was only eight hours old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How many years did you look after them for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh well - I got married - 1897. Well I was - I was about nineteen and a half. I got married - no, I got - I was - I was twenty in - twenty the eighth of October, and I got married on the ninth of December. Same year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And you looked after them until they were old enough to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Oh yes. Yes. Well then I lost my sister. 1917. She died and left me with four. I had one four, Rosie, Phyllis seven, Bella - that's her photo over there, was nine, and Dick was eleven. So s
he died 1917. Sugar's in the cup-board. She died 1917. Tenth of November, 1917. No thank you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So that's why you had a much bigger house was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Yes. Yes. Well - well we had - it was like a shop - a shut up shop. 14 New Road. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. That's where Jim lived with me - for about - eighteen years. And he had - eight children, or his wife did, along of me. Eight. Yes. And then my sister's husband, they were \{BLANK\}
 her husband she - he stopped out - out abroad - leaved England, and - so she packed up her bits, come and lived with me. And she used to go to work - at the whisky place, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Commercial Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Johnnie Walkers or something - some place. And I fetched her two children up, boy and girl. One was named Rick, the boy was Ric, and the girl - girl was Louis.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When was that? Was that after the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I don't know when Louis went out there. 1912. Mmm. Well I've got the letter. Yes. Oh. Yes. So that - I've had plenty of families to bring up. Plenty of children. And then I had m
y sixteen, they're all alive and kicking. And then I had another two in late life. I was forty-four when I had George and forty-seven when I had Leslie. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did you manage to get them all into the house when you had so many?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh - oh we - we
 used to manage. We had a big shop, plenty of rooms in it. Well in Jim's room we only had the one room. That's all - that's all he had when he married. And the - the stairs was - in the scullery, you open one door go down the steps, open another door, go 
u
p the stairs - into Jim's room. But he had five full size beds up in his room. 'Cos the stairs was here, and then there was a great big space there and a big space there, that you could put a full size bed. Both sides of the - staircase. You see? So he - 
t
here was eight - eight children. There. And I had another daughter, she come and lived with me 'cos she couldn't get a place. She had two children along of me. She had the front room upstairs. Our Lou. And - she had two children. Well as soon as she found
 
a place she moved. Well then there was another daughter, the youngest one, Jess. She had her first boy - when there was a raid, no, not a raid. A flood. It was the first flood ever we had. That - that was when John - that was when Rolly was born. She - sh
e lived at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Shelton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Shelton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Cand she come from Charlton all in the - water and that through the tunnel and come to me, she was confined the same night. On a Monday. 7th of January. But - I forget the year. I know the date. I know the date of all their birt
hdays. Yes. Yes. Yes, there was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When would it be that your husband started getting ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Pardon? Oh - well - he - he was never well. He - he was seven years of age before he could walk about. Mm. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 Bronchial}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  asthma. All - all through the winter he - he - used to be terrible with him. And - and we used to do about a month's work and two months out. He's gone to work }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 holding}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
 the railings to get round the corner to go to work. I lost him - hm - 1930. November the fifth. On a Wednesday morning. 1930, that's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How did you manage in the winters when he was out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well I - I used to get par - you know, get - get relief. Well then - I - started selling and - leave you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Selling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Selling. What - Christmastime now - then we - 
we'd be round the streets, with our mottoes and chains and - well }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 so would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767  our mother's, Merry Christmas and all that. And then - we used to go to market - markets, Stratford market - great big - costermonger's barrow wasn't it, and I used to get - celery 
and lettuces and all the pieces and - yes, beetroot, you could boil them in the copper. Freezing cold weather, out - out the yard, go out - our macs and hats on, scrubbing all the celery, the - icicles hanging on our arms. Oh - when he was a baby I used t
o
 go ship scrubbing. Used to get two shillings a day. Well I had three to keep. And my husband was laid up then for months and a months. And - when I come home - I used to give a lady sixpence for minding - Jim, 'cos he was a only a - baby, couple of month
s
 old, give her sixpence, a fivepenny ha'penny tin of Nestles milk, and we used to save tuppence for me fare for the next morning. Be at penny packet of tea, half pound of sugar, penn'orth of jam in the cup, loaf of bread, we used to have a good feed. Oh L
or'. I often think of that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you have any other ways of earning money besides scrubbing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. Not - not then. It was only when we come - more this way, Canning Town - no, I - I've got to think in me head - we used to have about - we used 
to have a stall - the corner of Star Lane, used to be a doctor's shop there then, and - I was queer once with a cold and - I had quinsies, well there was only Jim then to look after you see, but still - and then - when he was out of work and he had his - 
e
ightshillings, I was only talking about that the other day to Mr Smith, you know, he used to go round the dustbins - sorting out - people turn all their old - Christmas bits out what their children used to have, he'd go round, put 'em in the sacks, bring 
them home, turn old bits into new, and he used to stand at the corner where SPolidge's used to be, a little - church with steps. Tabernacle affair - and he used to sell 'em, he used to make board and s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 s and all that, oh yes, you know, we've - there is on
ly me and him but - will you - we used to do it. But the others, they - of course they never had no rough times like us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What were the Parish Relief people like then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh well of course you didn't get the dues then that you get now. But - and used to get a grocery ticket. They used to take 'em up to old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Rochester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and - he was very good, he'd give me a little bit over the mark and that. Might be fifteen shilling grocery ticket, might be ten or twelve and a couple of loaves
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But they didn't make you feel bad because you were asking for relief?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 People often say they were very hard in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well they was, because you didn't get the things then that you get now. Nothing near. But still - I said to one of our
 tenants along here, I said, well with all my - ups and downs - in my life - they was happy times. It was a struggle - you went to bed - hungry and - and you get up hungry and you keep hungry, and you wouldn't know where you was going to get - not without
 
because - until we started saving, then it wasn't so bad then. And then - Jim's - at Howards I think then, I can't remember that, but I used to push a - a little - little barrow, from Canning Town to Stratford Market, and I used to get a - half a bushel b
asket of apples, and I used to make toffee apples, and have 'em outside on - on a table. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 But you never tried that when you were first married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. Oh no. Oh yes, we used to do all right, I had - ha'penny and a penny each. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Ho
w did you meet your husband when you were in Bidder Street, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - well - his mother lived across the road, and to where I got the two rooms see for my father. That's when the children come out the workhouse. And - he was going to ch
ange but he never changed. Still - well - I used to go over to his mother's - and spend a hour. First of all I used to go next door to his mother's, until a young woman who I know - knew, Mrs Horton, and then I went - used to go - used to talk to his moth
e
r over the back. She was all right but the husband - her husband, he was a miserable old sinner. And of course - she used to say, well why don't you come in here Edie for a little while? You know, just to the pass the time and I'd have a cup of tea, perha
p
s I'd have me tea there. See, well then of course - my chap used to come in and - that's how we got into conversation. Well one night - that's up - that's how I left home when I did or else I wouldn't have got married. Not - not so quick, but - one night 
w
e was going to the pictures. And used to have Wednesday - Wednesday afternoon, Wednesday evening off. And I - I - me and him was going to the pictures. We was just going to turn down the Howards the woodyard when my father comes home. So he said, where do
 
you think you're going? I said, going to pictures dad. Are you? Home. He give me one swipe across the head. - across the face and said to my chap, don't you come near my door anymore for her. He says, or I'll put my toe behind you. Well then I used to hav
e
 to do me courting out the window of a night when he left. He'd whistle me and I'd look out the window and I'd say, goodnight, I'll try and see you tomorrow. What do you think of that? Terrible life. I wouldn't like any of my - and - well I - I ain't got 
no little 'uns now - but I wouldn't like it with my grandchildren, but still they've got easy life now. Very easy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So you decided to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes, well when - when I - I got married, well I hadn't got what - I - got half what I've got now. H
is mother let me - let us have the bed that he used to sleep on and that. And the bedclothes and all that and the - table, couple of chairs, well it was his bedroom, mostly. Still we - crept and crawled on. We was happy although - hard times but we was ha
ppy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you get married in the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, Silvertown church. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
When you were bringing up your children did you believe in smacking them and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no. Oh no. I - I used to threaten 'em and - I used to make 'em go to be
d. Oh no. No, I - I - I don't believe in hit - in hitting 'em 'cos you make 'em worse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was your own mother like that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, she was a dear old soul. Mother - who me? No ma. Oh she was a very nice woman. If my father'd been as nice, things would have been smoother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He used to come home drunk then did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. Terrible. She'd have black eye after black eye. Yes. Yes. Yes she had. I know one Christmas time, we went out, see we were awake, we could hear her - hear 'em round the next
 turn. And when we got indoors he would pay her, she had two shocking black eyes. Beast. He was - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He didn't often touch you though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh - oh - oh I have had a hiding and - well - when I was at home and we had the - had the two rooms - we a
ll used to sleep in - in the front room, and he used to sleep in the kitchenette - in the kitchen, on a chair bed. Many a time he's smacked his tea at me. Oh yes. He was no angel. I don't know what he is now. My father. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Your husband's parents were rather different were they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. Yes. Well the old chap wasn't very - pleasant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What was wrong with him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well - when I had my - eldest boy, 'course I was living there - and - if he used to cry, he'd gang on the stairs, he'd say -
 keep that kid quiet else I'll come and - chuck him out the window. I'd say, you miserable old devil, shut up. I - can't help it if he's got tummy ache. Feed him. And he used to all like that. No, well when my husband come home I used to tell him, he'd go
 downstairs then - carry on to his father. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were the neighbours more helpful in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of things would they do for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh well - I was young you see and they used to come in and help - and that, 'cos I 
had the baby you see delivered - until it was six months old, and then my father took it - he took it to - Hounds Road, well - Hounds Road, yes, the nursing home, and he used to pay - half a crown a week to have the baby mind. Well I had it when it was yo
u
nger, when the - until it was six months old, and then he - said - it was too much, there was the six of - six of us, and the baby, and father - he said, we'll put the baby in the home. Well it went. And he used to pay - half a crown a week for that. Well
 
then one day he come home and he said, there was - there was a retired matron, would like to take baby. So I said, oh no, don't part with her now. He said, well she'd be well looked after, she's going to a good home. So - so he took it. And from the time 
that baby left our place at six months - I've never seen it. Where it is or what - where - of course - years ago ain't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That was your own baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No - that was me sister, that's the baby, that my mum died. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And you were living with your parents in-law at that time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, well - I was only sixteen meself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 This is before you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 So your brothers and sisters went into the workhouse after your mother died?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh - oh a long while after, a long while after my mother died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You looked after them at first then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Yes. I looked after 'em - my Emmy, she'd left school - no she hadn't, she used to go to a shop round the corner, Custom House, and she used to do a bit of cleaning or errands 
or whatever it was - well she was fourteen then, and nearer - near on fourteen. Well when my mother died - there was - I was the eldest, and I had 'em all to look after. The baby eight hours old. I had to 'em wash for, clean for, cook for, and everything.
 Oh yes, well do it - do it all. Well - owing to my father how he went - anywhere - and he used to get the drink and all that, we come to Custom House then. I lost my mother {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
40 Acre Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then we come to Custom House. We had the upstairs flat along of a
 woman named Quaker, she lived downstairs. Well that's when my father was bad. And they took him into Leytonstone and they took the children into the workhouse. Well then I went out - to try and find a job. Down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Victoria Dock Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} what was, there was a cof
fee shop just before you got to the top. And - in the window - there was a - card. Respectable girl wanted, enquire within. Well when I went in and enquired, it was for this - this - house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bidder Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, what used to make all the paints. Two big lions h
e used to be at the door, I - you know, stone ones. Well that's where I went. Well my father, he was in - he was in Leytonstone. The children's in the work house and I went there to work. So I used to get three shillings a week. Well then - father was com
ing home. And I got two rooms in the bakers - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bidder Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, upstairs. And my father come home and he went there and - and then the children come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 And you left the job then did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh I had to 'cos looking after them. Well then - well - 
I was at home looking after them, cooking and washing and that for 'em. My father was at work, was able then, he got all right, he went to work, but he never used to worry about us. He used to worry about - all the women that was knocking about. Stop out 
a
ll night and all that. Well - what I used to get from over - over my - husband's mother, and what I could scrounge out of my bit - well then - well - then - I got married, through his behaviour, through my father's behaviour. I - I left him. And I went an
d
 lived with my husband's mother. Well then - it - we planned that we should get married but - we just went to church and that and he went straight back to work. Well then - well then father, he was bad again, they took him in to Leytonstone again. And - b
ut I had the children. I had four. I had Emmy, Tom and Lou and Alfie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Which house would you have been in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
I had one room. All in one room. It was - well - I never had no home when I first got married. Nothing at all hardly. And there was a f
our pal - there was the two paiases I used to stand at the foot of my bed - all - all day. Covered over with a quilt, of a night I used to put 'em on the floor, and the four children used to sleep on the floor. And if my old friend, Mrs Altington could ge
t here she would tell you the same, and the four children used to lay there. And - me and dad, we'd be in - in bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did you eat down with your husband's parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No. No. No, all us in the one room. Eat - eat and sleep. Children - children was at school, used to go to school. Used to get school - school meals and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Would they get some free clothes or anything like that from the school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes, we used to get boots and all. Used to go round the corner and we used to - we used to get 
jugs of - soup, well - pea soup stuff. No. No the convent. Convent. And - all the stale bread and that we used to - used to hot it up and that and used to feed 'em with that. Bread puddings. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was the Church of England any help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No. Yes, Catholic was. What they call the nunnery. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 When you were a girl were you sent to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh yes, when - that was when - when my mother was alive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Did she go to church herself or not
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 No. No. No. Well my mother c
ouldn't - couldn't go out, well she could go out but she was never - never allowed out, she - she couldn't go in her mothers meetings and - clubs like there is now. 'Cos my father'd strangle her. Yes. Spiteful, spiteful man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 He wouldn't ever help in the house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh no. No. Oh no. No, he - no, all as he thought of was his pint - and women. That's all. Like - like my sister's husband that died, her four children her husband, he never used to worry about them did he. Not - Dick. You know I had Ro
sy, Phyllis, and that, and Dick. Dick, was only eleven, and - and he was the eldest. The youngest was four. I fetched them all up and there was - well I fetched two of 'em up, until they was married. One went and lived with her aunt and she died. And then
 
one was at - lived at - somewhere, she's married now of course. Rosy, yes. Phyllis died. -Phyllis. And then there's Bella, and then there's Dick. Well Dick's getting up - getting on for sixty-six now, our Dick. Mr. B. Well when - when I was a little boy, 
a
 young boy, I used to go and help me father on the allotments, he said to me one day while we was over the allotment, see that caterpillar? I yes. On a cabbage. He said, pick it up, put it in this matchbox. All right dad. What have I got to do with it? He
 
said, take it - round to your Aunt Bella, that's the lady mum's talking about, her sister, and tell her to put it in her top drawer and look at it every morning 'til it becomes a baby. I did. And I always did believe my cousin Dick come from a caterpillar
. Yes, that's right isn't it luv. I often say - when I do meet him once in a blue moon, I say - yes, you're a caterpillar you are mate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where would your father meet the women then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Anywhere. In the pubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Were women allowed in the pubs then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Oh yes. Yes. But you - you - what they used to be at the - where - where my husband was - potman, they used to - used to shell their peas and - scrape the potatoes and all that, sit there, have a - half pint and - yes. Sit on the kerbs eating fish a
nd chips of a night time. No - times are altered now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Would you say that there were quite a lot of families poorer than you were at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Well I - I - I don't think there was many poorer. I don't think there was many poorer than - you know 
- and had the struggle that - that we had. I - well to be honest, this is the best time of - of my life, if I wasn't alone of course. Well if I - if I wasn't - if I had anybody with - with me I wouldn't be here. You see, because they don't let 'em to - pa
r
t - two, they don't let 'em to - man and wife. No. No. Well - I've got a son round the corner, fifty-one. Fifty-one last September. And we've never been parted. Only when he was in the army. That - that - I - that was nearly twenty years - twenty years wh
e
n I left 'em. And they had four children. And - I - I left 'em just like that. And - I knew this place was being built, and I said to the secretary I said, what about making there Molly? So she said, flats gran. I said, are they, I said, I'd like one. She
 
said, you wouldn't leave your crowd. I said, I would you know. She said, all right, I'll put your name down. But I didn't think that I'd get one, not here about a month before I got it. And I said to one of the council ladies I said, I won't get a place t
h
ere, I said, I'm too old. She said, what are you talking about? You ain't too old, she said, you can look after yourself. She said you're nice and respectable and that. You'll get one, don't you worry, you'll get one. True enough I did, the warden came ro
und and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 How many living descendants do you have now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where, here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No, altogether, alive. How many children and grand children and great-grand-children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh. Oh. Well - I've got eight children alive. I lost one. Three years and f
our months, 1917. I - I got eight alive. And I've got - thirty-five - thirty-five grandchildren. And I've got sixty - sixty-one now - sixty-one great - grandchildren. And I've got eleven great-great-grandchildren. And there's one, two, three more on the r
o
ad. So - 'cos there's two clubs here. One club's a hundred and fifty - members and one's about a hundred and thirty - thir - no - one's about a hundred. That's Thursday club a hundred and fifty, Friday club - about a hundred. And we - that - none of 'em c
a
lls me Mrs Hill. Here you are grandma, here you are gran, here you are. Oh - oh yes, I'm well - I'm well liked with 'em all. And the warden, if I make a bread pudding he'll say - bread pudding grandma? I say, yes sir. He'd say, right. And he'd say, when a
r
e you going to cook any parsnips? I - I'll say, well if you're going to bring me any I'll cook 'em, but if you don't I can't. He says, I'll get you some parsnips. Yes. Old Mrs Mitchell. And I was going to school, St Lukes school, I was only a kid, and - I
 
- I see the ambulance there, they're not ambulances like they are now. And I went back and I said, mum, there's a ambulance at Mrs Mitchell's. So mum come running out to see Mrs Mitchell, well and poor Mrs Mitchell, she had smallpox, and 'course my mother
 
goes to shake hands with her - not the next morning but the morning after - we - when we got up earlier - little 'uns, we always go in to mother, but the door was locked. So I said to my father, what's the door locked for dad? Oh, he said, your mother ain
't - ain't well. Ambulance come and took her away. Smallpox it was. Well - well - if I'd have gone - but they were so - friendly, and me seeing the conveyance there I went and called mother out, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 What sort of ambulance did they have, a wheelbarrow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
No - was like the black shut up - like the black - black maria, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Nothing like they used to carry Peggy Dooley about on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 You remember Peggy Dooley do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. I've seen him get in fights - hang on th
e church railing, take his leg off and wallop the coppers with it. Yes. Yes. Old Peggy Dooley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Was there a lot of fights in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes, oh yes. We lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and the back of us was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Stucker Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. We'd be up half the night looking out the window - at the fights. Specially them Grays. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Who were the Grays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 
Some - you know, rough 'ans, rough and tumble lot. Oh that used to be a terrible street, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Tucket Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Plenty of fights and that there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Mr. B. I never told you 
that bit did I? There used to be a - pub on the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Tucker Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 called - the Nelson. And - all the - navies and - workers used to get in there of a - Saturday nights speciality, and they'd start singing. Well they'd keep singing 'til it was time to
 close, then they'd come outside and sing, maybe about a dozen or perhaps twenty or thirty of 'em all singing. And then the women upstairs in their rooms couldn't get to sleep, they'd church anything at 'em, get out of it, go on. And of course - one man'd
 say, that's my missus you're swearing at, hold that one. And then there'd be a free fight amongst all of 'em. Didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12875567\charrsid9644767 there mum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 ? Screams and cries, the women used to come - out and scream. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Mrs H. Used to be fights there. Well years ago when - whe
n I first went down the town - police, they wouldn't come on their own. The policemen, no, used to be two or three together. Used to be shocking. Then it got quieter come the end.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Where was that they wouldn't go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Down the Old town. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Old{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Canning{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5333702 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 That's not the bit you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16011686 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12597048\charrsid9644767 Yes. Yes, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bidder Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. That - big pub on the corner. Oh yes, yes. There used to be seven pubs - down - down there. Yes. And it was only a small place wasn't it? Still, I wouldn't like my ti
mes over again. Not - hardship times. No. No, I couldn't.
